  url='http://www.seds.org/billa/top/';OpenURL(url,SHOW,TOFRONT,NEWWIN,LAUNCH);
  EXIT" } - The Nine Planets.
@endnode

/// Planets (definition)                                              //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-PL-DEF "ASense - Select: Definition of a planet"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV MAIN
@NEXTy ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
UPDATE (24-Aug-2006): The IAU has (again) redefined the term @{i}planet@{ui}.

    '@{b}Planet is a @{i}ROUND@{ui} object@{ub} (massive enough to be shaped into spherical
  shape by its own gravity) @{b}that is not a @{i}satellite@{ui} of another objecct,
  but of the Sun@{ub} (this excludes Galilean satellites of Jupiter, Titan,
  Triton, Charon and our Moon), @{b}and is NOT a member of an asteroidal belt@{ub}
  (consisting of objects of similar size as the one being examined).'
    @{b}Objects that fail the 3rd condition are now tagged as '@{i}Dwarf planets@{ui}'
  to indicate their disputed planetary status@{ub} (disputed by the presence
  of other similarly sized objects in the vicinity of their orbit).
    Objects that fail the first condition are called the @{"minor planets" link ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS}.

    The term '@{i}round@{ui}' still remains to be defined. (Saturn is 10% oblate.)
      
    @{b}Definition@{ub} is extremely partial, as it specifically @{b}covers ONLY the
  objects within the solar system@{ub}. Term 'planet' outside of our system
  remains undefined, as far as the IAU is concerned !?!

    @{b}As a member of a Kuiper Belt, the Pluto lost its planetary status,
  and is now officially a '@{i}dwarf planet@{ui}'@{ub}. The same category includes
  @{b}Ceres@{ub}, @{b}Orcus@{ub}, @{b}Quaoar@{ub}, @{b}Varuna@{ub}, @{b}Sedna@{ub}, the newly found @{b}Eris@{ub}, '@{i}Santa@{ui}',
  '@{i}Easterbunny@{ui}', and others that the future research may discover.

  ASTROLOGICAL NOTE: As far as the astrology concerned, the term '@{i}planet@{ui}'
  signifies a body with a sufficiently large @{"orb" link "ASense-astrology.guide/ASENSE-ASPECTS-COMPUTATION"} of influence. Thus, @{b}Sun
  and the Moon are also '@{i}planets@{ui}' in the context of astrology@{ub}@{b}@{ub}. Some minor
  objects also play a significant part, like the comet @{b}Chiron@{ub} for example.
@endnode
///
/// Planets                                               //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS "ASense - Select: Planets"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-PL-DEF
@NEXTy ASENSE-PLANETS-SUN
@{b}@{u}Planets@{uu}@{ub} are probably the most selfexplicable part of all.Nevertheless,
  astronomers should know that in astrology a term '@{i}planets@{ui}' is a shortcut
  for Sun, Moon and 9 (formerly) recognised planets, although the Sun is
  a star, the Moon is our satellite and the Pluto is a KBO.Some include
  the Moon's nodes within the term '@{i}planets@{ui}' as well, but here they are
  treated separately.This manual will loosely attempt to obey the official
  astronomical @{"definition" link ASENSE-SELECT-PL-DEF} of a term '@{i}planet@{ui}' (8 planets around the Sun).
  Term '@{i}body@{ui}' will be used as a general form whenever it seems suitable.

  @{b}@{u}Descriptions of included bodies@{uu}@{ub}:
    @{u}Luminaries@{uu}:                     @{u}Large gas giants@{uu}:  @{u}Dwarf KBelt's planets@{uu}:
      A. @{"Sun" link ASENSE-PLANETS-SUN} (and its @{"evolution" link ASENSE-SUN-EVOLUTION})    5. @{"Jupiter" link ASENSE-PLANETS-JUPITER}       a. @{"Pluto / Charon" link ASENSE-PLANETS-PLUTO}
      B. @{"Moon" link ASENSE-PLANETS-MOON}                        6. @{"Saturn" link ASENSE-PLANETS-SATURN}        b. @{"Eris / Dysnomia" link ASENSE-PLANETS-ERIS}
    @{u}Terrestrial planets@{uu}:            @{u}Small gas giants@{uu}:
      1. @{"Mercury" link ASENSE-PLANETS-MERCURY}                     7. @{"Uranus" link ASENSE-PLANETS-URANUS}
      2. @{"Venus" link ASENSE-PLANETS-VENUS}                       8. @{"Neptune" link ASENSE-PLANETS-NEPTUNE}
      3. @{"Earth" link ASENSE-PLANETS-EARTH} (Home, Sweet Home!) @{u}Cometary objects@{uu}:
      4. @{"Mars" link ASENSE-PLANETS-MARS}                        I. @{"Chiron" link ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-CHIRON}

  @{i}@{b}Note@{ub}@{ui}: The emphasis in the following sections of the manual has been
  given to the @{i}astronomical@{ui} facts about the described bodies.This is
  because the astrologers (even the amateur ones) tend to already know
  what a particular planet means from the astrological point of view.

    For curious amateur astronomers, @{i}some astrological notes were also
  given separately at the ends of the articles@{ui}.Feel free to read them.

  @{i}@{b}Note 2@{ub}@{ui}: Probably the most intruiging story is the one about the Sun.
  Part of it describes the past and future evolution of the solar system.

@endnode
///
///   Sun                                                 //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-SUN "ASense - Planets: Sun"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@NEXT ASENSE-SUN-EVOLUTION
@{b}@{u}Sun@{uu}@{ub}: Our star.

    Sun has been spectrally classified as a @{b}G2V@{ub} star (a bright yellow dwarf).
  It has an age of 4.56 Gyr, and is exceptionally stable, single star.
  The Sun by itself contains 99.8% of mass of our solar system and is
  within 10% of the most massive stars in the Milky Way.(An average star
  is a much lighter red dwarf.)

    @{b}Sun has about twice the amount of iron than local stars around have@{ub}
  (1.9% metallicity).This is important, because this indicates that other
  stars around have @{i}less@{ui} chances to have planets orbiting around them,
  simply because they have less rocky material in their systems, which
  is required to form Earth-like planets in the first place.

    Sun has been called @{i}@{b}Helios@{ub}@{ui} by Greeks, @{i}@{b}Sol@{ub}@{ui} by Romans, but of course
  all languages have a name for it.In its entirety, it is made of ionised
  gas, also called @{i}plasma@{ui}.In its core temperature and pressure
  are high enough to enable the fusion of H into He.Every second, 700 Mt
  of H is being fused into 695 Mt of He.The remaining 5 Mt of mass are
  being converted into energy and this is the source of Sun's power.Small
  percent of the energy is also emitted around in a form of @{i}neutrinos@{ui}.

    The core occupies inner 30% of diameter, and about 50% of H inside has
  already been converted to He.About 40% of Sun's hydrogen will eventually
  be fused into helium.Temperature in the core is about 15.5 MK (5 MK is a
  minimum, required for fusion of H to begin), and the density is 14 times
  that of lead.Regardless the pressure, the core is still entirely gaseous.

                                  . . .

  @{b}@{u}Layers of the Sun@{uu}@{ub}:
  - @{b}core@{ub} (inner 25%), rotates as a solid body, pressure is 250 Gatm.
  - @{b}envelope@{ub} (outer 75%), differential rotation, faster on equator,
    a lot of convectional movement is present within the envelope,
    which as a result causes a very strong magnetic field
  - @{b}photosphere@{ub} - edge of the visible surface of the Sun (last layer
    hot enough to emit @{i}white@{ui} light)
  - @{b}chromosphere@{ub} - very thin layer of matter that is cooler and
    emits @{i}colored@{ui} light (most of the Sun's light is in the @{i}yellow@{ui}
    part of the visible light's spectrum)
  - @{b}corona@{ub} - rarefied gas layer, irregulary shaped, visible during
    occultations by the Moon.It extends upto 1 Gm into space, has
    a temperature of 1+ MK, and is a source of Sun's gamma radiation.
  - @{b}magnetosphere@{ub} - very complicated magnetic field of the Sun is
    the cause of sunspots.It extends well beyond Pluto's orbit.
    Origin of this field are the processes within the Sun's interior.
    Movement of gas giants with their own magnetic fields, namely
    Jupiter and Saturn, causes the variations in the magnetosphere.
    These variations are the origin of the 11 years sunspots cycle.
    Luckily for us, the eccentricity of the Jupiter's orbit is almost 0,
    and thus the amplitudes of the sunspot's cycle are small, causing
    only easily bearable changes in the Earth's climate.
  - @{b}solar wind@{ub} - outward moving stream of ionized particles, resembling
    Sun's composition.Wind drags the magnetic field out, which is still
    anchored to the Sun.This slows the star's rotation over time, hence
    older stars rotate slower.The process is called '@{i}magnetic braking@{ui}'.
    The edge of a solar wind is still undetected, but the estimates are
    that it stretches some 150+ AU outward.The bubble made by the wind
    protects the solar system from the interstellar dust and gas.
  - @{b}Termination shock@{ub} - the edge of a solar wind.
      The theory says that it lies at some 101..118 AU away from the Sun.,
    @{FG shine}NEWS@{FG text}: The @{"Voyager 1" link "pics/2005-0524voyager-sm.jpg/MAIN" 0} has in December 2004 at 90 AU distance encountered
    a region unlike any other previously known.The magnetic field suddenly
    increased by the factor 2..2.5 and the wind speed slowed down.These
    findings triggered an ongoing debate of whether the ship has already
    reached the termination shock, or it still has some space to travel.
  - @{b}Heliosheath@{ub} - @{i}merged-interactions@{ui} region.This region is something
    like a @{i}@{b}flame of a fire@{ub}@{ui}.It twists and twirls swiftly and constantly.
    The interstellar influences are intermixed with the solar wind here.
  - @{b}Heliopause@{ub} - final edge of the solar wind and the beginning of the
    interstellar space.The heliopause is the edge of the solar flames.
    There is no solar wind outward.The theory says that it strectches
    some 153..158 AU away from the Sun.This changes swiftly, however.
    @{FG shine}NEWS@{FG text}: If the termination shock really lies at 90 AU away from the
    Sun, as the Voyager 1's findings suggest, then the heliopause too
    may lie some 15..20 AU closer to the Sun than expected by the theory.
    Since the current speed of Voyager 1 is only 3.6 AU/yr, we will have
    to wait some 10..15 years to find out.If its energy source endures.
  - @{b}Bow shock@{ub} - aggregation of particles in front of the Sun, created by
    the pushing movement of the solar bubble.On the opposite side of the
    Sun from the bow shock, the heliosheath is elongated in a long tail.
  - @{b}Oort Cloud@{ub} - the surrounding cloud of comets, a leftovers from the
    formation time. Trillions of small icy objects are expected to lie
    there, but their combined mass should still be relatively small.The
    orbits of these objects are very loose and are easily disturbed by
    passing stars.The cloud thus serves as the origin and reservoir of
    the long-term comets.The edge of the Oort Cloud lies ~2..3 ly away
    from the Sun.It presents the end of Sun's gravitational influence.

    @{b}Sunspots@{ub} are areas on the Sun's surface that are cooler than the
  surrounding areas by ~2000 K.They can be upto 50 Mm large, and are
  caused by interactions within the magnetosphere that are not yet
  very well understood.More spots means an increased solar activity.
    During the latter half of XVII century there was a period with
  very few sunspots on the Sun, that lasted for several decades.This
  time is known as @{b}Maunder Minimum@{ub}, or @{i}@{b}Little Ice Age@{ub}@{ui}.There was snow in
  july in Europe, and crops have failed to mature in northern areas.

  @{b}@{u}Chronology of Solar exploration@{uu}@{ub}:
   1. Pioneer 5 - USA Solar Monitor, launched on 11th Mar 1959.
      Pioneer 5 is now in a solar orbit.

   2. Pioneer 6 - USA Solar Probe - 63.4 kg, launched on 16th Dec 1965.
      Pioneer 6 is still (2004) transmitting from solar orbit.

   2. @{b}Pioneer 7@{ub} - USA Solar Probe - 63.4 kg, launched on 17th Aug 1966.
      Pioneer 7 was recently turned off.

   4. @{b}@{i}Pioneer 8@{ui}@{ub} - USA Solar Probe - 63.4 kg, launched on 13th Dec 1967.
      Pioneer 8 is still (2004) transmitting from solar orbit.

   5. Pioneer 9 - USA Solar Probe - 63.4 kg, 8th Nov 1968. - 3rd Mar 1987.
      Pioneer 9 is now in a solar orbit.

   6. @{b}Skylab@{ub} - USA SpaceStation, launched on 26 May 1973.
      Skylab was America's first space station.It was manned for 171 days by
      3 crew members during 1973 and 1974.The space station was equipped with
      the Apollo Telescope Mount (ATM), which was used to take about 150,000
      images of the sun.Skylab was abandoned in Feb 1974, and re-entered the
      Earth's atmosphere in 1979.

   7. Explorer 49 - USA Solar Probe - 328 kg, launched on 10th Jun 1973.
      Explorer 49 was placed in the lunar orbit.

   8. Helius 1 - USA/W.Germany Solar Probe - 370 kg, launched on 10th Dec 1974.
      Helius 1 is now in a solar orbit.

   9. Helius 2 - USA/W.Germany Solar Probe, launched on 16th Jan 1976.
      Helius 2 is now in a solar orbit.

  10. @{b}Solar Maximum Mission@{ub} (SMM) - USA Solar Probe, launched on 14th Feb 1980.
      SMM was designed to provide observation of solar flares during a period
      of maximum solar activity.The spacecraft suffered an on-orbit failure, so
      that a repair mission on STS-41C (space shuttle mission) was send to fix
      the problem in 1984.The astronauts successfully rendezvoused with SMM.
      SMM collected data until 24th Nov 1989, and re-entered the Earth's
      atmosphere on 2nd Dec 1989.

  11. @{b}Ulysses@{ub} - USA/ESA Solar Flyby - 370 kg, launched on 6th Oct 1990.
      Ulysses used Jupiter as a gravity assist to swing it out of the ecliptic
      plane and onward to the poles of the Sun.The encounter with Jupiter was
      on 8th Feb 1992.The first solar polar passage was in Jun 1994.Ulysses
      passed the solar equator in Feb 1995 and passed over the north solar pole
      in Jun 1995.It also studied the interstellar space out of the ecliptic.

  12. @{b}Yohkoh@{ub} - Japan/USA/England Solar Probe, launched on 31st Aug 1991.
      Yohkoh studied high energy radiation from solar flares.

  13. @{b}@{i}SOHO@{ui}@{ub} - ESA Solar Probe, launched on 12th Dec 1995.
      Solar Heliospheric Observatory (SOHO) was designed to study the Sun's
      internal structure by observing velocity oscillations of the solar wind
      and radiance variations of the Sun, and to investigate the physical
      processess that form and heat the Sun's corona and that give rise to
      the solar wind.It was put into a 'halo orbit' around the L1 Lagrange
      Point (a point 1.5 Gm away from Earth, at which the gravitational pull
      of the Earth balances that of the Sun).

  14. @{b}Genesis@{ub} - USA Solar Wind Sample Return, launched on 30th Jul 2001.
      Genesis's primary mission was to collect samples of the solar wind
      particles and to return them to Earth for detailed analysis.The ship
      crushed on the ground upon returning, but the robustness of its
      construction saved most of the samples from destruction.About 75%
      of the samples were recovered from the wreckage intact or usable.

  @{b}@{u}Properties of the Sun@{uu}@{ub}:
               age: 4.56 Gyr
              mass: 1.989e30 kg (332,943 Earth's, 1047 Jupiter's)
            radius: 696 Mm (109.1 Earth's, 9.683 Jupiter's)
           density: 1.41 g/cm^3 (0.256 Earth's) (150 g/cm^3 in the center)
                 T: 5777 K (15.6 MK in centre, 3800 K on sunspots)
          distance: 147 - 152 Gm
           gravity: 277.6 m/s^2 (on equator)
   escape velocity: 618.02 km/s
         magnitude: -26.72 V (~7% of light is in UV)
    abs. magnitude:   4.85 V
               B-V: +0.675
               U-B: +0.151
               V-R: +0.378
               R-I: +0.349
 init. composition: 70.7% H, 27.4% He, 1.9% of everything else (by mass)
                    (0.00915% O, 0.00165% C, 0.001% Fe ,...)
   by nr. of atoms: 90.1%H, 9.7% He, 0.08% O, 0.019% C, 0.00253% Fe, ...
      power output: 384,426,058 EW
        rot. speed: ~2 km/s (surface has differential rotation:
                             25.4 d on equator, 36+ d on poles,
                             core rotates as a solid body)

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically: Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: Day, life, power, force, strength, father.
    Sun has been assigned the rulership over the zodiacal sign of @{b}Leo@{ub}.
@endnode
///
///   Moon                                                //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-MOON "ASense - Planets: Moon"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-SUN
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-MERCURY
@{b}@{u}Moon@{uu}@{ub}: Our satellite.

    Moon is a barren rocky planetoid, quite a large one, when compared
  with its primary planet which it orbits around (the Earth).Together with
  the Moon, @{i}the Earth is almost a double planet@{ui}.Pluto is the only other
  planet within the solar system that possesses such an attribute.

    @{b}Moon is responsible for the existance of @{i}tides@{ui} on our planet, and is
  also tightly related to many biological cycles.@{i}Menstrual cycle@{ui} of females
  is just one example@{ub}.Not only the water is being pulled, but also the crust
  (about 0.5 m up and down), but we don't feel that.

    The peek of the tidal bulge is not exactly under the Moon, but slightly
  ahead.This is because tha Earth's rotation caries it in that direction, and
  a dragging resistance produces a torque on the Earth.Tbis slows down the
  Earth by 1.5 mas/century.(900 Myr ago, a day on Earth lasted only 18 h.)
    Since the angular momentum cannot be lost, the Moon accelerates it's own
  angular momentum and moves away from us at the speed of 3.8 cm/yr.Currently,
  only the Moon has synchronised its orbital and rotational periods, but the
  Earth would eventually do the same thing.Pluto is the only planet that has
  already done so with it's companion Charon, and they both keep the same
  face toward one another.

    Very small @{b}librations@{ub} (max 0.04°) are caused by the combined influence
  of Sun's gravity and the eccentricity of Earrh's orbit.They perturb the
  Moon with cyclical application of torque in both E-W and N-S directions.

    @{b}Far side of the Moon holds the largest crater in the solar system@{ub}:
  @{i}@{b}Pole-Aitken@{ub}@{ui}, 2250 km wide and 12 km deep.The Moon itself originates from a
  collision: @{i}@{b}billions of years ago, an object as big as Mars collided with
  Earth, and the force of that mate created the Moon@{ub}@{ui}.Because it has been made
  from a piece of Earth's mantle, the Moon is not as dense as Earth, and the
  Earth is hence denser (some of the lighter material has been thorn away to
  form the Moon).In fact, @{b}Earth is thus the densest body in the solar system@{ub}.

    Unlike Earth, the Moon is no longer geologically active, and its rocks
  are very old (3..4.6 Gyr).Four seismic station were installed on the Moon
  during the Apollo program.They detected no intrinsic tectonic activity,
  except for the residual (cooling and tidal forcing) and artificial ones
  (deliberate crashing of a lunar module into the surface).The results have
  shown that the Moon has a 60 km thick crust on the near side, comprising
  ~10% of the satellite's volume.(The volume of the Earth's crust is only
  ~1% of the volume of the Earth.) @{b}Recently, a water ice has been found in
  the depths of lunar polar craters@{ub}.The ice probably has a cometary origin.

    @{b}Lunar sky is always black@{ub} because difraction of the light @{i}requires@{ui} an
  atmosphere.Gravity is one-sixth of the Earth's.

  @{b}@{u}Layers of the Moon@{uu}@{ub}:
  - @{b}core@{ub} - ~340 km in size, about 2% of the Moon's mass.
    Lunar mass center is ~2km offset toward the direction of Earth.
  - @{b}mantle@{ub} - surrounding half molten rocky material, no longer active
  - @{b}crust@{ub} - 0 km under mare Crisium, 107 km N of the Korolev crater.
    The mean thickness is about 60-70 km.
  - (@{i}no atmoshere@{ui})
  - (@{i}no magnetic field@{ui}), some remnant magnetism embedded in rocks

  @{b}@{u}Surface features@{uu}@{ub}:
  - @{b}young maria@{ub} (16%) - impact craters flooded with lava.They are
    concentrated on the near side for some unknown reason.
  - @{b}old highlands@{ub} (@{i}terrae@{ui})
  - @{b}regolith@{ub} - fine dust and debris produced by meteor impacts, 2-8 m
    thick on the maria, 15+ m on the highlands, found everywhere except
    on the steep crater walls.

  @{b}@{u}Chronology of Lunar exploration@{uu}@{ub}:
   1. Pioneer 0 - USA Lunar Orbiter - launched on 17th Aug 1958.
      First stage exploded.

   2. Pioneer 1 - USA Lunar Orbiter - launched on 11th Oct 1958.
      Failed to reach escape velocity.

   3. Pioneer 3 - USA Lunar Flyby - launched on 6th Dec 1958.
      Failed to reach escape velocity.

   4. @{b}Luna 1@{ub} - USSR Lunar Flyby - 361 kg, launched on 2nd Jan 1959.
      @{i}@{b}Luna 1 was the first lunar flyby@{ub}@{ui}.It discovered the solar wind.
      Luna 1 is now in a solar orbit.

   5. Pioneer 4 - USA Lunar Distant Flyby - 5.9 kg, launched on 3rd Mar 1959.
      Pioneer 4 is now in a solar orbit.

   6. @{b}Luna 2@{ub} - USSR Lunar Hard Lander - 387 kg, launched on 12th Sep 1959.
      Luna 2 impacted the lunar surface on 14th Sep 1959, and was the first
      ship that has done that.

   7. @{b}Luna 3@{ub} - USSR Lunar Far Side Flyby - 278.5 kg, launched on 4th Oct 1959.
      @{i}@{b}Luna 3@{ub}@{ui} reached the Moon on 7th Oct 1959 and @{i}@{b}returned the first image of
      the Moon's hidden side@{ub}@{ui}.Space probe is now in a decayed earth-moon orbit.

   8. Ranger 3 - USA Lunar Hard Lander - 327 kg, launched on 26th Jan 1962.
      Ranger 3 missed the moon and is now in a solar orbit.

   9. @{b}Ranger 4@{ub} - USA Lunar Hard Lander - 328 kg, launched on 23rd Apr 1962.
      Ranger 4 was the first US ship that impacted the Moon.

  10. Ranger 5 - USA Lunar Flyby - 340 kg, launched on 18th Oct 1962.
      Ranger 5 was to intended to be a lunar lander but became a flyby because
      of a spacecraft failure.It is now in a solar orbit.

  11. Luna 4 - USSR Lunar Probe - 1,422 kg, launched on 2nd Apr 1963.
      Luna 4 was intended to be a lunar lander but missed the Moon.
      It is now in an Earth Moon orbit.

  12. Ranger 6 - USA Lunar Hard Lander - 361.8 kg, launched on 30th Jan 1964.
      Cameras failed; lunar probe impacted the surface of the Moon.

  13. Ranger 7 - USA Lunar Hard Lander - 362 kg, launched on 28th Jul 1964.
      Rnager 7 reached the Moon on 31st Jul 1964.The ship has sent back
      pictures taken from a close range before impacting the Moon.

  14. Ranger 8 - USA Lunar Hard Lander - 366 kg, launched on 17th Feb 1965.
      Ranger 8 reached the moon on 20th Feb 1965.It sent back high-resolution
      pictures until it impacted in @{i}Mare Tranquillitatis@{ui}.

  15. Ranger 9 - USA Lunar Hard Lander - 366 kg, launched on 21st Mar 1965.
      Ranger 9 sent pictures of its impact to the moon.

  16. Luna 5 - USSR Lunar Soft Lander - 1,474 kg, launched on 9th May 1965.
      Luna 5 soft-lander failed and impacted the moon.

  17. Luna 6 - USSR Lunar Soft Lander - 1,440 kg, launched on 8th Jun 1965.
      Luna 6 missed the moon and is now in a solar orbit.

  18. Zond 3 - USSR Lunar Flyby - 959 kg, launched on 18th Jul 1965.
      Zond 3 sent pictures of the lunar far side.It is now in a solar orbit.

  19, Luna 7 - USSR Lunar Soft Lander - 1,504 kg, launched on 4th Oct 1965.
      Luna 7 failed and impacted the moon.

  20. Luna 8 - USSR Lunar Soft Lander - 1,550 kg, launched on 3rd Dec 1965.
      Luna 8 failed and impacted the moon.

  21. @{b}Luna 9@{ub} - USSR Lunar Soft Lander - 1,580 kg, launched on 31st Jan 1966.
      @{i}@{b}Luna 9 was the first ship to successfully land on the lunar surface@{ub}@{ui}.
      It returned first photographs of the lunar landscape.

  22. @{b}Luna 10@{ub} - USSR Lunar Orbiter - 1,597 kg, launched on 31st Mar 1966.
      Luna 10 is currently in a lunar orbit.

  23. @{b}Surveyor 1@{ub} - USA Lunar Soft Lander - 269 kg, launched on 30th Apr 1966.
      Surveyor 1 made the first American soft landing on the lunar surface.

  24. @{b}Lunar Orbiter 1@{ub} - USA Lunar Orbiter - 386 kg, launched on 10th Aug 1966.
      Lunar Orbiter 1 orbited the moon, photographed the far side, and then
      impacted the surface on command.

  25. Luna 11 - USSR Lunar Orbiter - 1,638 kg, launched on 24th Aug 1966.
      Luna 11 is currently in a lunar orbit.

  26. Surveyor 2 - USA Lunar Soft Lander - 292 kg, launched on 20th Sep 1966.
      Surveyor 2 failed and impacted the moon.

  27. Luna 12 - USSR Lunar Orbiter - 1,620, launched on 22nd Oct 1966.
      Luna 12 is in a lunar orbit.

  28. @{b}Lunar Orbiter 2@{ub} - USA Lunar Orbiter - 390 kg, launched on 6th Nov 1966.
      Lunar Orbiter 2 orbited the moon, photographed the far side for potential
      Apollo landing sites and then impacted on command.

  29. @{b}Luna 13@{ub} - USSR Lunar Soft Lander - 1,700 kg, launched on 21st Dec 1966.
      Luna 13 landed on the lunar surface.

  30. @{b}Lunar Orbiter 3@{ub} - USA Lunar Orbiter - 385 kg, launched on 5th Feb 1967.
      Lunar Orbiter 3 orbited the moon, photographed the far side for potential
      Apollo landing sites and then impacted on command.

  31. @{b}Surveyor 3@{ub} - USA Lunar Soft Lander - 283 kg, launched on 17th Apr 1967.
      Surveyor 3 landed on the lunar surface.

  32. @{b}Lunar Orbiter 4@{ub} - USA Lunar Orbiter - 390 kg, launched on 4th May 1967.
      Lunar Orbiter 4 orbited the moon at a polar inclination and impacted on
      command.

  33. Surveyor 4 - USA Lunar Soft Lander - 283 kg, launched on 14th Jul 1967.
      Surveyor 4 lander failed and impacted the moon.

  34. @{b}Explorer 35@{ub} - USA Lunar Orbiter - 104 kg, launched on 19th Jul 1967.
      Explorer 35 acquired field and particle data.
      It orbited the Moon until 1972.

  35. @{b}Lunar Orbiter 5@{ub} - USA Lunar Orbiter - 389 kg, launched on 1st Aug 1967.
      Lunar Orbiter 5 orbited the moon at a polar inclination, took high
      resolution pictures of many important sites, and impacted on command.

  36. @{b}Surveyor 5@{ub} - USA Lunar Soft Lander - 279 kg, launched on 8th Sept 1967.
      Surveyor 6 landed on the lunar surface.

  37. @{b}Surveyor 6@{ub} - USA Lunar Soft Lander - 280 kg, launched on 7th Nov 1967.
      Surveyor 6 landed on and took off from the lunar surface.

  38. @{b}Surveyor 7@{ub} - USA Lunar Soft Lander - 1,036 kg, launched on 7th Jan 1968.
      Surveyor 7 landed on the lunar surface.

  39. Luna 14 - USSR Lunar Orbiter - 1,700 kg, launched on 7th Apr 1968.
      Luna 14 is in a lunar-solar orbit.

  40. @{b}Zond 5@{ub} - USSR Lunar Flyby - 5,375 kg, launched on 14th Sep 1968.
      Zond 5 flied around the Moon and returned to Earth.

  41. @{b}Zond 6@{ub} - USSR Flyby - 5,375, launched on 10th Nov 1968.
      Zond 6 flied around the Moon and returned to Earth.

  42. @{FG shine}Apollo 8@{FG text} - USA Lunar Manned Orbiter - 28,883 kg, 21-27 Dec 1968.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}Frank Borman, James A. Lovell, Jr., William Anders@{ui}.
      Apollo 8 was the first manned lunar fly-around and Earth return.
      The astronauts made 10 orbits around the Moon on Christmas Eve.

  43. @{FG shine}Apollo 10@{FG text} - USA Lunar Manned Orbiter - 42,530 kg, 18-26 May 1969.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}Thomas Stafford, Eugene A. Cernan, John W. Young@{ui}.
      Apollo 10 was a manned lunar fly-around and Earth return.Stafford and
      Cernan tested the @{i}Lunar Module@{ui}, separating it from the @{i}Command and
      Service Module@{ui} and descended to within 50,000 feet of the lunar surface.
      The astronauts acquired a large number of excellent 70-mm photographs.

  44. Luna 15 - USSR Lunar Lander - 2,718 kg, launched on 13th Jul 1969.
      Luna 15 was unsuccessful sample return attempt.Crashed during landing.

  45. @{b}@{u}@{FG shine}Apollo 11@{FG text}@{uu}@{ub} - USA Lunar Manned Lander - 43,811 kg, 16-24 Jul 1969.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}Neil A. Armstrong, Edwin E. Aldrin, Jr., Michael Collins@{ui}.
      Apollo 11 was the first manned lunar landing, which took place on
      20th Jul 1969.The landing site was @{i}Mare Tranquillitatis@{ui} at 0°67' N
      latitude and 23°49' E longitude.@{b}Armstrong and Aldrin collected
      21.7 kg of soil and rock samples@{ub} and deployed experiments.

  46. @{b}Zond 7@{ub} - USSR Lunar Flyby - 5,979 kg, launched on 8th Aug 1969.
      Zond 7 flied around the Moon and returned to Earth.

  47. @{b}@{u}@{FG shine}Apollo 12@{FG text}@{uu}@{ub} - USA Lunar Manned Lander - 43,848 kg, 14-24 Nov 1969.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}Charles Conrad Jr., Alan L. Bean, Richard F. Gordon, Jr@{ui}.
      Apollo 12 was a manned lunar landing which took place on 19th Nov 1969.
      The landing site was @{i}Oceanus Procellarum@{ui} at 3°12' S latitude and 23°23' W
      longitude.This was the prior landing site for Surveyor 3.
      @{b}Conrad and Bean retrieved portions of Surveyor 3, including the camera@{ub}.
      @{b}Samples amounting to 34.4 kg were returned from the moon@{ub}.Astronauts also
      deployed the @{b}Apollo lunar surface experiment package@{ub} (ALSEP), an automated
      research station which was also deployed by all subsequent lunar crews.

  48. @{FG shine}Apollo 13@{FG text} - USA Lunar Flyby - 43,924 kg, 11-17 April 1970.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}James A. Lovell, Jr., Fred W. Haise, Jr., John L. Swigert, Jr@{ui}.
      The Apollo 13 mission became one of survival for the astronauts on
      board.During the translunar coast an explosion destroyed both power
      and propulsion systems of the Command Service Module.The Lunar Module
      was used as a lifeboat for the astronauts.

  49. @{b}@{u}Luna 16@{uu}@{ub} - USSR Lunar Lander - 5,600 kg, launched on 12th Sep 1970.
      Luna 16 landed on 29th Sep 1970 at Mare Fecunditaits at latitude 0°41' S
      and longitude 56°18' E.@{b}A return vehicle brought 100 grams of lunar
      samples to Earth@{ub}.

  50. @{b}Zond 8@{ub} - USSR Lunar Flyby, launched on 20th Oct 1970.
      Zond 8 flied around the Moon and returned to Earth.

  51. @{b}Luna 17@{ub} - USSR Lunar Lander and Rover - 5,600 kg, launched on 10th Nov 1970
      @{i}@{b}Luna 17 has made a lunar landing with an automated Lunokhod 1 rover@{ub}@{ui}.

  52. @{b}@{u}@{FG shine}Apollo 14@{FG text}@{uu}@{ub} - USA Lunar Manned Lander - 44,456 kg, 31st Jan - 8th Feb 1971.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}Alan B. Shepard, Jr., Edgar D. Mitchell, Stuart A. Roosa@{ui}.
      @{b}Shepard and Mitchell@{ub} landed on the moon on February 5, 1971, in the
      @{i}Fra Mauro highlands@{ui}, at 3°40' S latitude and 17°28' E longitude.They
      @{b}collected 42.9 kg of lunar samples@{ub} and used a @{i}hand-held cart@{ui} to transport
      rocks and equipment

  53. @{b}@{u}@{FG shine}Apollo 15@{FG text}@{uu}@{ub} - USA Lunar Manned Lander - 46,723 kg, 26th Jul - 7th Aug 1971.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}David R. Scott, James B. Irwin, Alfred M. Worden@{ui}.
      @{b}Scott and Irwin@{ub} landed on the moon on 30th Jul 1971.The landing site was
      @{i}Hadley-Apennine@{ui} at 26°6' N latitude and 3°39' E longitude.They @{b}collected
      samples amounting to 76.8 kg@{ub}.A lunar @{i}@{b}Roving Vehicle@{ub}@{ui} was carried on this
      mission (and all subsequent ones) which allowed the astronauts to travel
      several kilometers from the landing site.The @{i}@{b}commander service module was
      the first to carry orbital sensors and to release a subsatellite@{ub}@{ui} into
      lunar orbit.@{i}@{b}Worden performed the first deep spacewalk@{ub}@{ui} to retrieve film
      from the service module.

  54. Luna 18 - USSR Lunar Lander - 5,600 kg, launched on 2nd Sep 1971.
      Luna 18 was unsuccessful sample return attempt.Crashed during landing.

  55. Luna 19 - USSR Lunar Orbiter - 5,600 kg, launched on 28th Sep 1971.
      Luna 19 is now in a lunar orbit.

  56. @{b}@{u}Luna 20@{uu}@{ub} - USSR Lunar Lander - 5,600 kg, launched on 14th Feb 1972.
      Luna 20 landed on the moon on 21st Feb 1971 at @{i}Apollonius highlands@{ui} at
      3°32' N latitude and 56°33' E longitude.@{b}The ship returned 30 grams of
      lunar samples to Earth@{ub}.

  57. @{b}@{u}@{FG shine}Apollo 16@{FG text}@{uu}@{ub} - USA Manned Lunar Lander - 46,733 kg, 16-27 Apr 1972.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}John W. Young, Charles M. Duke, Jr., Thomas K. Mattingly II@{ui}.
      @{b}Young and Duke@{ub} landed on the Moon on 21st Apr 1972 at the @{i}Descartes
      crater@{ui} at 9°00' N latitude and 15°31' E longitude.They deployed
      instruments, drove the lunar rover, and @{b}collected 94.7 kg of samples
      during a 71-hour surface stay@{ub}.

  58. @{b}@{u}@{FG shine}Apollo 17@{FG text}@{uu}@{ub} - USA Manned Lunar Lander - 46,743 kg, 7-19 Dec 1972.
      @{b}Crew@{ub}: @{i}Eugene A. Cernan, Harrison H. Schmitt, and Ronald B. Evans@{ui}.
      @{b}Cernan and Schmitt@{ub} landed on the Moon on 12th Dec 1972.The landing site
      was Taurus-Littrow at 20°10' N latitude and 30°46' E longitude.They
      @{b}returned 110.5 kg of rock and soil samples@{ub}.@{i}@{b}The astronauts covered
      30.5 km of terrain in the lunar rover during a 75-hour stay@{ub}@{ui}.

  59. @{b}Luna 21@{ub} - USSR Lunar Lander/Rover - 4,850 kg, launched on 8th Jan 1973.
      @{i}@{b}Luna 21 made lunar landing with an automated Lunokhod 2 rover@{ub}@{ui}.

  60. @{b}Luna 22@{ub} - USSR Lunar Orbiter - 5,600 kg, launched on 29th May 1974.
      Luna 22 successfully entered lunar orbit.

  65. Luna 23 - USSR Lunar Probe - 5,6000 kg, launched on 28th Oct 1974.
      Luna 23 crashed on the lunar surface.

  66. @{b}@{u}Luna 24@{uu}@{ub} - USSR Lunar Lander - 4,800 kg, launched on 9th Aug 1976.
      Luna 24 landen at @{i}Mare Crisium@{ui} at 12°45' N latitude and 60°12' E longitude.
      @{b}Samples amounting to 170 grams were returned from the moon@{ub}.

  67. @{b}Muses-A@{ub} - Japan Lunar Orbiters, launched on 24th Jan 1990.
      The ship consisted of two small orbiters but they failed to send back
      data from their orbit around the Moon.@{i}@{b}This was the first non USA or USSR
      probe to reach Moon@{ub}@{ui}.

  68. @{i}@{b}Galileo@{ub}@{ui} - USA/ESA Jupiter Orbiter/Atm. Probe - 2,222 kg, launched on
      18th Oct 1989.
      Galileo made two approaches to the Earth and Moon on its way to Jupiter
      for the purpose of gravity assistance.The first one was on 8th Dec 1990,
      and the second one on 8th Dec 1992.

  69. @{b}Clementine@{ub} - USA Lunar Orbiter, launched on 25th Jan 1994.
      Clementine's official name is "Deep Space Probe Science Experiment"
      (DSPSE).It was a Department of Defense program used to test new space
      technology.Clementine was a newly designed ship using lightweight
      structure and propellant systems.The ship has spent 70 days in lunar
      orbit (from 6th Feb - 5ht May 1994).
      Its 4 cameras mapped the surface of the Moon at 125-250 meters/pixel
      resolution.@{i}@{b}Clementine also used a laser to gather altimeter data which
      has made it possible to generate the first lunar topographic map@{ub}@{ui}.

  70. @{b}Lunar Prospector@{ub} - USA Lunar Orbiter - 295 kg, launched on 6th Jan 1998.
      Lunar Prospector arrived at the Moon on 11th Jan 1998.It was designed
      for a low polar orbit investigation of the Moon, including the mapping
      of surface composition and possible ice deposits, the measuring of
      magnetic and gravity fields, and the study of lunar outgassing events.
      This data could help scientists plan a potential lunar base and develop
      theories of the formation of the Moon, Earth and the Solar System.Its
      mission was scheduled to last one to three years.@{i}@{b}Lunar Prospector has
      found the water ice deposits in the deep shades of lunar polar craters@{ub}@{ui}.

  71. @{i}@{b}SMART-1@{ub}@{ui} - ESA Lunar Orbiter - 366.5 kg, launched on 27st Sep 2003.
      The SMART-1 (@{i}Small Missions for Advanced Research in Technology 1@{ui}) was
      a lunar orbiter designed to test spacecraft technologies for future
      missions such as a solar-powered ion drive.Its mission was to return
      data on the geology, morphology, topography, mineralogy, geochemistry,
      and exospheric environment of the Moon.The spacecraft will use its ion
      powered drive for 15 to 17 months to elongate its Earth orbit.It is
      planned for ship to reach the Moon in Mar 2005.After that, it will
      spend 6 months in lunar polar orbit, mapping the surface and testing
      the onboard equipment.The total cost of the spacecraft is estimated
      at 100 million euros in 2001 economy conditions.

  72. @{i}SELENE@{ui} - Japan 3 Lunar Orbiters - 1720 kg, (1st Sep 2005).
      SELENE (SELenological and ENgeneering Explorer) has the objectives to
      study the lunar environment and to develop critical technologies for
      future lunar exploration.Mission duration: at least one year.

  73. @{i}Lunar-A@{ui} - Japan Lunar Orbiter/2 Penetrators, (2005).
      Lunar-A will deliver two penetrators to the Moon's surface to study
      seismometry and thermal properties.The purpose is to learn more about
      the Moon's internal structure.The penetrators are designed to withstand
      a 10,000 G impact.

  @{b}@{u}Properties of the Moon@{uu}@{ub}:
              mass: 7.349e22 kg (0.012298 Earth's)
     equ. diameter: 3,474.8 km (0.27241 Earth's)
    orbital period: 27.32166 days (tropical month)
    synodic period: 29.53059 days (length of lunar day, synodic month)
         semi-axis: 384,400 km
       inclination: 5.1454°
      eccentricity: 0.0554
     mean velocity: 1.03 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.12 (0 = black, 1 = white)
       rot. period: 27.32166 days
              tilt: 1.5424°
       nr of rings: 0
       nr of moons: 0
           density: 3.344±.005 g/cm^3
                 T: 380 K (day), 120 K (night), (396 K max, 40 K min)
           gravity: 1.62 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 2.38 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: -12.74 V
  atm. composition: no atmosphere

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically: Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: Night, mother, weak.
    Moon has been assigned the rulership over the zodiacal sign of @{b}Cancer@{ub}.
@endnode
///

///   Mercury                                             //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-MERCURY "ASense - Planets: Mercury"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-MOON
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-VENUS
@{b}@{u}Mercury@{uu}@{ub}: The most inner planet.

    Mercury is the closest planet to the Sun, and thus it moves the fastest.
  Its @{i}@{b}maximum elongation@{ub}@{ui} from the Sun @{i}@{b}is only 28°@{ub}@{ui}, and since it isn't as
  bright as Venus, it is very difficult to observe.

    Commonly, people thought of Mercury to be 2 separate bodies and have
  called the planet @{b}Apollo@{ub} when it was @{i}the morning star@{ui}, and @{b}Hermes@{ub} when
  it was @{i}the evening star@{ui}.The Greek astronomers knew that the two names
  reffered to the same body.@{b}Heraclitus@{ub} even believed that Mercury and
  Venus orbit the Sun, and not the Earth.

    Mercury has a highly eccentric orbit.At perihelion it is only 46 Gm
  away from the Sun, while at aphelion the distance reaches 70 Gm.The
  perihelion of its orbit precesses around the Sun at a very slow rate.

    19th century astronomers made very careful observations of Mercury's
  orbit, and found tiny discrepancies that they were unable to explain
  by using Newtonian mechanics.This issue puzzled the minds of scientist
  for decades.Finally, @{b}Albert Einstein@{ub} applied his @{i}General Theory of
  Relativity@{ui} to the problem and was able to successfully solve it.The
  discrepancies vanished.This was an important proof of his theory.

    Until 1960s it was thought that the Mercury has synchronised its orbital
  and rotational periods long ago.Radar doppler observations showed in 1965
  that this is only partially true.Mercury rotates 3 times in 2 of its years,
  thus having an orbital/rotational resonance of 3:2 with itself.Hence, @{i}@{b}a
  Mercurian day lasts 176 Earth days, which is equal to 2 Mercurian years.@{ub}@{ui}

    Slow rotation of the Mercury produces some @{i}bizarre@{ui} effects when coupled
  with its high orbital eccentricity: @{b}At some part of its orbit near the
  perihelion, the speed of Mercury's orbital movement becomes faster than
  its rotation@{ub}.An observer on the surface would see the Sun moving slowly
  from east to west as the years goes by, gradually increasing in size as
  the planet approaches the perihelion.@{i}The movement of the Sun across the
  sky would become slower and slower, until it completely stops and then
  starts to move back from west to east.@{ui}At the perihelion the backward
  movement would be the fastest and the Sun's image would be the largest.
  Then, the process would reverse, and the Sun would eventually resume its
  normal forward movement.
    Between perihelion and aphelion points, the visible Sun's diameter
  would change by about 50%.The temperature of the surrounding terrain
  would also change significantly, for a few hundred degrees, depending
  on a time of year/day.In fact, @{b}Mercury has the most extreme surface
  temperature variations of all planets in the solar system.@{ub}They range
  from 90 K during night to 700 K during day.

    From outside, Mercury looks like Moon, a heavily cratered old surface
  with no atmosphere.But, Mercury is a much denser body, @{i}a second densest@{ui},
  after Earth.Without gravitational compression, Mercury would be the
  densest one.This indicates that Mercury's interior has a @{i}large Fe core@{ui}
  of some 3,600 to 3,800 km in diameter.This means that the silicate shell
  above is only 500 to 600 km thick, and that the core comprises some 42%
  of the planet's volume.At least some parts of the core should be molten,
  because Mercury exhibits a @{i}weak magnetic field@{ui}, the strength of which is
  about 1% of the Earth's.The other possibility is that the magnetic field
  is just a remnant magnetism in the rocks retained from the ancient times,
  and that the core is not molten anymore.
    Oddly, @{i}@{b}no Fe has been detected on the surface by spectroscopic studies.
  This may indicate a more complete diferentiation@{ub}@{ui}, than is the case with
  other terrestrial planets.

    Mercury has a very thin atmosphere, consisting of atoms blasted off from
  it's surface by the solar wind.These atoms quickly escape into space because
  of high temperature of their surrounding.The atmosphere thus remains thin,
  almost nonexistant.

    The surface of Mercury exhibits enormous @{i}escarpments@{ui}, some of them hundreds
  of km long and up to 3 km high.They have formed by compression of the surface
  due to the planet's cooling.It is estimated that the Mercury's surface area
  has shrunk by about 0.1%, which is a decrease of 1% of planet's diameter.
    One of the largest features on surface is @{b}Caloris Basin@{ub}, about 1,300 km
  in diameter.@{b}'@{i}Basin@{ui}' is defined in 1962 by Hartman and Kuiper as a "@{i}large
  circular depression with distinctive concetric rings and radial lineaments@{ui}"@{ub}.
  Caloris was probably created by a very large impact during the early history
  of the solar system.That impact is also responsible for the chaotic terrain
  on the other side of the planet.A projectile that collided with Mercury was
  probably larger than 100 km in diameter.The impact generated 3 km high
  mountain rings and send ejecta 600 to 800 km around the crater.
    In addition to heavily cratered terrain, Mercury also exhibits regions
  with relatively smooth @{i}plains@{ui}.They may be the result of ancient volcanic
  activity, or a deposition of ejecta from cratering impacts.
    The surface is covered with fine dust, also known as @{i}regolith@{ui}, and is no
  longer active.

    Amazingly, @{b}water ice has been detected in 1991 by radar observations@{ub}.
  The water has been preserved in protective shadows of some craters on the
  north pole of Mercury.
    The insides of craters that never get exposed to the Sun would remain
  cooler than 112 K.This temperature is sufficiently low to preserve the
  ices on, or just below the surface.The water may have been brought to the
  Mercury by cometary impacts or outgassed from the interior of the planet.

    Mercury has no known satellites.

  @{b}@{u}Chronology of Mercurian exploration@{uu}@{ub}:
  1. @{b}Mariner 10@{ub} - USA Mercury/Venus Flyby - 526 kg, launched on 3rd Nov 1973.
     The ship was operational until 24th Mar 1975.
     @{i}@{b}Mariner 10 was the first dual planet mission, and was also the first
     spacecraft that was equiped with an imaging system@{ub}@{ui}.It flew past Venus
     on 5th Feb 1974 to get gravity assistance.The ship flew past Mercury
     three times: on 29th Mar 1174, 21st Sep 1974, and 16th Mar 1975, and
     produced over 2,700 photos with 45% of the planet being covered.The
     ship measured surface temperatures ranging from 90 K to 460 K on the
     night and day sides.It also detected a weak magnetic field, but failed
     to detect an atmosphere.Mariner 10 is now in a solar orbit.

  2. @{b}MESSENGER@{ub} - USA Mercury Orbiter - 987.7 kg, launched on 3rd Avg 2004.
     MESSENGER - MErcury Surface, Space ENvironment, GEochemistry and Ranging.
     The aim of this mission is the exploration of Mercury.It is one of the
     cheap discovery missions.Prior to Mercury arrival, the ship will perform
     3 Venus flybys, and 2 Mercury flybys.The ship is planned to arrive into
     orbit on 2nd July 2009.The nominal duration of the mission is one year.

     The planet is too close to the Sun to be safely imaged by HST.

  @{b}@{u}Properties of Mercury@{uu}@{ub}:
              mass: 3.303e23 kg (.055271 Earth's)
     equ. diameter: 4.8794 Mm (.38252 Earth's)
    orbital period: 87.969 days
         semi-axis: 0.3871 AU
       inclination: 7.004°
      eccentricity: 0.2056
     mean velocity: 47.88 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.10 (0 = black, 1 = white)
       rot. period: 58.6462 days
              tilt: 0.00°
       nr of rings: 0
       nr of moons: 0
           density: 5.42 g/cm^3
                 T: 452 K (min 100 K, max 700 K)
   surface gravity: 2.78 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 4.25 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: -1.9 V
  atm. composition: 42% He, 42% K, 15% O2, 1% other
     atm. pressure: ~0 bar

  @{b}@{u}Astrology: Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: Speed, thinking, trade, travel, movement, children,
    agility, intelect, communication, link, transport, message.

    As an inner planet, Mercury has rulership over 2 signs: @{b}Gemini@{ub} and @{b}Virgo@{ub}.
  This corelates with its possible appearance as a morning or evening star.

  @{b}@{u}Mythology@{uu}@{ub}: Mercury is the Roman god of @{i}commerce, travel and thievery@{ui}
    (Greek's @{i}@{b}Hermes@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}the messenger of gods@{ui}).
@endnode
///
///   Venus                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-VENUS "ASense - Planets: Venus"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-MERCURY
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-EARTH
@{b}@{u}Venus@{uu}@{ub}: The brightest planet, a sister of the Earth.

    @{b}Venus@{ub} is the second planet from the Sun, and a 7th body by size, slightly
  smaller than the Earth.It @{b}is the brightest star-like object on the sky@{ub} and
  was hence named after the Roman's goddess of love and beauty.Among Greeks,
  it was '@{i}Aphrodite@{ui}', and among Babylonians '@{i}Ishtar@{ui}'.
    Moreover, @{b}the planet moves in the most circular orbit, with eccentricity
  of only 0.0068@{ub}.Roundness in shape and movement has always been a desireable
  quality of human females.With a few exception, the surface features on Venus
  were named after female figures.

    Since Venus orbits closer to the Sun than the Earth, @{i}@{b}its maximal elongation@{ub}@{ui}
  (angular distance from the Sun) @{i}@{b}is only 49°@{ub}@{ui}.Thus, it shows @{i}phases@{ui}, like the
  Moon does and is only observable during the early morning and late evening
  hours.Phases were discovered by Galileo, and their existance supported the
  Coppernicus's heliocentric theory.

    Commonly, people thought of Venus to be 2 separate bodies and named the
  planet @{b}Eosphorus@{ub} when it was @{i}the morning star@{ui}, and @{b}Hesperus@{ub} when it was
  @{i}the evening star@{ui}.The Greek astronomers knew that the two names reffered
  to the same body.@{b}Heraclitus@{ub} even believed that Mercury and Venus orbit
  the Sun, and not the Earth.

    Venus rotates very slowly, and it does that in @{i}retrograde@{ui} direction, just
  like Uranus and Pluto.@{i}For an observer on Venus, the Sun would rise on west,
  and set on the east@{ui}.@{i}@{b}The rotational period is very slow, and is synchronised
  with Sun and the Earth in such a way that Venus always presents the same side
  to the Earth when two planets are in their closest approach@{ub}@{ui}.It is not known
  if this is a resonance effect or merely a coincidence.
    One Venusian @{i}day@{ui} lasts 243 days, which is slightly longer than a Venusian
  @{i}year@{ui}, which is only 225 days long.

    On the @{i}outside@{ui}, Venus looks like a sister planet to Earth:
    - it has similar mass and size (95% of Earth's diameter, 80% of Earth's
      mass).
    - it has similar density and chemical composition.
    - it has a young surface, and an atmosphere.

    On the @{i}inside@{ui}, however, Venus is an @{b}acidic @{i}Furnace@{ui}@{ub}, radically different
  from Earth:
    - the atmosphere pressure at the surface is @{b}92 bar@{ub} (about the same as
      at 1 km depth in Earth's oceans
    - the atmosphere is composed mostly of carbon-dioxide (CO2), with the
      addition of several layers of many km thick @{i}clouds of sulfuric acid@{ui},
      a very nasty chemical.
    - the atmosphere produces a run-away greenhouse effect that raises the
      surface temperature by 400 K, from expected 328 K to 740 K, which is
      @{b}hot enough to melt lead and tin@{ub}.(Even 328 K would be quite hot for
      us Earthlings, but @{i}740 K is a furnace even for robots@{ui}.)

    The surface of Venus is actually hotter than Mercury's, although it is
  twice as far away from the Sun than Mercury.If we humans do not behave
  very well, and keep destroying our habitat, there is a good prospect that
  we prematurely end up like Venus.In other words, we need to minimise the
  production of carbon-dioxide, methane and other greenhouse gases if we
  wish to survive in a long term run.

    Venus probably once had large amounts of water, just like Earth, but it
  all boiled away.It is now a very dry @{i}volcanic desert@{ui}.

    @{i}Winds@{ui}, blowing at speeds of 350 km/h were detected at the cloud tops, but
  on the surface level, they were very slow, only a few km/h.

    Because of the thick atmosphere, there are no small craters on Venus.
  Smaller object burn up in the atmosphere and never reach the surface.The
  existing craters seem to come in @{i}bunches@{ui}, indicating that @{b}larger meteors
  that @{i}do@{ui} reach the surface usually break up during the fall@{ub}.

    Most of the surface consists of gently roling plains with little relief.
  There are @{i}@{b}2 large highlands@{ub}@{ui}: @{b}Ishtar Terra@{ub} in the northern hemisphere
  (about the size of Australia), and @{b}Aphrodite Terra@{ub}, along the equator
  (about the size of South America).The interior of Ishtar consists of
  a high plateau, @{i}Lakshmi Planum@{ui}, surrounded by the highest mountains of
  Venus, including the enormous @{i}Maxwell Montes@{ui}.
    Apart from the highlands, several broad @{i}depressions@{ui} exist: @{b}Atalanta
  Planitia, Guinevere Planitia@{ub}, and @{b}Lavinia Planitia@{ub}.

    The oldest terrain on Venus seems to be about 800 million years old.
  Extreme volcanism at that time wiped out the earlier surface, including
  any large craters from ancient periods of Venus's geological history.In
  fact, it appears that @{b}the Venus has been completely resurfaced 300 to
  500 Myr ago@{ub}.It is still an open debate on how and why has this occured.
    Most of the surface is covered with @{i}lava flows@{ui}.Venus is still volcanicly
  active, but only in a few hot spots, because of the thicker crust.There
  are more than 100,000 small @{i}shield volcanoes@{ui} and a few hundred large ones.
  The volcanoes are similar to those found on Hawaian islands on Earth.Flows
  from volcanoes have produced long curvy @{i}lava channels@{ui}, extending for
  hundreds of km.The longest one is 7,000 km long.
    Giant @{i}calderas@{ui}, more than 100 km in diameter were found on Venus.
  (Caldera is a large @{i}depression@{ui}, formed by the collapse of volcanic cone.)
  Terrestrial calderas are usually only several km in diameter.

    There are two terrain features that are unique to Venus.The first one
  are @{b}coronae@{ub}, "@{i}@{b}a large circular to oval features, encircled with cliffs,
  which are hundreds of km across@{ub}@{ui}".They are thought to be the expression on
  the surface of the mantle's upwelling.The second one are @{b}arachnoids@{ub}, "@{i}@{b}a
  circular to elongated features similar to coronae, but with a system of
  radiating dikes@{ub}@{ui}".They may have been produced by molten lava seeping into
  surface breaks.The result resembles an irregular spider's web, and hence
  the name.Arachnoids may be the precursors of coronae.

    The interior of Venus is probably very similar to Earth's: an Fe core
  of about 6,000 km in diameter enveloped by a molten rocky mantle.Recent
  results from the Magellan gravity data indicate that @{i}@{b}Venusian crust is
  stronger and thicker than it was previously been assumed@{ub}@{ui}.Convection in
  the mantle produces stress on the surface, but because of the crust's
  thickness, @{i}the stress is being relieved in many relatively small regions
  in a form of volcanoes, instead of being concentrated at plate boundaries
  as is the case on Earth@{ui}.

    Venus has no magnetic field, perhaps because of its slow rotation.

    @{i}@{b}Neith@{ub}@{ui}, the hypothethical moon of Venus, does not exist.All, but one of
  its sightings were proved to be just regular stars in the background.The
  remaining one could have been a short lived nova of 7th magnitude, but we
  will never know.Numerous spaceships that have visited and orbited Venus
  have found no moons.(@{i}Neith was named after a mysterious goddess of Sais,
  whose veil no mortal raised@{ui}.)

    Venus has been visited, orbited, and landed upon by a large number of
  spacecrafts, mostly Russian.Some of them, like Galileo, have used Venus
  to get the acceleration needed for their voyage to the outer parts of
  the solar system.

  @{b}@{u}Chronology of Venusian exploration@{uu}@{ub}:
   1. Venera 1 - USSR Venus Flyby - 643.5 kg, launched on 12th Feb 1961.
      Venera 1 is now in a solar orbit.

   2. Mariner 2 - USA Venus Flyby - 201 kg, launched on 27th Aug 1962.
      Mariner 2 arrived at Venus on 14th Dec 1962, and scanned its surface
      with infrared and microwave radiometers.The ship detected the surface
      temperature to be about 698 K and went off the air 3 weeks later, on
      3rd Jan 1963.It is now in a solar orbit.

   3. Zond 1 - USSR Venus Flyby - 890 kg, launched on 2nd Apr 1964.
      Communication lost en route; now in a solar orbit.

   4. Venera 2 - USSR Venus Flyby - 962 kg, launched on 12th Nov 1965.
      Communication failed just before arrival.Now in a solar orbit.

   5. Venera 3 - USSR Venus Atmosph. Probe - 958 kg, launched on 16th Nov 1965.
      Communication failed just before atmosphere entry.Crashed on Venus.

   6. @{b}Venera 4@{ub} - USSR Venus Atmosph. Probe - 1,104 kg, launched on 12th Jun 1967.
      Venera 4 arrived at Venus on 18th Oct 1967.This was @{i}@{b}the first probe to
      be placed directly into the atmosphere of Venus@{ub}@{ui} and to return atmospheric
      data.It showed that the atmosphere is 90-95% carbon-dioxide.It detected
      no nitrogen.The surface temperature reading was 773 K and pressure 75 bar.
      The ship was crushed by pressure before it reached the surface.

   7. @{b}Mariner 5@{ub} - USA - Venus Flyby - 244 kg, launched on 14th Jun 1967.
      Mariner 5 arrived at Venus on 19 Oct 1967, one day after Venera 4.It has
      studied the Venusian magnetic field and found that its atmosphere was
      composed of 85-99% carbon-dioxide.The ship is in a solar orbit now.

   8. @{b}Venera 5@{ub} - USSR Venus Atmosph. Probe - 1,128 kg, launched on 5th Jan 1969.
      Venera 5 arrived at Venus on 16th May 1969.Atmospheric data was returned,
      indicating that the atmosphere was composed of 93-97% CO2, 2-5% nitrogen,
      and less than 4% oxygen.The probe was lost at the altitude of about 26 km,
      crushed by the pressure.

   9. @{b}Venera 6@{ub} - USSR Venus Atmosph. Probe - 1,128 kg, launched on 10th Jan 1969.
      Venera 6 arrived at Venus on 17th May 1969.Atmospheric data was returned,
      indicating that the atmosphere was composed of 93-97% CO2, 2-5% nitrogen,
      and less than 4% oxygen.The probe was lost at the altitude of about 11 km,
      crushed by the pressure.

  10. @{b}Venera 7@{ub} - USSR Venus Lander - 1,180 kg, launched on 17th Aug 1970.
      Venera 7 arrived at Venus on 15th Dec 1970, and @{i}@{b}was the first successful
      landing of a spacecraft on another planet@{ub}@{ui}.It used an external cooling
      device which allowed it to send back data for 23 minutes.The surface
      temperature was 748 K, and the pressure was 90 bar.

  11. @{b}Venera 8@{ub} - USSR Venus Lander - 1,180 kg, launched on 27th Mar 1972.
      Venera 8 arrived at Venus on 22th Jul 1972.It measured wind speed
      variations on its descend through the atmosphere:100 m/s above 48 km,
      40-47 m/s at 42-48 km level, 1 m/s below 10 km.It returned data for
      50 minutes after it landed.

  12. @{b}Mariner 10@{ub} - USA Mercury/Venus Flyby - 526 kg, launched on 3rd Nov 1973.
      Mariner 10 was the first dual planet mission.It flew past Venus on
      5th Feb 1974 for a gravity assist to planet Mercury.It was also the
      first spacecraft equipped with cameras.It recorded circulation in the
      Venusian atmosphere and measured the temperature of the cloud tops to
      be 250 K.The ship is in a solar orbit now.

  13. @{b}Venera 9@{ub} - USSR Venus Orbiter/Lander - 4,936 kg, launched on 8th Jun 1975.
      Venera 9 arrived at Venus on 22nd Oct 1975, 3 days before Venera 10.Both
      orbiters photographed the clouds in the upper atmosphere.Differences in
      cloud layers were discovered at 57-70 km, 52-57 km, and 49-52 km from the
      surface.The lander landed on the surface on 22nd Nov 1975, and during a
      period of 53 minutes @{b}transmitted the first black and white pictures of
      the planet's surface@{ub}.It showed sharp-edged flat rocks and basaltic
      terrain.The probe is now in a Venus orbit.

  14. @{b}Venera 10@{ub} - USSR Venus Orbiter/Lander - 5,033 kg, launched on 14th Jun 1975.
      Venera 9 arrived at Venus on 25th Oct 1975, 3 days before Venera 9.Both
      orbiters photographed the clouds in the upper atmosphere.Differences in
      cloud layers were discovered at 57-70 km, 52-57 km, and 49-52 km from the
      surface.The lander landed on the surface on 22nd Nov 1975, and during a
      period of 65 minutes transmitted the black and white pictures of planet's
      surface.Terrain was more eroded than at Venera 9 landing site.

  15. @{b}Pioneer Venus 1@{ub} - USA Venus Orbiter - 582 kg, launched on 20th May 1978.
      Pioneer Venus 1 (a.k.a. Pioneer 12) arrived at Venus on 4th Dec 1978.It
      operated continuously until 8th Oct 1992, when the contact was lost.It
      was expected that it burned in the atmosphere 6 days later.This was the
      first ship that used radar to map the planet's surface.No magnetic field
      was known, but the lightnings in the atmosphere were observed.From 1978
      to 1988 the amount of sulfur-dioxide in the atmosphere decreased by 10%.
      The reason for that is unknown.Perhaps a large volcano erupted just prior
      to the orbiter's arrival and ejected sulfur-dioxide into the atmosphere.
      When things settled down, the amount of sulfur-dioxide slowly declined.

  16. @{b}Pioneer Venus 2@{ub} - USA Venus Atmos. Probe - 904 kg, launched on 8th Aug 1978.
      Pioneer Venus 2 (a.k.a. Pioneer 13) arrived at Venus on 9th Dec 1978.It
      carried 4 atmospheric probes, one large and 3 small ones.Four probes
      descended by parachute, while the spacecraft burned up in the atmosphere.
      At 70-90 km height, the probes encountered a fine haze layer.Below 30 km
      the atmospher was clear, and between 10-50 km there was little convection.

  17. @{b}Venera 11@{ub} - USSR Venus Flyby/Lander - 4,940 kg, launched on 5th Sep 1978.
      Venera 11 landed on Venus on 25th Dec 1978, and returned data for 95 min.
      The imaging systems failed.

  18. @{b}Venera 12@{ub} - USSR Venus Flyby/Lander - 4,940 kg, launched on 14th Sep 1978.
      Venera 12 landed on Venus on 21th Dec 1978, and returned data for 118 min.
      Electrical discharges, probably from lightning, were recorded.

  19. @{b}Venera 13@{ub} - USSR Venus Flyby/Lander - 5,000 kg, launched on 30th Oct 1981.
      Venera 13 landed on Venus on 1st Mar 1982, and @{b}returned black and white,
      and first color panoramic views of the Venusian surface@{ub}.It also conducted
      soil analysis using an x-ray fluorescence spectrometer.The sample was
      determined to be leucite basalt, a rare rock type on Earth.

  20. @{b}Venera 14@{ub} - USSR Venus Flyby/Lander - 5,000 kg, launched on 4th Nov 1981.
      Venera 14 landed on Venus on 5th Mar 1982, and returned black and white,
      and color panoramic views of the Venusian surface.It also conducted
      soil analysis using an x-ray fluorescence spectrometer.The sample was
      determined to be tholeitic basalt, similar to that found at mid-ocean
      ridges on Earth.

  21. @{b}Venera 15@{ub} - USSR Venus Orbiter - 5,000 kg, launched on 2nd Jun 1983.
      Venera 15 arrived at Venus on 10th Oct 1983.It's high-resolution imaging
      system produced images with a resolution of 1-2 km per pixel.Venera 15
      and 16 produced a map of the northern hemisphere from the pole to 30° N.
      They found several hot spots, possibly caused by volcanic activity.

  22. @{b}Venera 16@{ub} - USSR Venus Orbiter - 5,000 kg, launched on 7th Jun 1983.
      Venera 16 arrived at Venus on 14th Oct 1983.It's high-resolution imaging
      system produced images with a resolution of 1-2 km per pixel.Venera 15
      and 16 produced a map of the northern hemisphere from the pole to 30° N.
      They found several hot spots, possibly caused by volcanic activity.

  23. @{b}Vega 1@{ub} - USSR Venus/Comet Halley Flyby - 4000 kg,launched on 15th Dec 1984.
      Vega 1 flew past Venus on 11th Jun 1985 on its way to Comet Halley. It
      dropped off a Venera style lander and a balloon to investigate the middle
      cloud layer.The balloon floated in the atmosphere for about 48 hours at an
      altitude of 54 km.Downward gusts of 1 m/s were encountered and wind speed
      of up to 240 km/h were measured.The lander's soil experiment failed.
      The ship reached Comet Halley on 6th Mar 1986, and is now in a solar orbit.

  24. @{b}Vega 2@{ub} - USSR Venus/Comet Halley Probe - 4000 kg,launched on 21st Dec 1984.
      Vega 2 flew past Venus on 15th Jun 1985 on its way to Comet Halley. It
      dropped off a Venera style lander and a balloon to investigate the middle
      cloud layer.The lander's soil experiment sampled anorthosite-troctolite,
      which is found in lunar highlands, but is a rare rock type on Earth.The
      balloon floated in the atmosphere for about 48 h at an altitude of 54 km.
      Downward gusts of 1 m/s were encountered and wind speeds of up to 240 km/h
      were measured.
      The ship reached Comet Halley on 9th Mar 1986, and is now in a solar orbit.

  25. @{i}@{b}Galileo@{ub}@{ui} - USA/ESA Jupiter Orbiter/Atmosph. Probe - 2,222 kg, launched on
      18th Oct 1989.
      Galileo has used the gravity assistance of Venus on 10th Feb 1990 in order
      to get to the Jupiter, which was its primary destination.It then flew pass
      Earth twice for further gravity sling-shot assistance on 8th Dec 1990 and
      8th Dec 1992.On its way to Jupiter it made encounters with two asteroids:
      951 Gaspra on 29th Oct 1991, and 243 Ida on 28th Aug 1993.

  26. @{b}Magellan@{ub} - USA Venus Orbiter - 3,545 kg, launched on 4th May 1989.
      Magellan arrived at Venus on 10th Aug 1990.The ship's primary mission was
      to map the surface of Venus by radar.Its radar imaging system was able to
      penetrate the thick clouds of Venusian atmosphere in order to produce
      images at 300 m/pixel resolution.The spacecraft mapped 99% of the planet's
      surface.In order not to jeopardize with the possible future missions to
      Venus, in 1994 the controllers directed the orbiter into the atmosphere
      where it burned up.

  27. @{i}Venus Express@{ui} - ESA Venus Orbiter - 1,200 kg, (Nov 2005)
      The aim of the mission is to study atmospheric and plasma environment
      of Venus.The ship is planned to arrive at Venus 153 days after launch.
      Nominal duration of mission is 2 Venusian sidereal days (486 days).

  @{b}@{u}Properties of Venus@{uu}@{ub}:
              mass: 4.869e24 kg (.81476 Earth's)
     equ. diameter: 12.1036 Mm (.94886 Earth's)
     mean diameter: 12.102 Mm
    orbital period: 224.701 days
         semi-axis: 0.7233 AU
       inclination: 3.394°
      eccentricity: 0.0068
     mean velocity: 35.02 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.65 (0 = black, 1 = white)
       rot. period: -243.0187 days
              tilt: 177.36°
       nr of rings: 0
       nr of moons: 0
           density: 5.25 g/cm^3
                 T: 755 K
   surface gravity: 8.87 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 10.36 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: -4.4 V
  atm. composition: 96% CO2, 3+% N2, traces of SO2, H20, CO, Ar, He, Ne, HCl, HF
     atm. pressure: 92 bars

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically: Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: Female, beauty, charm, circle, girl, art, music,
    cosmetics, plants, agriculture, kitchen, fashion, design, style, love.

    As an inner planet, Venus has rulership over 2 signs: @{b}Taurus@{ub} and @{b}Libra@{ub}.
  This corelates with its possible appearance as a morning or evening star.

  @{b}@{u}Mythology@{uu}@{ub}: Venus is the Roman @{i}goddess of love and beauty@{ui} (Greek's @{i}@{b}Aphrodite@{ub}@{ui}).
@endnode
///
///   Earth                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-EARTH "ASense - Planets: Earth"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-VENUS
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-MARS
@{b}@{u}Earth@{uu}@{ub}: Our planet.
    In every language there is a name for Earth.The Greek one is '@{i}Gaea@{ui}',
  the Mother Earth; and the Roman '@{i}Tellus@{ui}', the fertile soil.
    Earth was 'discovered' (as a planet) in the XVI century by @{b}Copernicus@{ub}.
  In fact, @{b}Aristarchos of Samos@{ub} (280 BC) has been the first to propose the
  heliocentric idea, but his views were too advanced at that time to hold on.
  Although the humans live on Earth, it was not until the XX century, and
  the beginning of space exploration, that we had had the maps of entire
  planet.Pictures made from space finally put some color on the remaining
  white (uncharted) parts of the global map.

    @{b}The Earth is the densest planet in the solar system@{ub}.

    Unlike other terrestrial planets, the Earth still has a significant
  amount of @{i}plate tectonics@{ui} going on.The crust is divided into several
  separate plates (8 major plates and about 20 small ones), which float
  around on top of the molten lava below.Earthquakes are much more common
  at the plate boundaries.

  @{b}@{u}Major plates@{uu}@{ub}:
  1. @{i}North American@{ui} (N America, NW Atlantic, Greenland)
  2. @{i}South American@{ui} (S America, SW Atlantic)
  3. @{i}Antarctic@{ui} (Antarctica, S Ocean)
  4. @{i}Eurasian@{ui} (NE Atlantic, Europa, Asia without India)
  5. @{i}African@{ui} (SE Atlantic, Africa, W Indian Ocean)
  6. @{i}Indian-Australian@{ui} (India, Australia, New Zealand, most of Indian Ocean)
  7. @{i}Nazca@{ui} (SE Pacific)
  8. @{i}Pacific@{ui} (most of the Pacific Ocean, S coast of California)

  @{b}Small plates@{ub}: @{i}Arabian@{ui}, @{i}Cocos@{ui}, @{i}Philippine@{ui},...

  @{u}Four major processes occur at the plate boundaries@{uu}:
  1. @{b}Spreading@{ub} (plates move away from each other and the upwelling magma
    creates a new crust in the resulting gap (central Atlantic))
  2. @{b}Subduction@{ub} (one of the plates dives beneath the other, melts in the
    mantle and gets recycled (west coast of S America))
  3. @{b}Transverse motion@{ub} on plate boundaries (St. Andreas Fault in California)
  4. @{b}Collisions between continental plates@{ub} (continents smash one onto other,
    creating a bulge of corrugated terrain (India/Euroasia => Himalaya mt.))

    @{i}Tidaö interactions with the Moon@{ui} are keeping the plate tectonics more
  active, and @{i}are@{ui} also @{i}slowing down the Earth's rotation by 2 ms/century@{ui}.
  900 Myr ago there were 481 18-hour days in a a year.

    @{i}@{b}Erosion and tectonism are able to destroy and recreate the surface of
  the Earth in a relatively short period of 500 Myr@{ub}@{ui}.Thus, the older relief
  (like ancient impact craters) has been erased long time ago.Although the
  Earth is 4.56 Gyr old, the oldest known rocks are only 4 Gyr old and rocks
  older than 3 Gyr are rare.@{i}@{b}The oldest known fossils of living organisms are
  less than 3.9 Gyr old@{ub}@{ui}.Records from the inception of life were obliterated.
  When life was scarce and fragile, occuring only in a few remote niches of
  pristine Earth, there were much less chances that it would get fossilized,
  and that the stones containing fossils would survive intact until today,
  ending up near the surface where scientists can dig them up for studying.
  Someone properly educated has had to be on the right place to find the
  fossil, recognise it, and preserve it for further analysis.If records of
  these old fragments of history even exist, so far they haven't been found.

    @{i}4.56 Gyr ago, the Sun has emitted 32% less energy than today@{ui}.In order
  for the Earth to be warm enough to contain liquid water upon its surface,
  the ancient Earth's atmosphere needed to contain a much larger percent of
  greenhouse gases (CO2, CH4).Since then, almost all of carbon from those
  gases has been incorporated into carbonate rocks and, to a lesser extent,
  dissolved into oceans and consumed by living organisms.@{i}Continuous flow of
  CO2 into these various sinks and back is essential for preserving the
  stability of temperature ranges and life conditions on the planet@{ui}.

    @{b}Plate tectonics, plants and 71% of water cover are playing the major
  part in balancing the temperature on Earth between freezing and boiling@{ub}.
  @{i}@{b}Without CO2, the average temperature would be -18°C instead of +12°C@{ub}@{ui}.
  With more CO2 and less plants to recycle it, we can end up like Venus.
  Several times in its geological history, the Earth became a @{b}frozen iceball@{ub},
  with ice enveloping the entire planet.However, on equatorial regions the
  ice cover was shallow enough to allow the sunlight to pass through and to
  support some plant and animal life below.
    @{i}@{b}Volcanism@{ub}@{ui}, sometimes triggered by large impacts, occasionally released
  enough carbon-dioxide into atmosphere to allow the greenhouse effect to
  take more significant place and the ice above oceans melted.Long term
  cycles of orbital movement also play an important part in Earth's climate,
  as it was found by Milutin Milankovic.

    Presence of @{i}@{b}free oxygen@{ub}@{ui} in the atmosphere is quite remarkable from a
  chemical point of view.Oxygen is a very reactive gas, and under 'normal'
  circumstances there would be only a trace amount of it present.The fact
  that we have large quantities of this gas in our atmosphere is something
  that we have to thank the plants for.Without vegetation to replenish it,
  the oxygen would be quickly consumed by various geological sinks.

    Main constituent of the Earth's atmosphere is nitrogen (77%), followed
  by oxygen (21%), argon (1%), water vapor (0.3%), and carbon-dioxide (0.3%).
  There are traces of many other chemicals, like ozone (O3), and some dust.
    The atmosphere swells up during day and contracts by night.It is also
  heavilly affected by tides, although we do not normally notice that.The
  atmosphere shields us from cosmic rays and protects us from asteroidal
  debris, since most of the smaller meteors burn up in the atmosphere
  before they can reach the surface.
    A @{i}@{b}thin layer of ozone@{ub}@{ui} in the upper atmosphere shields us from intense
  Sun's ultraviolet radiation (UVA).Unfortunately, humans have managed to
  damage that layer, especially in the area around the S pole, creating
  an ozone hole.

    Earth has a @{b}moderate magnetic field@{ub}, produced by convective movements
  of conductive material in the outer core.Irregularities in these flows
  cause magnetic poles to shift around and to occasionaly reverse their
  direction relative to the surface (S pole becomes N and vice versa).
  Geomagnetic north pole is currently located in northern Canada.(The
  '@{i}geomagnetic @{b}north@{ub} pole@{ui}' is the position on the Earth's surface directly
  above the *@{b}south@{ub}* pole of the Earth's magnetic field.)
     The interaction of the solar wind with the Earth's magnetosphere
  produces beatiful auroras in polar parts of the globe.It also produces
  @{b}Van Allen radiation belts@{ub}, a pair of doughnut shaped rings of plasma
  trapped in the orbit around the Earth.The belts surround the equator.

    The Earth has only one large natural satellite, the @{"Moon" link ASENSE-PLANETS-MOON}.It also has
  numerous artificial satellites, placed in the orbit by humans.Apart from
  that, there is some dust in the L4 and L5 Lagrangian points (points 60°
  away from the Moon that allow a stable orbit).Asteroids @{b}3753 Cruithne@{ub}
  and @{b}2002 AA29@{ub} have complicated orbital relationship with the Earth.They
  are not really moons, but @{i}@{b}companions@{ub}@{ui} of the Earth.Situation is somewhat
  similar to the connection between the Saturn's moons @{i}Janus@{ui} and @{i}Epimetheus@{ui}
  (they exchange their orbits every four years by trading angular momentum).
    Lilith, the *Black* Moon, is a fiction and does not exists.
    Lilith, the *Dark* Moon, is the name for the other (empty) focal point
  of the Earth's orbit.The point lies deep below the surface of the Earth,
  somewhere in the lower mantle.

  @{b}@{u}Layers of the Earth@{uu}@{ub}:
    @{b}Layer             Depth     State      Mass   Composition@{ub}
                      [km]                 [%]
  - Inner core        5144-6378 solid       1.7   Fe, Ni                7500 K
  - Outer core        2885-5144 liquid     30.8   90% Fe, Ni; 10% S, O  -> Mag. field
  - D'' layer         2700-2885             3     Core/lower mantle mix Composition change
  - Lower mantle       670-2700 liquid     49.2   Si, Mg, O, Fe, Ca, Al
  - Transition region  400-670  plastic     7.5   Ca, Al, Si (garnet)   -> basaltic magma
  - Upper mantle        10-400  semi-fluid 10.3   Olivine, pyroxene
  - Oceanic crust        0-10   solid       0.099 Basalt
  - Continental crust    0-50   solid       0.374 Quartz, feldspar
  - Atmosphere                  gaseous           78% N2, 21% O2, 1% Ar
    - O3 layer - very thin, protects the Earth from Sun's UVA radiation
  - Magnetosphere - distorted into raindrop-like shape, the tail extending
                    for about 60 Earth's diameters outward from the Sun.
    - Inner Van Allen radiation belt (7.6-13 Mm in altitude) (mostly electrons)
    - Outer Van Allen radiation belt (19-41 Mm in altitude) (mostly protons)
      Belts have a doughnut shape, and are surrounding the equator.

    @{b}Discontinuity Depth Type of change@{ub}
                  [km]
  * Lehman        5144  Composition change
  * Gutenberg     2885  Composition change
  * 670            670  Phase, composition or viscosity change;
                        no earthquakes below
  * 400            400  Phase change
  * Mohorovicic   4-55  Sharp compositional change to crust
  * Conrad        5-30  Mafic -> felsic crust, often absent

      Convection in the outer core combines with Earth's rotation to create a
    dynamo effect that generates the Earth's magnetic field.
      Transition region, @{i}the fertile layer@{ui}, is the source of basaltic magma.
    It contains '@{i}garnet@{ui}', a complex Al-bearing silicate mineral.The mineral
    is dense when cold, and buoyant when hot.The minerals melt easily to form
    basalt, which can then rise upward as magma.
      @{i}Olivine@{ui} ((Mg, Fe)2SiO4) and @{i}pyroxene@{ui} ((Mg, Fe)SiO3) are the primary
    components of upper mantle.
      About 17 km^3/yr of new oceanic crust is being generated every year.
      @{i}Quartz@{ui} (SiO2), @{i}feldspars@{ui} ((Ca, Na, Al) silicates) and other low-density
    silicates (like @{i}clays@{ui}) are the primary constituents of Earth's crust.

  @{b}@{u}Mass distribution [Pt]@{uu}@{ub}:     @{b}@{u}Chemical composition@{uu}@{ub}:
  - atmosphere       5.1      - Fe 34.6%
  - oceans        1400        -  O 29.5%
  - crust        26000        - Si 15.2%
  - mantle     4043000        - Mg 12.7%
  - outer core 1835000        - Ni  2.4%
  - inner core   96750        -  S  1.9%

  @{b}@{u}Properties of Earth@{uu}@{ub}:
              mass: 5.976e24 kg
     equ. diameter: 6.378137 Mm
    polar diameter: 6.356752 Mm
   sidereal period: 365.256 days
   tropical period: 365.242 days
         semi-axis: 1.0 AU
       inclination: 0.0°
      eccentricity: 0.0167
     mean velocity: 29.79 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.37 (0 = black, 1 = white)
       rot. period: 23.9345h (0.99727 d)
              tilt: 23.45°
       nr of rings: 0
       nr of moons: 1
           density: 5.515 g/cm^3
                 T: 287 K (min 183 K, max 380 K)
   surface gravity: 9.78 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 11.18 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: -2.01 V
  atm. composition: 78.1% N2, 20.9% O2, 0.93% Ar, 0.03% H20, 0.03% CO2, O3,
                    traces of H2, noble gases, pollutants and dust
     atm. pressure: 1.013 bar

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically@{uu}@{ub}: no significance, unless a heliocentric/barycentric chart is
    used.In that case, it has a very positive and beneficial influence.
    Traditionally, the Earth has not been used in astrology.Transits of Earth
    may appear only in charts of astronauts that temporarily leave the planet
    at some point of their lives.It is totally insignificant (astrologically)
    for everyone else.(OK, maybe the robotic spacecrafts are also influenced.)
@endnode
///
///   Mars                                                //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-MARS "ASense - Planets: Mars"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-EARTH
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-JUPITER
@{b}@{u}Mars@{uu}@{ub}: The Red Planet.

    Mars has a distinctive red color on the sky because soil, rocks and sky
  on it are all red.Red is the color of blood, and so the planet became the
  god of WAR.@{i}Mars@{ui} with Romans, @{i}Ares@{ui} with Greeks.The Egyptians named the planet
  @{i}Her Descher@{ui}, the red one.Moreover, @{i}@{b}Mars has the most@{ui} eccentric@{ub} @{i}@{b}orbit among
  the terrestrial planets.If roundness of orbit makes the planets Venus and
  Jupiter (and also Earth) astrologically beneficial, than the eccentricity
  suggests the opposite@{ui}: agression @{i}and@{ui} change@{ub}.
    Orbital eccentricity affects Martian climate in great deal.The temperature
  variations over the course of Martian year are much higher than on similar
  conditions on Earth.Again, '@{i}change@{ui}' is the keyword.

    For long time Mars has been considered the best candidate for harboring
  extraterrestrial life.Astronomers that sow lines on its surface thought that
  they represent rivers and irrigation channels, constructed by intelligent
  beings.Seasonal color changes on the planet's surface were attributed to
  changes in the local vegetation.In 1938 @{b}Orson Welles@{ub} broadcasted a radio
  drama based on the science fiction classic '@{i}War of the Worlds@{ui}' by @{b}H.G.Wells@{ub}
  and caused a near panic among the people who listened the broadcast.Large
  number of them believed that the story was true and was actually happening.

    In July 1965 @{b}Mariner 4@{ub} reached the planet and transmitted first 22 close
  up pictures of Mars.All that was revealed was a dry cratered surface with
  no vegetation and no artificially constructed canals.

    Subsequently, in July and September 1976 @{b}Viking 1 & 2@{ub} landers landed on
  the surface and conducted 3 biology experiments.They discovered unexpected
  and enigmatic chemical activity in the Martian soil, but failed to provide
  clear evidence for the presence of living microorganisms within the samples.
  The results of these experiments are still being debated.Other instruments
  found no signs of organic chemistry, but they provided a precise analysis
  of the composition of the Martian atmosphere and found previously undetected
  trace elements.The question of whether life existed on Mars at some time in
  the distant past remains open.

    The atmosphere contains 95.32% CO2, 2.7% N2, 1.6% Ar, 0.13% O2, 0.03% H2O,
  and traces of other gases (Neon, Krypton, Xenon, Ozone).Atmospheric pressure
  is very low, only 7-11 mBar.Barometric pressure varies on semiannual basis,
  because @{b}the main ingredient of the atmosphere, CO2, seasonally freezes out
  to form an immense polar cap, alternately on each pole@{ub}.This cap of carbon
  dioxide snow evaporates again in spring, leaving the permanent layer of
  underlying water ice.Although Martian atmosphere contains only 1/1,000th of
  water that the Earth's atmosphere does, low pressure allows the water to
  condense and to form clouds.Clouds ride high in the atmosphere and swirl
  around the mountain slopes and patches of early morning fog form in the
  valleys.There is a lot of evidence that in the ancient Martian history the
  atmosphere was denser, allowing water to flow on the planet, forming great
  rivers, lakes, shorelines and islands.It is believed, with some evidence
  to support that belief, that a large part of that large quantity of water
  is still on the surface of the Mars, frozen as ice and burried just a meter
  or two below the surface.
    Northern carbon-dioxide cap sublimes completely during the Martian summer,
  but the southern one doesn't.This is because it is located on the highlands,
  and the temperature on the mountains is always lower than on the plains.
    Although the atmosphere has a low pressure, it is thick enough to form
  vast dust storms that from time to time engulf the entire planet for months.

    Average Martian temperature is 218 K (-55° C), and the maximal one is
  27° C.Minimal recorded temperature is 140 K (-133° C).

    Although Mars is much smaller than the Earth, its @{b}surface area is about
  the same size as the land area on Earth@{ub}.
    @{u}The terrain displays several spectacular sites@{uu}:
  1. @{b}Olympus Mons@{ub} - the largest mountain in the solar system, 24 km high.
     It has a base of 500 km in diameter and is rimmed by a cliff 6 km high.
  2. @{b}Tharsis@{ub} - a huge bulge on the surface, 4,000 km across and 10 km high.
  3. @{b}Valles Marineris@{ub} - network of canyons, 4,000 km long and 2-7 km deep.
  4. @{b}Hellas Planitia@{ub} - an impact crater, 2,000 km wide and 6 km deep.

    Southern hemisphere of Mars is made of ancient, cratered highlands.In
  contrast, most of the northern hemisphere are much younger plains.@{b}At the
  boundary of 2 hemispheres occurs an abrupt elevation change of several km@{ub}.
  The reason for this dichotomy is unknown, but some speculate that a very
  large impact shortly after formation of Mars may have been the cause.

    The interior of Mars probably consists of a dense core, some 3,400 km
  in diameter, surrounded by a molten rocky mantle somewhat denser than the
  Earth's, and a thin crust above that.The crust is estimated to be about
  80 km thick in the southern hemisphere (highlands), but only 35 km in the
  north (plains).Overall low density of Mars, when compared with the other
  terrestrial planets, indicates that @{b}it's core contains a relatively large
  fraction of sulfur in addition to iron@{ub}.Probably in a form of iron sulfide.
  (Sulfur is a lighter element commonly present with iron in small quantities
  and is considered as an imperfection in metalurgy.)

    At present time Mars seems to lack active plate tectonics.Without lateral
  plate motion hot spots under the crust stay in a fixed position relative to
  the surface.When combined with the lower Martian gravity, this accounts for
  the Tharsis bulge and its enormous volcanoes.There is no evidence of current
  volcanic activity.
    Martian atmosphere provides @{i}some@{ui} greenhouse effect, but much smaller than
  on Venus and Earth.It is able to raise the surface temperature for only 5°C.
  Lack of active plate tectonics prevents recycling of carbon dioxide embeded
  in carbonate rocks back into atmosphere.The Earth (and Venus especially)
  would be much warmer if they were located at Martian distance from the Sun.

    There is a clear evidence of @{i}erosion@{ui} on many places, both by wind and by
  running liquid water.There may have been large lakes or even oceans in the
  past.Their existance, however, appears to be very brief, and has occured
  very long time ago.The age of the erosion channels is estimated to be about
  4 Gyr.(Valles Marineris was NOT created by running water, but by breaking
  of the crust during the creation of Tharsis bulge.

    Mars Global Surveyor has unexpectedly detected a large, but not global,
  weak magnetic field in various regions of the planet.The field is probably
  just a remnant of an earlier global magnetic field which no longer exists.
  This finding may have important implications for the structure of planet's
  interior and for the history of the Martian atmosphere, and hence for the
  prospects of the existance of ancient life on Mars.

    Small number of meteorites (SNC meteorites) are believed to have their
  origins on Mars.Large volcanic eruptions and asteroid impacts may have
  thrown these bodies into solar system orbit.Some of them eventually ended
  up on Earth.Scientists have collected several chunks that have survived
  a descend through the Earth's atmosphere and studied them.
    On 7th Aug 1996 @{b}David McKay et al@{ub} announced the first identification of
  @{i}organic compounds in a Martian meteorite@{ui}.The authors suggested that these
  compounds, together with a number of other mineralogical features observed
  in the rock, may be an evidence for the existance of microorganisms on the
  ancient Mars.Although this is a strong evidence, it is not good enough to
  prove the existance of extraterrestrial life.An extraordinary claim would
  require an extraordinary evidence.Several contradictory studies have been
  published since the McKay paper.

    @{b}During late summer of 2003, Mars has approached the Earth closer than it
  has ever been during past 50,000 years@{ub}.Several spaceships were sent to Mars
  at that time to take the advantage of that situation.Skywatchers enjoyed the
  view.In august/september Venus (normally the brightest object on the sky
  apart from the Sun and the moon), was on the other side of the Sun, thus
  invisible.Jupiter, usually the second brightest object (after Venus), has
  also been on the other side of the Sun, not far from the Venus.@{i}@{b}This has
  enabled the Mars to be the brightest object on the sky for several weeks,
  shinning at -2.9 magnitude@{ub}@{ui}.If it wasn't located low on horizon on northern
  hemisphere, it's sighting would have been even more magnificient.But alas,
  the layers of thick atmosphere near the horizon have obsured the view during
  the most parts of the night.Viewers on the southern hemisphere have had the
  best view.If you have missed the oppurtunity to observe the Mars during this
  event, do not despair: @{i}the planet will come even closer in a mere 3 centuries@{ui}.
  Patience is a virtue. :-)

    Mars has 2 moonlets, @{b}Phobos@{ub} (Fear) and @{b}Deimos@{ub} (Panic).They are probably
  a captured asteroids.Both have very small size and irregular shape and are
  heavily cratered.Their densities are too low for them to be composed of
  pure rock.Instead they are probably a mixture of rocks and ices.If that
  is true, than they are more probably a captured dead cometary remnants.
  If the presence of ice is confirmed, they may serve as 'space stations'
  or intermediate stops to, and from Martian surface for manned missions.

  @{b}@{u}The moons of Mars@{uu}@{ub}:

    Name     a   i     e      Period mag   diam         density    albedo     Yr of discovery mass   Esc.vel.
            [km] [°]          [days]       [km]         [g/cm^3]              and discoverer  [Pt]   [km/s]
    ---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    Phobos  9380 1.075 0.0151 0.319  11.4  27×21.8×18.8 1.867±.076 0.071±.012 1877 A. Hall    0.0108
    Deimos 23460 1.793 0.0002 1.262  12.5  15×12.2×11   2.247±.251 0.068±.007 1877 A. Hall    0.0018

    @{b}Phobos@{ub} is @{i}@{b}closer to its primary planet than any other moon in the solar
      system@{ub}@{ui}.Its orbit lies only 5,980 km above the surface of the Mars.The
      pictures from Mars Global Surveyor indicate that the surface of Phobos
      is covered with a layer of fine dust about a meter thick, similar to
      the regolith on the Moon.@{i}Phobos 2@{ui} (USSR spacecraft) detected a faint
      steady outgassing from Phobos, but it failed to determine the nature
      of the material.Water is the best bet.
        @{i}@{b}Phobos orbits the Mars below the synchronous orbit radius, thus it
      rises on the west and sets on the east, usually twice a day.It is so
      close to the surface that it cannot be seen above the horizon from
      all points of Martian surface@{ub}@{ui}.
        Because it orbits so low, the tidal forces are @{i}lowering@{ui} its orbit
      (current rate is 1.8 m / century).In about 50 Myr it will approach
      the Martian surface too close and the tides will break it up into a
      ring of particles.The ice from particles will quickly evaporate and
      the dust and rocks will then continue their descend to the surface.
        The most prominent feature on Phobos is the large crater @{i}Stickney@{ui},
      named after the maiden name of discoverer's wife.The impact which
      created the crater has almost shattered Phobos.

    About one half of the spaceships that have tried to take a journey to Mars
  failed to reach their destination.The Red Planet stood up with it's violent
  attributes.Here goes the list of ships that were sent to Mars:

  @{b}@{u}Chronology of Martian exploration@{uu}@{ub}:
   1. Mars 1960A - USSR Mars Probe, launched on 10th Oct 1960.
      Mars 1960A failed to reach Earth orbit.

   2. Mars 1960B - USSR Mars Probe, launched on - 14th Oct 1960.
      Mars 1960B failed to reach Earth orbit.

   3. Mars 1962A - USSR Mars Flyby, launched on 24th Oct 1962.
      Mars 1962A failed to leave Earth orbit after the final rocket stage
      exploded.

   4. Mars 1 - USSR Mars Flyby - 893 kg, launched on 1st Nov 1962.
      Communications with Mars 1 failed en route.

   5. Mars 1962B - USSR Mars lander, launched on 4th Nov 1962.
      Mars 1962B failed to leave Earth orbit.

   6. Mariner 3 - USA Mars Flyby - 260 kg, launched on 5th Nov 1964.
      Mariner 3's solar panels did not open, preventing a flyby.
      Mariner 3 is now in a solar orbit.

   7. @{b}Mariner 4@{ub} - USA Mars Flyby - 260 kg, 28th Nov 1964 - 20th Dec 1967.
      Mariner 4 arrived at Mars on 14th Jul 1965 and passed within 9,920 km of
      the planet's surface.It returned 22 close-up photos showing a cratered
      surface.The thin atmosphere was confirmed to be composed primarily of
      carbon dioxide (CO2), with atmospheric pressure being in the range of
      5-10 mbar.A small intrinsic magnetic field was detected.
      Mariner 4 is now in a solar orbit.

   8. Zond 2 - USSR Mars Flyby, launched on 30th Nov 1964.
      Contact with Zond 2 was lost en route.

   9. @{b}Mariner 6@{ub} - USA Mars Flyby - 412 kg, launched on 24th Feb 1969.
      Mariner 6 arrived at Mars on 24th Feb 1969, and passed within 3,437 km
      of the planet's equatorial region.Mariner 6 and 7 took measurements of
      the surface and atmospheric temperature, surface molecular composition,
      and pressure of the atmosphere.Over 200 pictures were taken.
      Mariner 6 is now in a solar orbit.

  10. @{b}Mariner 7@{ub} - USA Mars Flyby - 412 kg, launched on 27th Mar 1969.
      Mariner 7 arrived at Mars on 5th Aug 1969, and passed within 3,551 km
      of the planet's south pole region.Mariner 6 and 7 took measurements of
      the surface and atmospheric temperature, surface molecular composition,
      and pressure of the atmosphere.Over 200 pictures were taken.
      Mariner 7 is now in a solar orbit.

  11. Mariner 8 - USA Mars Flyby, launched on 8th May 1971.
      Mariner 8 failed to reach Earth orbit.

  12. Kosmos 419 - USSR Mars Probe, launched on 10th May 1971.
      Kosmos 419 failed to leave Earth orbit.

  13. @{b}Mars 2@{ub} - USSR Mars Orbiter/Lander - 4,650 kg, launched on 19th May 1971.
      Mars 2 lander was released from the orbiter on 27th Nov 1971.Unfortuntely,
      it crashed because its breaking rockets failed - no data was returned.
      @{i}@{b}Mars 2 is the first human artifact on Mars@{ub}@{ui}.The orbiter returned data
      until 1972.

  14. @{b}Mars 3@{ub} - USSR Mars Orbiter/Lander - 4,643 kg, launched on 28th May 1971.
      Mars 3 arrived at Mars on 2nd Dec 1971.The lander @{i}@{b}became the first
      successful landing on Mars@{ub}@{ui}.Unfortuntely, it failed after sending only
      20 seconds of video data to the orbiter.The orbiter returned data until
      Aug 1972.It made measurements of surface temperature and atmospheric
      composition.

  15. @{b}Mariner 9@{ub} - USA Mars Orbiter - 974 kg, launched on 30th May 1971 - 1972.
      Mariner 9 arrived at Mars on 3rd Nov 1971 and was placed into orbit
      on 24th Nov.This was the first US spacecraft to enter an orbit around
      a planet other than the Moon.At the time of its arrival a huge dust
      storm was in progress on the planet.Many of the scientific experiments
      were delayed until the storm had subsided.The first hi-resolution images
      of the moons Phobos and Deimos were taken.River and channel like features
      were discovered.Mariner 9 is still in Martian orbit.

  16. Mars 4 - USSR Mars Orbiter - 4,650 kg, launched on 21st Jul 1973.
      Mars 4 arrived at Mars on Feb 1974, but failed to go into orbit due to
      a malfunction of its breaking engine.It flew past the planet within
      2,200 kilometers of the surface and returned some images and data.

  17. @{b}Mars 5@{ub} - USSR Mars Orbiter - 4,650 kg, launched on 25th Jul 1973.
      Mars 5 entered into orbit around Mars on 12th Feb 1974.It acquired
      imaging data for the Mars 6 and 7 missions.

  18. Mars 6 - USSR Mars Orbiter/Lander - 4,650 kg, launched on 5th Aug 1973.
      Mars 6 entered the Mars orbit on 12th Mar 1974 and launched its lander.
      The lander returned atmospheric descent data, but failed on its way down.

  19. Mars 7 - USSR Mars Orbiter/Lander - 4,650 kg, launched on 9th Aug 1973.
      Mars 7 approached Mars on 6th Mar 1974, but failed to enter into orbit.
      The lander missed the planet.Carrier and lander are now in a solar orbit.

  20. @{b}Viking 1@{ub} - USA Mars Orbiter/Lander - 3,399 kg, launched on 20th Aug 1975.
      Viking 1 and 2 were designed after the Mariner spacecraft.They consisted
      of an orbiter and a lander.The orbiter weighted 900 kg and the lander's
      weight was 600 kg.Viking 1 went into orbit about Mars on 19th Jun 1976.
      The lander touched down on 20th Jul 1976 on the western slopes of Chryse
      Planitia.Both landers had experiments to search for Martian micro-organism.
      The results of these experiments are still being debated.The landers
      provided detailed color panoramic views of the Martian terrain.They also
      monitored the Martian weather.The orbiters mapped the planet's surface,
      acquiring over 52,000 images.
      Viking 1 orbiter was deactivated on 7th Aug 1980 when it ran out of
      altitude-control propellant.
      Viking 1 lander was accidentally shut down on 13th Nov 1982, and
      communication was never regained.

  21. @{b}Viking 2@{ub} - USA Mars Orbiter/Lander - 3,399 kg, launched on 9th Sep 1975.
      Viking 1 and 2 were designed after the Mariner spacecraft.They consisted
      of an orbiter and a lander.The orbiter weighed 900 kg and the lander's
      weight was 600 kg.Viking 2 went into orbit about Mars on 24th Jul 1976.
      The lander touched down on 7th Aug 1976 at Utopia Planitia.Both landers
      had experiments to search for Martian micro-organism.The results of these
      experiments are still being debated.The landers provided detailed color
      panoramic views of the Martian terrain.They also monitored the Martian
      weather.The orbiters mapped the planet's surface, acquiring over 52,000
      images.
      Viking 2 orbiter was deactivated on 25th July 1978 when it ran out of a
      ltitude-control propellant.
      Viking 2 lander used Viking 1's orbiter as a communications relay, and
      had to be shut down at the same time as the orbiter, on 7th Aug 1980.

  22. Phobos 1 - USSR Mars Orbiter/Lander - 5,000 kg, launched on 7th Jul 1988.
      Phobos 1 was sent to investigate the Martian moon Phobos.It was lost
      en route to Mars by a command error on 2nd Sep 1988.

  23. Phobos 2 - USSR Phobos Flyby/Lander - 5,000 kg, launched on 12th Jul 1988.
      Phobos 2 arrived at Mars and was inserted into orbit on 30th Jan 1989.The
      orbiter moved within 800 kilometers of Phobos and then failed.The lander
      never made it to Phobos.

  24. Mars Observer - USA Mars Orbiter, launched on 25th Sep 1992.
      Communication with Mars Observer was lost on 21st Aug 1993, just before
      it was to be inserted into orbit.

  25. @{b}Mars Global Surveyor@{ub} - USA Mars Orbiter, launched on 7th Nov 1996.
      Mars Global Surveyor was inserted into an elliptical capture orbit on
      12th Sep 1997.The spacecraft was initiated due to the loss of the Mars
      Observer and the basic design is after the Mars Observer.Mars Global
      Surveyor is designed to orbit the Mars over a two year period and to
      collect data on the surface morphology, topography, composition,
      gravity, atmospheric dynamics, and magnetic field.This data will be
      used to investigate the surface processes, geology, distribution of
      material, internal properties, evolution of the magnetic field, and
      the weather and climate of Mars.On 17th Sep 1997 Mars Global Surveyor
      has detected a scattered remnants of the once global magnetic field.

  26. Mars 96 - Russia Orbiter & Lander, launched on - 16th Nov 1996.
      Mars 96 consisted of an orbiter, two landers, and two soil penetrators
      that were to reach the planet in Sep 1997.The rocket carring Mars 96
      lifted off successfully, but as it entered orbit the rocket's fourth
      stage ignited prematurely and sent the probe into a wild tumble.It
      crashed into the ocean somewhere between the Chilean coast and Easter
      Island.The spacecraft sank, carrying with it 270 grams of plutonium-238.

  27. @{b}Mars Pathfinder@{ub} - USA Lander/Surface Rover - 264 kg (lander), 10.5 kg
      (rover), launched on 4th Dec 1996.
      Mars Pathfinder arrived at Mars on 4th Jul 1997 and impacted the surface
      at 16:57 UT at a velocity of about 18 m/s.It bounced about 15 meters into
      the air, bouncing another 15 times and rolling before coming to rest
      approximately 2.5 min after impact and about 1 km from the initial impact
      site.The landing site was in the Ares Vallis region at 19.33 N, 33.55 W
      and was named the Sagan Memorial Station.A six-wheel rover, Sojourner,
      rolled onto the Martian surface on 6th Jul at about 5:40 UT.
      Mars Pathfinder returned 2.6 Gbits of information, including more than
      16,000 images from the lander and 550 images from the rover, as well as
      more than 15 chemical analyses of rocks and extensive data on winds and
      other weather factors.The last successful data transmission was on the
      27th Sep 1997, on 83rd day of the mission since landing on the surface.
      This was the second mission in NASA's low-cost Discovery series.

  28. Nozomi (Planet B) - Japan Mars Orbiter - 541 kg, launched on 4th Jul 1998.
      Japan's Institute of Space and Astronautical Science (ISAS) launched
      this probe to study the Martian environment.This was the first Japanese
      spacecraft sent to another planet.Nozomi was supposed to encounter Mars
      in Dec 2003, but the communication with the spacecraft was lost en route,
      just prior to its arrival.

  29. Mars Climate Orbiter - USA Mars Orbiter, launched on 11 Dec 1998.
      Mars Climate Orbiter, also known as the Mars Surveyor '98 Orbiter,
      was a companion to the Mars Polar Lander.Its mission was to study the
      Martian weather, climate, and water and carbon dioxide budget.It was
      destroyed when a navigation error caused it to miss its target altitude
      at Mars by 80 to 90 km instead of entering the martian atmosphere at an
      altitude of 57 km during the orbit insertion maneuver.

  30. Mars Polar Lander - USA Mars Lander, launched on 3rd Jan 1999.
      Mars Polar Lander, also known as the Mars Surveyor '98 Lander, was a
      companion to the Mars Climate Orbiter.It was to touch down on the southern
      polar layered terrain, between 73 S and 76 S, less than 1,000 km from the
      south pole, near the edge of the carbon dioxide ice cap during Mars's late
      southern spring.The last telemetry from the spacecraft was sent just prior
      to atmospheric entry on 3rd Dec 1999.No further signals have been received
      from the lander.The cause of this loss of communication is not known.

  31. Deep Space 2 (DS2) - USA Mars Penetrators, launched on 3rd Jan 1999.
      Deep Space 2 (DS2) project is a New Millenium mission consisting of two
      probes which were to penetrate the surface of Mars near the south polar
      layered terrain and send back data on the sub-surface properties.
      On 3rd Dec 1999 the probes were nearing Mars on a trajectory to enter the
      atmosphere and bring them to their intended landing site, but contact was
      never made with either probe and the mission was presumed lost.

  32. @{i}@{b}2001 Mars Odyssey@{ub}@{ui} - USA Mars Orbiter - 725 kg, launched on 7th Apr 2001.
      2001 Mars Odyssey orbiter will nominally orbit Mars for three years,
      with the objective of conducting a detailed mineralogical analysis of
      the planet's surface from orbit and measuring the radiation environment.
      The mission has as its primary science goals to gather data to help
      determine whether the environment on Mars was ever conducive to life,
      to characterize the climate and geology of Mars, and to study potential
      radiation hazards to possible future astronaut missions.It will also
      act as a communications relay for Mars rovers Spirit and Opportunity.
      Mars Odyssey has detected hydrogen just below the surface, which means
      that water ice mixed with rocks (dirty snow) may exist at ~1 m depth.

  33. @{i}@{b}Mars Express@{ub}@{ui} - ESA Mars Orbiter/Lander - 1123 kg, launched on 1st Jun 2003.
      The objective of the orbiter is to obtain a global high-resolution 
      photo-geology (10 m) and mineralogical mapping (100 m), including
      the mapping of atmospheric composition and circulation.It would
      also study the interactions between the atmosphere and both the
      interplanetary space and subsurface areas.The aim of Beagle II
      Lander (among other things) was to search for life on Mars.
      Mars Express released the Lander on 19th Dec 2003, 8:31 UT.The
      Lander entered the Martian atmosphere on 25th Dec 2003, but no
      signals were received afterward and the mission was declared lost.
      After the departure of Beagle II, the orbiter performed several
      braking maneuvers and entered the martian orbit on 30th Dec 2003.
      Nominal mission duration is planned to be 1 martian year (687 d).

  34. @{i}@{b}Mars Exploration Rover@{ub}@{ui} '@{b}Spirit@{ub}' - USA Rover - 878 kg, launched on
      10th Jun 2003.
      Spirit successfully landed on Mars on 4th Jan 2004, 4h35m UT at Gusev
      crater (14.82 S, 184.85 W).The landing site is a possible former lake
      in a giant impact crater.Robot geologist has as it's primary mission
      to analyze rocks and soils in search for clues to past water activity
      on Mars.The mission is expected to last at least 90 days.

  35. @{i}@{b}Mars Exploration Rover@{ub}@{ui} '@{b}Opportunity@{ub}'- USA Rover - 878 kg, launched on
      8th Jul 2003.
      Opportuinity successfully landed on Mars on 25th Jan 2004, 5h 5m UT at
      Terra Meridiani (2.07 S, 6.08 W), the "Hematite Site".Hematite is an
      iron mineral that typically forms in water.Robot geologist has as it's
      primary mission to analyze rocks and soils in search for clues to past
      water activity on Mars.The mission is expected to last at least 90 days.

  36. @{i}Mars Reconnaisance Orbiter@{ui} - USA Mars Orbiter - ~1,975 kg, (8 - 28 Aug 2005)
      The aim of the mission is to make the map of the surface with a high
      resolution of less than a 1 m/pixel.Good enough to see a beachball.
      It will also study the surface composition and conduct a search for
      underground water in order to identify possible future landing sites.
      Primary misson duration is 1 martian year (687 days), after which
      the orbiter will be used as a communications relay.

  37. @{i}Phoenix@{ui} - USA Mars Lander - (late 2007)
      The aim of the mission is to search for organic molecules and water.

  38. @{i}NetLanders@{ui} - CNES (French Space Agency) 4 Mars Landers - (late 2007)
      Network of scientific stations (4 landers).Mission duration: 1 martian
      year (~687 days).NetLanders are planned to be launched together with
      the Mars Sample Return technology mission onboard.

  39. @{i}Mars Science Laboratory@{ui} - USA Rover - (late 2009)
      Rover sized like a minivan would have at least 1 martian year to crawl
      the surface and to study the biological potentials of at least one area.

  40. @{i}Scout Mission@{ui} - (2011)

  @{b}@{u}Properties of Mars@{uu}@{ub}:
              mass: 6.421e23 kg (0.10745 Earth's)
     equ. diameter: 6.7944 Mm (.53264 Earth's)
    orbital period: 686.98 days
         semi-axis: 1.5237 AU
       inclination: 1.850°
      eccentricity: 0.0934
     mean velocity: 24.13 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.15 (0 = black, 1 = white)
       rot. period: 24h37m22.7s (1.025957 d)
              tilt: 25.19°
       nr of rings: 0
       nr of moons: 2 (2 moonlets)
           density: 3.94 g/cm^3
                 T: 218 K (min 133 K, max 300 K)
   surface gravity: 3.72 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 5.02 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: -2.01 V
  atm. composition: 95.32% CO2, 2.7% N2, 1.6% Ar, 0.13% O2, 0.07% CO, 0.03% H20,
                    0.00025% Ne, 0.00003% Kr, 0.000008% Xe, 0.000003% O3
     atm. pressure: 0.007 bar

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically@{uu}@{ub}: Male, change, agression, activity, sport, army, force, young,
    brave, agility, fast, immediate, exercise, athletics, danger, explosive.
    Mars has been assigned the rulership over the spring sign of @{b}Aries@{ub}.

  @{b}@{u}History@{uu}@{ub}: The name of month March derives from Mars.

  @{b}@{u}Mythology@{uu}@{ub}: Mars is a Roman god of @{i}war@{ui} (Greek's Ares).Before it became the
    god of war, Mars was the god of @{i}agriculture@{ui}.(Spring is a time of change,
    atributed to Mars, and it is a good time to start the agricultural work.
    Spring is also the best time to start a military campaign (a conquest),
    at least it was in the ancient times.Thus, when the Roman civilization
    got stronger, a god of agriculture got promoted to occupy a more violent
    position.Greek's Ares was originally a god of war.
    @{b}Phobos@{ub} and @{b}Deimos@{ub} are sons of Ares (Mars) and Aphrodite (Venus).
@endnode
///
///   Jupiter                                             //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-JUPITER "ASense - Planets: Jupiter"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-MARS
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-SATURN
@{b}@{u}Jupiter@{uu}@{ub}: The largest gas giant.

    @{b}Jupiter alone has more mass than all of the other planets combined@{ub}.It is
  318 times more massive than the Earth and has a volume which is more than
  1,300 times larger.@{b}It is about as big as a gas giant can be@{ub}.With additional
  mass, the density would increase, but not the size.

    Jupiter has 63 currently known satellites, some of which are very big.
  There are @{i}8 regular satellites, 4 small ones and 4 very large ones@{ui}.As for
  the irregulars, the majority of them are the remnants of captured comets
  and asteroids, a space debris.Out of @{i}55 currently known irregular moons@{ui},
  only 8 have a diameter larger than 10 km, and @{i}only one@{ui} a diameter @{i}larger
  than 100 km@{ui} in size.Most of the irregular moons are moving in retrograde
  direction, and some of them are remnants of larger bodies that have been
  shattered into pieces by previous collisions.
    4 large satellites of Jupiter are called @{i}Galileans@{ui}, because they were
  first observed by @{b}Galileo@{ub} on 7th Jan 1610.First he observed three points
  of light arranged in a straight line next to Jupiter.He thought that they
  were stars, but the lining caught his attention, so he throw a look on
  the following day as well, and noticed a change in their position.For a
  week he continued his observations.On 11th of January, a forth "star"
  appeared, which turned out to be Ganymede.After a week, he concluded
  that what he saw were not stars, but planetary bodies orbiting around
  the Jupiter.He quickly published his discovery in '@{i}Sidereus Nuncius@{ui}'
  in Mar 1610.This discovery provided evidence to support Copernican
  system and showed that everything did not revolve around the Earth.
    @{b}Simon Marius@{ub} claimed to have observed Jupiter's moons about 5 weeks
  earlier than Galileo, but he didn't published his observations right
  away.His claims couldn't be verified, and so the Galileo, whose work
  was more reliable and extensive, took the glory, and was given the
  credit he deserved.The 4 moons are now called '@{i}@{b}Galilean moons@{ub}@{ui}'.
    In 1614, Marius did provide names for the moons, based on a suggestion
  from @{b}Johannes Kepler@{ub}:

  "@{i}Jupiter is much blamed by the poets on account of his irregular loves.
  Three maidens are especially mentioned as having been clandestinely
  courted by Jupiter with success.@{b}Io@{ub}, daughter of the River, Inachus,
  @{b}Callisto@{ub} of Lycaon, @{b}Europa@{ub} of Agenor.Then there was @{b}Ganymede@{ub}, the
  handsome son of King Tros, whom Jupiter, having taken the form of an
  eagle, transported to heaven on his back, as poets fabulously tell...
  I think, therefore, that I shall not have done amiss if the First is
  called by me Io, the Second Europa, the Third, on account of it's
  majesty of light, Ganymede, the Fourth Callisto..."

  "This fancy, and the particular names given, were suggested to me by
  @{b}Kepler@{ub}, Imperial Astronomer, when we met at Ratisbon fair in October 1613.
  So if, as a jest, and in memory of our friendship then begun, I hail him
  as joint father of these four stars, again I shall not be doing wrong.@{ui}"

    Galileo originally called the moons '@{i}Medicean planets@{ui}', after the
  @{b}Medici@{ub} family, and referred to the individual moons by roman numvbers
  (@{b}I, II, III, IV@{ub}).His naming system was abandoned in mid 1800's when it
  became apparent that it would be very confusing, as the new additional
  moons were being discovered.It is then, that the names of @{b}Io@{ub}, @{b}Europa@{ub},
  @{b}Ganymede@{ub} and @{b}Callisto@{ub} were officially adopted.

    Drag of Galilean moons is slowly slowing down Jupiter's rotation.

    Jupiter has a strong gravity field that acts as a sink for various
  comets and asteroids that lurk around.It either throws them away from
  the solar system, captures them, or destroys them.@{b}Without Jupiter, life
  on Earth would be exposed to more frequent bombardment from space and
  much more hazardous@{ub}.

    The appearance of the atmosphere is very colorful.The colors are due
  to a chemical reactions of trace elements (possibly of sulfur from Io).
  Light bands are called '@{i}zones@{ui}', and dark one are called '@{i}belts@{ui}'.The bands
  show differential rotation.Cloud colors depend also on their altitude.
  Red clouds are the highest, followed by brown and white in the midle.The
  blue ones are the lowest, occasionally visible through the upper layers.

    Auroral emissions were observed in the polar regions.They appear to be
  caused by material from Io that spirals along magnetic lines to fall into
  Jupiter's atmosphere.

    There is much less water in the atmosphere than expected.It was expected
  for Jupiter to have twice as much oxygen than the Sun, but instead it has
  the amount that is @{i}lesser@{ui} than the Sun's.At least in the upper cloud layers.

    Jovian atmosphere is dominated by the @{i}@{b}Great Red Spot@{ub}@{ui}, a hurricane twice
  the size of Earth that goes on and on for more than 300 years.The spot has
  been discovered by Cassini.It has a dimension of 12×25 Mm and moves in a
  counter-clockwise direction (anticyclon).At the outer edge, the material
  rotates with a period of 4 to 6 days.Near the centre, motions are small
  and almost chaotic.The array of other smaller storms and whirlpools can
  be found throughout the banded clouds.They all interact with each other.
  Physically, the Great Red Spot is a high pressure region where cloud tops
  are higher and cooler, and thus differently colored.It is unknown why the
  Great Red Spot shows such a persistance over time.

    A pattern of east-to-west winds extends probably upto 75° of north and
  south latitudes.Downward and upward convective movements dominate in the
  polar regions.
  
    Turbulent @{i}winds@{ui} of 600 km/h that extend for thousands of kilometers deep
  into interior were detected.

    The atmospheric composition of Jupiter is 89% hydrogen, and 11% helium
  with small amounts of methane, ammonia and water vapor.There are traces of
  other elements too, like sulfur, oxygen and sodium that are coming from Io.

    At depths of about 10,000 km, the hydrogen atoms split due to high
  pressure (1 Mbar) and temperature (6,000 K).This state of ionization is
  known as '@{i}liquid metallic hydrogen@{ui}'.The situation is similar to Sun's
  interior.Laboratory experiments show that @{b}the hydrogen doesn't change its
  phase suddenly, so there is no clear boundary between gaseous and liquid
  layers of hydrogen@{ub}.It exists in a mixed form, and slowly transforms from
  gas to liquid.Below the hydrogen is a soupy liquid mixture of water, methane
  and ammonia under high pressures and temperatures.Finally at the center
  is a rocky core of up to 10 Earth masses.The temperature in the core is
  estimated to be around 20,000 K.Large deposits of @{i}Uranium@{ui} in the core,
  together with gravitational compression, are responsible for the excess
  of heat that the Jupiter radiates into space.

    Heat driven convections within the liquid metallic hydrogen layer are
  the cause of Jupiter's very strong @{i}magnetic field@{ui}.@{b}The field is so strong,
  that it's magnetotail extends for 750 Gm, all the way to Saturn@{ub} (where it
  was detected by Voyager 2).In a Sun's direction, the field stretches only
  few Gm.Galilean moons are located within the magnetosphere, which is very
  destructive for Io.@{i}1 ton of material is being stripped away from Io every
  second by the force of the field.The ionized material follows the magnetic
  lines, and some of it ends up in the Jupiter's polar atmosphere, producing
  auroras, very bright in UV@{ui}.Surprisingly, @{b}the @{i}Pioneer spacecrafts@{ui}, which
  visited the Jupiter system 4.5 years prior to @{i}Voyagers@{ui}, haven't detected
  any of the intensive activity surrounding the Io@{ub}.Is it possible that all
  that drastic volcanism switched on suddenly between Dec 1973 and Jan 1979 ?

    Some of the ions trapped within the magnetosphere manage to pick up
  the electrons to become neutral atoms.Then, they are able to escape the
  field, flying away with speeds that reach 1/10th of the speed of light.

    Jupiter has faint ring system, invisible from Earth.It was discovered
  by Voyager 1, after 2 people in the mission control insisted that after
  a long journey, it is worthy to throw a quick look around to check out
  if there are any rings around the planet.Nobody expected them, and their
  discovery was a total surprise.
    The rings were made of dust stripped away from 4 inner moons by Jovian
  magnetosphere.Energetic micrometeoric impacts, accelerated by Jupiter's
  gravitational and magnetic field, are constantly crumbling the surfaces
  of those moons into dust that replenishes the rings.Dusty particles do
  not stay very long within the rings.Atmospheric and magnetic drag quickly
  spiralls them down to Jupiter.
    @{i}@{b}The ring system is simple, and is composed of an inner halo, a main ring,
  and the Gossamer rings@{ub}@{ui}.Gossamer rings were thought to be a single ring, but
  Galileo spacecraft discovered that they are really two rings, one embedded
  into another.
    The @{b}halo ring@{ub} is toroidal in shape and extends from 92 to 122.5 Mn from
  the center of Jupiter.The @{b}main ring@{ub} extends from halo's boundary to about
  128.94 Mm (just inside the orbit of @{i}Adrastea@{ui}).Close to the orbit of @{i}Metis@{ui},
  the main ring decreases in brightness.
    The innermost @{b}Amalthea Gossamer ring@{ub} extends from the orbit of @{i}Adrastea@{ui}
  to the orbit of @{i}Amalthea@{ui}, at 181 Mm from Jupiter's center.
    @{b}Thebe Gossamer ring@{ub} extends from @{i}Amalthea's@{ui} orbit to @{i}Thebe's@{ui} orbit, at
  221 Mn from the center of Jupiter.
    Being made of dust, all rings are very dark, with albedos of 0.05.

    On July 1994 remnants of a comet @{b}Shoemaker-Levy 9@{ub} collided with Jupiter.
  Comet was broken by previous approach to Jupiter onto at least 20 pieces,
  the largest of which were about 2 km in diameter.The crash was observed
  by Hubble Space Telescope, and the scarves from a chain of impacts were
  visible for a full year afterwards.

  @{b}@{u}The moons of Jupiter@{uu}@{ub}:
     Jupiter's moon system resembles that of the Sun, with bodies arranged
   by density from highest in inner orbits to lowest in the outer regions.
   @{b}Just like in the solar system, there are 4 small inner moons, followed
   by four giant ones, and some irregular debris outside@{ub}.

     @{i}Io, Europa and Ganymede are locked in almost perfect orbital resonance
   of 1:2:4, with Callysto very close to complete the full 1:2:4:8 pattern@{ui}.

