    @{b}Metis@{ub} [MEE-tis] is the innermost known satellite of Jupiter.It is
      a very small rocky moonlet that probably serves as a source of
      material for the Jupiter's main ring, within which it lies.
      @{i}Metis was named after a Titaness who was a consort of Zeus@{ui}.

    @{b}Adrastea@{ub} [a-DRAS-tee-uh] is the second of the 4 small inner moons of
      Jupiter, smaller than Metis, but more dense.Both Adrastea and Metis
      lie within Jupiter's main ring and are the source of material for
      it's replenishment.Higher density may indicate a different origin.
      @{i}Adrastea was the daughter of Jupiter and Ananke and the distributor
      of rewards and punishments@{ui}.

    @{b}Amalthea@{ub} [am-al-THEE-uh] is the largest among 4 small inner moons of
      Jupiter.It is an extremely irregular moon, having dimensions of
      270×165×150 km in diameter.Moreover, it has a few extremely large
      craters relative to it's size.@{i}Pan@{ui}, the largest crater, is 100 km
      in diameter, and at least 8 km deep.Another crater, @{i}Gaea@{ui}, is 80 km
      wide and probably twice as deep as Pan.
        Amalthea also have two known mountains, @{i}Mons Lyctas@{ui} and @{i}Mons Ida@{ui},
      with local relief reaching up to 20 km.
        The surface of the moon is dark and reddish, the color caused by
      a dusting of sulfur originating from Io's volcanoes.There are also
      bright patches of green on the major slopes, with unknown origin.
        The satellite @{i}rotates synchronously@{ui}, with it's long axis pointed
      towards Jupiter.It is exposed to intense Jupiter's radiation field
      and continuously receives high doses of energetic ions, protons and
      electrons produced by the Jupiter's magnetosphere.In addition, it is
      bombarded with micrometeorites and heavy sulfur, oxygen and sodium
      ions that have been stripped away from Io.
        Amalthea was the first moon to be discovered around Jupiter after
      the discovery of four large Galilean moons.It is also the last moon
      in the solar system which was found by a direct visual observation
      with a telescope.It was discovered in 1892 by American astronomer
      @{i}Edward Emerson Barnard@{ui} from the Lick Observatory with the help of
      a 36 inch (91 cm) refractory telescope.
        @{i}Amalthea was a nymph who nursed the infant Zeus with goat milk@{ui}.

    @{b}Thebe@{ub} [THEE-bee] is the furthest of the 4 small inner moons of Jupiter.
      It has 3 or 4 very large impact craters, roughly comparable with the
      size of the moon.The largest one, @{i}Zethus@{ui}, measures 40 km in diameter.
        @{i}Thebe was a nymph and a daughter of the river god Asopus@{ui}.

    @{b}Io@{ub} [EE-oh] @{i}@{b}is the most volcanic body known@{ub}@{ui}.It is the innermost of the
      4 large Galilean moons.It orbits closer to Jupiter's cloud tops than
      the Moon orbits the Earth.This proximity makes it exposed to Jovian
      strong gravity pull and it's intense radiation belt.@{b}Tides inflicted
      by Jovian gravitation strain the Io's internals and cause volcanism.
      On one side Europa and Ganymede perturb Io in its orbit, and on the
      other, Jupiter pulls it back@{ub}.@{i}@{b}The struggle causes tidal bulging upto
      100 meters on surface@{ub}@{ui}, which is 100 times more than tides on Earth.
        On the surface there are lava flows, lava lakes, volcanic geysers
      spewing sulfurous plumes to over 500 km high.@{i}Mountains are reaching
      upto 16 km in height, and the whole landscape baths in sulfur and
      is covered with magma spills@{ui}.Io has a thin atmosphere consisting of
      sulfur-dioxide.
        Voyager 1 identified 9 erupting volcanoes.Voyager 2 found that 8
      out of 9 were still erupting by the time of its arrival, four months
      later.Plumes from the volcanoes were reaching 300 km in height, and
      the @{i}material was being ejected at velocities up to 1.05 km/s@{ui}, which
      is 3780 km/h.For comparison, ejecta velocities at Mount Etna, one
      of Earth's most explosive volcanoes, reach only 50 m/s, a 20 times
      slower speed.
        Voyager 1 measured a temperature of a large hot spot on Io, which
      was believed to be a lava lake.@{i}@{b}While the surrounding terrain has a
      deep subzero temperature of 130 K, the hot spot was warmed to about
      290 K (17°C).This indicated that the surface is not molten, although
      it appeared to be so@{ub}@{ui}.

        @{b}As the Jovian magnetosphere rotates, it sweeps past Io and strips
      away 1 ton per second of volcanic gases and other materials.This
      produces a neutral cloud of atoms orbiting with Io, as well as a
      huge doughnut shaped torus of ions that glow in UV light@{ub}.@{i}The torus's
      heavy ions migrate outward and their pressure inflates the Jovian
      magnetosphere to more than twice of it's expected size@{ui}.Some of the
      sulfur and oxygen ions fall into Jupiter's atmosphere, resulting in
      auroras.
        @{i}Io acts as an electrical generator as it moves through Jupiter's
      magnetic field, developing 400 kV across it's diameter and generating
      an electrical current of 3 MA that flows along the magnetic field to
      the planet's ionosphere@{ui}.
        Io has a metallic Fe-Ni core with a rocky envelope that extends to
      the surface.Rocks are silicate rich, and the core extends halfway to
      the surface.Rocky crust is very thin.@{i}Despite the volcanism, the mean
      surface temperature on Io is only 130 K@{ui}.
        Io is the 13th largest body in the solar system, and is larger than
      the Moon.

    @{b}Europa@{ub} [yur-ROH-pah] @{i}is the smallest of the 4 large Galilean moons.
      Yet, it is still@{ui} the 15th largest body in the solar system, @{i}bigger
      than Triton and Pluto@{ui}.It is slightly smaller than our Moon, though.

        @{i}Europa was named after the beautiful Phoenician princess who
      was abducted by Zeus@{ui}.Zeus (Jupiter) has transformed himself into
      a shape of white bull and carried Europa away to the island of
      Crete.He than revealed his true identity and Europa became the
      first queen of Crete.With Zeus, Europa had 3 sons, @{i}Rhadamantus@{ui},
      @{i}Minos@{ui} and @{i}Sarpedon@{ui}, who were the Trojan war contemporaries.
      To remember the story we now also have the constellation of
      @{i}Taurus@{ui}, and a latin saying '@{i}Quod licet Jovi, non licet bovi@{ui}.'
      (What Jupiter can, an ox can't.)

        Europa has caught significant scientific attention in recent
      years, after it has been discovered that it @{i}@{b}may contain a large
      ocean of liquid water beneath it's icy crust@{ub}@{ui}.The water layer is
      believed to be @{i}@{b}upto 100 km thick@{ub}@{ui}, and significant parts of it may
      still be liquid.The moon has a metallic Fe-Ni core surrounded by
      a rocky envelope, upon which lies an ocean of liquid water and a
      thick crust of ice.@{i}@{b}Tidal forces that heat the Io@{ub}@{ui} may have kept the
      water layer on Europa unfrozen, although @{i}@{b}in the case of Europa@{ub}@{ui},
      they @{i}@{b}have only tenth of the strength that they have on Io@{ub}@{ui}.Still,
      that may be sufficient enough.The existance of liquid water gives
      a moderate prospects for life to exist as well.In bacterial form at
      least.All of that is still very uncertain and speculative, though.

        The surface of Europa is criss-crossed with fissures and ridges
      in the ice.There are very few craters, indicating a @{i}young surface@{ui}.
      Only 3 craters larger than 5 km in diameter have been found.One of
      them, @{i}Awyll@{ui} (the Celtic god of underworld), has 50 km in diameter,
      and there is another one which has 30.The impacts that have created
      them were strong enough to break the thick icy crust into slabs and
      to penetrate into deep ocean below.Icy slush mixed with rocks have
      rushed from below between the plates and slowly refroze afterwards.
      Evidence of @{i}cryovolcanism@{ui} has been found (i.e. volcanoes spilling
      half molten soft ice instead of lava).Mean surface temperature on
      Europa is 128 K.

        Recently, patches of @{i}sulfuric acid@{ui} (a nasty chemical) have been
      found by the Hubble Space Telescope (HST).Thickness of the deposits
      is still unknown.They can be just a light dusting on the surface, or
      an important component of the icy crust.Sulfur may originate from
      sodium- and manganese-sulfates from oceans that were altered by the
      intense Jupiter's radiation.

        An extremely tenuous @{i}layer of molecular oxygen@{ui} was detected by
      Hubble as well.It is created from water ice by radiation, extends
      upto 200 km from the surface and slowly leaks away.Hydrogen from
      water escapes faster because it is lighter, and thus the oxygen
      remains in small quantities.The resulting atmospheric pressure
      is e-11 smaller than that on Earth (10 pbar).@{i}If all the oxygen
      from Europa's atmosphere is piled together, it would barely be
      able to fill several cubic hectometers on Earth's surface@{ui}.

        @{b}When the Sun becomes a subgiant, it would be hot enough to melt
      the icy crust, and to expose the underlying ocean of water.Life may
      florish for a while on Europa during that period@{ub}.Perhaps one that
      originated from Earth, which is going to be a furnace at that time.
      That is, if the solar system survives unchanged the collision of
      Milky Way with the Andromeda galaxy.

    @{b}Ganymede@{ub} [GAN-ee-meed] is the largest one of the 4 Galilean moons,
      and also @{b}the largest moon in our solar system@{ub}.It @{b}is bigger than
      the Mercury@{ub} and could have been classified as a planet if it
      orbited the Sun instead of Jupiter.On the other hand, Ganymede
      is much less dense than the Mercury, with only 45% of Mercury's
      mass.This corelates with a fact that it is really only a moon.

        Ganymede is most likely composed of a rocky core with a mantle
      of silicates and soft water ice and a crust of rock and ice.The
      core takes up 50% of satellites diameter.There is also a dense
      metallic core at the centre of rocky core, which may be the source
      of Ganymede's @{i}magnetic field@{ui}.Differentiation into layers implies
      the existance of greater degree of heat sometime in the past.

        The moon has no atmosphere, but the Hubble Space Telescope has
      recently detected @{i}ozone@{ui} on it's surface, which is being produced
      by radiation from the Jupiter's magnetosphere.Charged particles
      penetrate the surface ice and break up the water molecules.This
      indicates that Ganymede probably has a @{i}tenuous oxygen atmosphere
      like the one detected on Europe@{ui}, since the underlying process
      that generates the oxygen is the same.

        Ganymede is @{i}heavily cratered moon@{ui}, with a complex geological
      history.There are light and dark regions, mountains, valleys,
      craters and lava flows.Dark regions are more heavily cratered,
      indicating their older age.The bright regions have ridges and
      throughs that go for thousands of kilometers, with a vertical
      relief of few hundred meters.They are formed more recently by
      tension from some global tectonic processes.Although the real
      reason is unknown, there are some indications of local crust
      spreading due to the freezing of water contained deeply below.
      The spreading has caused the crust to shear and separate.
      Mean surface temperature on Ganymede is 125 K.

    @{b}Callisto@{ub} [kah-LISS-toe] is the furthermost of the 4 Galilean moons.
      It is the 11th largest body in the solar system, @{b}slightly larger
      than Mercury, but somewhat smaller than Ganymede and Titan@{ub}.@{i}It's
      orbit lies just beyond Jupiter's main radiation belt@{ui}.

        @{b}Callisto is the most heavily cratered moon in the solar system@{ub}.
      It has an ancient, 4 Gyr old crust that lacks any feature except
      impact craters.There are no large mountains, possibly due to the
      icy nature of the surface.
        Two enormous impact basins (extremely large craters) are found
      on Callisto.The first is @{i}@{b}Valhalla@{ub}@{ui}, with a bright central region
      600 km in diameter and associated concentric rings that have a
      diameter of 3000 km.The second one is @{i}@{b}Asgard@{ub}@{ui}, 1600 km in diameter.
      There are also 12 chains of craters, which are believed to result
      from the impacts of fragmented objects, probably of comets similar
      to Shoemaker-Levy 9 which collided with the Jupiter in Jul 1994.
      (Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9 was first disrupted during a close passage
      of Jupiter and then, on subsequent return, the pieces smashed onto
      Jupiter forming a chain of impacts.)
        The surface shows a surprising @{i}lack of small craters@{ui}, suggesting
      that some process must have obliterated them.For example, glacial
      movements could have buried the small craters and other small-scale
      features, creating the fresh ice surface.

        @{b}Callisto has the lowest density among te Galilean moons@{ub}.@{i}@{b}Its
      interior is only partially differentiated@{ub}@{ui}, with percentage of
      rocks slowly increasing as depth increases.Above the compressed
      interior of rocks and ice is a @{i}@{b}possible salty ocean more than
      10 km deep, followed by the icy crust that is about 200 km thick@{ub}@{ui}.
      The premise of an ocean came from studying the magnetic fields
      around Jupiter and its moons.It was found that @{i}Callisto's magnetic
      field varies@{ui} (flows in various directions at different times) in
      response to the background magnetic field of Jupiter.
        There is no known atmosphere.

    @{b}Leda@{ub} [LEE-duh] is a very small rocky moonlet, a member of @{i}Himalia@{ui} group.
      @{i}Leda was the queen of Sparta and the mother of Helen and Pollux@{ui}.
  * @{b}Himalia@{ub} [hih-MAL-yuh] is the largest one of Jupiter's outer satellites.
      It is an irregularly shaped moon, 184 km in diameter, that is most
      likely a captured asteroid.@{i}Himalia was a nymph who bore 3 sons of Zeus@{ui}.
    @{b}Lysithea@{ub} [ly-SITH-ee-uh] is a small moonlet, a member of @{i}Himalia@{ui} group.
      @{i}Lysithea was a daughter of Oceanus and one of Zeus's lovers@{ui}.
    @{b}Elara@{ub} [EE-lar-uh] is a small rocky moon, a member of @{i}Himalia@{ui} group.
      @{i}Elara and Zeus were the parents of Tityus the giant@{ui}.

  *   @{i}Leda, Himalia, Lysithea@{ui} and @{i}Elara@{ui} all have similar orbital parameters,
    indicating that they were probably a single body once, disrupted by an
    impact.The collision must have happened not so long ago (astronomically
    speaking), because Himalia still hasn't synchronised its rotational and
    orbital periods.The event that broke the satellite, may have spun it as
    well.Himalia now rotates with a period of 0.4 days, while Elara has a
    period of 0.5 days.Rotational periods of other group members are unknown,
    but are probably not synchronised and are close to Himalia's period.
      The group moves in a @{i}prograde@{ui} direction on a large distance of 11 Gm,
    indicating that the original satellite was probably a captured asteroid.

 ** @{b}Ananke@{ub} [a-NANG-kee] is a small moonlet, 28 km in diameter.It moves in
      a @{i}retrograde@{ui} direction, and is acompanied by a flock of debris.Debri
      moonlets are the remnants of a mighty collision that shattered some
      larger asteroid into pieces.Ananke is just the largest of the chunks.
      They all revolve around Jupiter now, and are spiralling toward it.
        Ananke and Zeus were the parents of @{i}Adrastea@{ui}.
 ** @{b}Carme@{ub} [KAR-mee] is a small moonlet, some 46 km in diameter.It moves in
      a @{i}retrograde@{ui} direction, and is acompanied by a flock of debris.Debri
      moonlets are the remnants of a mighty collision that shattered some
      larger asteroid into pieces.Carme is just the largest of the chunks.
      They all revolve around Jupiter now, and are spiralling toward it.
        Carme and Zeus were the parents of @{i}Britomartis@{ui}, a Cretan goddess.
 ** @{b}Pasiphae@{ub} [pah-SIF-ah-ee] is a small moon, 58 km in diameter.It moves in
      a @{i}retrograde@{ui} direction, and is acompanied by a flock of debris.Debri
      moonlets are the remnants of a mighty collision that shattered some
      larger asteroid into pieces.Pasiphae is just the largest of the chunks.
      They all revolve around Jupiter now, and are spiralling toward it.
    @{b}Sinope@{ub} [sah-NOH-pee] is a small moonlet, a member of the @{i}Pasiphae@{ui} group.

 **   @{i}Ananke, Carme@{ui}, and @{i}Pasiphae@{ui} all have similar orbital parameters,
    indicating that they were possibly a single body once, disrupted by an
    impact.The collision must have happened long ago, because each of them
    has later been broken into ever smaller pieces by subsequent impacts.
    Each of them now has it's own group of extremely small moonlets, that
    has resulted from subsequent disruption.
      All 3 groups move in a @{i}retrograde@{ui} direction on a very large distances
    of 21.2 Gm (Ananke), 23.4 Gm (Carme) and 23.6 Gm (Pasiphae), indicating
    that the original satellite was a captured asteroid.Their inclinations
    and eccentricities also corelate with each others.
      Most (almost all) of the newly found moonlets belong to these 3 groups.

  @{b}@{u}Chronology of Jovian exploratino@{uu}@{ub}:
  1. @{b}Pioneer 10@{ub} - USA Jupiter Flyby - 259 kg, launched on 3rd Mar 1972.
     Pioneer 10 flew by Jupiter on 1st Dec 1973.It returned over 500
     pictures of Jupiter and its moons.Its greatest achievement was the
     data collected on Jovian magnetic field and solar wind interactions.
     Pioneer 10 crossed the orbit of Pluto on 13th Jun 1983, and left the
     solar system by now.

  2. @{b}Pioneer 11@{ub} - USA Jupiter/Saturn Flyby - 259 kg, launched on 6th Apr 1973.
     Pioneer 11 flew by Jupiter on 1st Dec 1974, and returned better
     pictures than Pioneer 10.It has used Jupiter's gravity field as an
     assistance to get to the Saturn, which it reached on 1st Dec 1979.
     It has now left the solar system.

  3. @{i}@{b}Voyager 1@{ub}@{ui} - USA Jupiter/Saturn Flyby - 800 kg, launched on 5th Sep 1977.
     Voyager 1 flew by Jupiter on 5 Mar 1979, and Saturn on 12th Nov 1980.It
     discovered the ring system around the planet.

  4. @{i}@{b}Voyager 2@{ub}@{ui} - USA Jupiter/Saturn/Uranus/Neptune Flyby - 800 kg, launched
     on 20th Aug 1977, 2 weeks before Voyager 1.
     Voyager 2 flew by Jupiter on 9th Jul 1979, Saturn on 26th Aug 1981,
     Uranus on 24 Jan 1986, and Neptune on 24 Aug 1989.
     This is the only spacecraft that has visited the outer gas giants and
     we owe to this piece of equipment much of the knowledge that we have
     about them.In a unique cosmic dance, it subsequently used the gravity
     assistance of gas giants to swong itself to succeeding destinations.

     Both ships are now on the route to the end of solar system, and are
     searching for the boundary of the solar wind.They will continue to
     send data about interstellar space until they nuclear power supplies
     run out, some 10 years from 2003. (The power is generated from the
     heat coming from the radioactive decay of @{i}plutonium dioxide@{ui}, PuO2.)
     @{FG shine}NEWS@{FG text}: In November 2003 Voyager 1 has encountered what it seems to be
     the edge of the @{"termination shock" link ASENSE-PLANETS-SUN 60}, at 93.6 AU away from the Sun.
     Currently (May 2004), the Voyager 1 is 95 AU away, and is moving at
     the speed of 3.6 AU/yr. Meanwhile, the Voyager 2 is 72 AU away, and
     is distancing at the lesser speed of 3.3 AU/yr.

  5. @{b}Ulysses@{ub} - USA/ESA Sun Flyby - 370, launched on 6th Oct of 1990.
     Ulysses used Jupiter's gravity field on 8th Feb 1992 as an assistance
     to get above the plane of ecliptic to be able to study Sun's poles.

  6. @{i}@{b}Galileo@{ub}@{ui} - USA/ESA Jupiter Orbiter/Atmospheric Probe - 2,322 kg, launched
     on 18th Oct 1989.
     Galileo is a long term mission, designed to explore the Jovian system
     for 2 years.In order to get to the Jupiter, it used gravity assistance
     of Venus on 10th Feb 1990, Earth on 8th Dec 1990 and 8th Dec 1992.It has
     encountered asteroids Gaspra on 29th Oct 1991 and Ida on 28th Aug 1993.
     The Probe was sent to the Jupiter's atmosphere to study it until its
     destruction by pressure.

  -- @{i}@{b}Hubble Space Telescope@{ub}@{ui} (HST) - USA/ESA Telescope, launched on 25th Apr 1990
     HST observed the Jupiter in Jul 1994 to obtain pictures of the collision
     of fragments of the Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9 with the planet.

  @{b}@{u}Properties of Jupiter@{uu}@{ub}:
              mass: 1.908e27 kg (317.94 Earth's)
     equ. diameter: 142.984 Mm (11.209 Earth's)
    polar diameter:
    orbital period: 4332.71 d (11.86 yr)
         semi-axis: 5.2028 AU
       inclination: 1.308°
      eccentricity: 0.0483
     mean velocity: 13.07 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.52 (0 = black, 1 = white)
       rot. period: 9h55m30s (0.41354 d)
              tilt: 3.13°
       nr of rings: 5 rings
       nr of moons: 63 (4 big, 2 medium, 10 small, 47 midget ones (< 10 km))
           density: 1.33 g/cm^3
                 T: 152 K
           gravity: 22.08 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 59.56 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: -2.70 V
  atm. composition: 89% H, 11% He by volume, 75% H, 25% He by mass

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically: Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: Rulership, big, patron, bank, church, hierarchy,
    institution, order, money, carier, growth, size, plenty, abundance,
    capitalism, layer, government, patriarchal, thunder.
    Jupiter has rulership over the (northern) autumn sign of @{b}Sagittarius@{ub}.

  @{b}@{u}Mythologically@{uu}@{ub}: Jupiter was a supreme Roman deity (Greek's @{i}Zeus@{ui}).
@endnode
///
///   Saturn                                              //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-SATURN "ASense - Planets: Saturn"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-JUPITER
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-URANUS
@{b}@{u}Saturn@{uu}@{ub}: Ringed gas giant.

    Saturn is the second largest gas giant in the solar system and the only
  one with easily visible @{b}complicated ring system@{ub}.Saturn is easily visible
  from the Earth, thus it was known since prehistoric times.The ring system
  has been discovered by @{b}Galileo@{ub} in 1610, soon after he discovered 4 big
  moons of Jupiter.Galileo was fascinated with rings, but also very confused.

    The geometry of rings was finally infered in 1659 by @{b}Christian Huygens@{ub}.
  Until the discovery of rings around Uranus in 1977, it was thought that
  the Saturn was the only planet with rings.Earth passes through the plane
  of rings every few years.

    3 of the rings are visible from the Earth, but Voyagers revealed an
  @{i}astonishingly complex ring system@{ui}.There are gaps, eccentric ringlets,
  clumps, spokes, twisted strands and small satellites that shepperd the
  material contained in rings, thus constantly changing their shape and
  density as they all revolve around Saturn.
    Rings were made of dust and ice debris, with various sizes present,
  ranging from microscopic ones to those of several km in diameter.The
  latter ones are of course much rarer, and are shepperding the rings.
  Curiously, @{b}all the material contained within the rings would barely be
  able to make a single body of 200 km in diameter if clumped together@{ub}.
  Their combined mass is estimated to be only 3.5e19 kg, which is less
  than the mass of @{i}Mimas@{ui}, a small Saturn's rings shepparding moon.
    The rings are 270 Mm wide, but less than a km thick.@{i}@{b}Unlike the rings
  of other gas giants, the particles that make the Saturn's rings contain
  a lot of water ice and thus have more reflective power@{ub}@{ui}.Their albedo ranges
  from 0.2 to 0.6, which makes the rings very bright in their appearance.

    Saturn's atmosphere is almost entirely made of H (93%) and He (7%).It
  contains less He than Jupiter (which has 11%), possibly because that the
  heavier He has sunk down.The gravity contraction coupled with a decay of
  radioactive elements are making the planet to @{i}radiate more energy than it
  receives from the Sun@{ui}.
    @{b}Saturn is the least dense of all the planets in the solar system, and@{ub}
  also the only one which is less dense than water (some 30% less), and it
  is @{b}also the fastest rotator@{ub}.Saturn's day is only 10h 39m 24s long.
    @{i}@{b}Rapid rotation makes it oblate by almost 10%@{ub}@{ui}.

    Saturn appears to be in a very fluid state, because of light weight and
  fast rotation.The @{i}winds@{ui} on the planet are very strong.Wind velocities of
  1,800 km/h were recorded near the equator, and they fall off uniformly
  with increasing latitudes.On the equator winds blow mostly in the eastern
  direction, while on the latitudes larger than 35° they start to alternate
  more between east and west directions.There are less color contrasts in
  the atmosphere than on Jupiter, maybe because the high speed winds create
  more horizontal mixing.Long lived ovals exist, but are generally smaller
  than on Jupiter.
    @{i}@{b}Winds show a striking level of symmetry between two hemispheres@{ub}@{ui}.This,
  and the fact that they mostly blow eastward, indicates that @{i}they are not
  confined to the cloud layer, but must extend inward at least 2,000 km@{ui}.
  Some scientists suggest that they may even blow through the interior of
  the planet as liquid streams because of it's high fluidity.
    Convecting and conducting liquid layers certainly exist and go deep
  below the surface, because @{b}the magnetic poles almost coincide with the
  poles of rotation.They are inclined less than 1°, which is the smallest
  inclination in the solar system@{ub}.
    The interior is thought to resemble that of Jupiter, with a small core
  and a large liquid hydrogen envelope, followed by an atmosphere of again
  mostly hydrogen.Saturn has a size similar to that of Jupiter, but less
  than a third of it's mass.

    @{i}@{b}The magnetosphere@{ub}@{ui} of Saturn @{i}@{b}is exposed@{ub}@{ui} not only to solar wind, but
  also @{i}@{b}to the Jupiter's magnetotail from time to time when they align.
  When this happens, the kilometric radio emissions from Saturn cease@{ub}@{ui}.
  Auroras at high latitudes were detected (as expected), but also @{i}some
  aurora-like UV emissions of hydrogen at mid-latitudes only in sunlit
  regions, which is puzzling@{ui}.
    There are toruses of H+ and O+ ions in the magnetosphere at about
  400 Mm originating from water ice sputtered from the surfaces of
  Dione and Tethys.@{b}Strong plasma-wave emissions are associated with
  the inner torus, where the ions are being accelerated to very high
  velocities.In terms of temperatures, they corespond to 400..500 MK@{ub} !
    Outside the inner torus there is a @{i}thick sheet of plasma@{ui} extending
  to about 1 Gm.Sources of material in that sheet is probably Saturn's
  ionosphere, Titan's atmosphere and a @{i}torus of neutral hydrogen@{ui} that
  surrounds Titan between 0.5 and 1.5 Gm.
    On high solar wind pressure, the Saturn's magnetosphere extends
  only 1.1 Gm in the Sun's direction.

    Minimal temperatures of 82 K were measured at 70 mbar pressure level,
  and they steadily increased to 143 K at 1,200 mbar, which was the deepest
  level probed.Near the poles the temperatures were about 10° cooler, but
  the difference is probably seasonal.In core, temperatures reach 12 kK.

    So far Saturn has been visited by 3 spacecrafts: @{b}Pioneer 11@{ub} (1979),
  @{b}Voyagers 1@{ub} (Nov 1980), and @{b}Voyager 2@{ub} (Aug 1981).A fourth one, @{b}Cassini@{ub},
  launched on 15th Oct 1997, is on it's way and will arrive on the scene
  on 1st Jul 2004.Cassini's main target is to explore the Saturn's largest
  moon @{b}Titan@{ub}, which is the only moon in the solar system equiped with a
  dense atmosphere.
  @{FG shine}UPDATE@{FG text} (jul 2004):Cassini has arrived successfuly and already discovered
  that @{b}Saturn's period of rotation@{ub} (as measured by the rotation of it's
  magnetic field) @{b}has @{i}decreased@{ui} 6 min since the visits by Voyagers@{ub}, more
  than 2 decades ago.

  @{b}@{u}The moons of Saturn@{uu}@{ub}:
    Saturn has a regular system of moons.The moon count is 31 (so far).
    There are also 3 unconfirmed moons that were spotted only once.One
    of them @{i}orbits around Dione@{ui}, one is between Tethys and Dione, and
    one between Dione and Rhea.

    Most of the moons have lower densities, indicating that they are
    composed with little rocky material, and a lot of water ice.@{i}Titan@{ui},
    and to some extent @{i}Dione@{ui}, are the exceptions.Several moonlets were
    estimated to have very low densities, but that is still doubtful.
    Moons outside the rings are less reflective, with lower albedos.

    @{b}Regular moons all have low eccentricities and move in equatorial
    plane of Saturn@{ub}.Irregular moons are captured asteroids and comets
    that orbit further away from Saturn.Many of them revolve in a
    retrograde direction and are spiraling toward Saturn.@{i}Phoebe is
    the only one moon that hasn't yet synchronised its orbital and
    rotational periods@{ui}.It's rotational period is about 9 hours.All of
    the irregular moons have low albedos, indicating rocky composition.

    @{i}@{b}Hyperion@{ub}  is locked in a 4:3 orbital resonance with @{b}Titan@{ub}.
    @{b}Enceladus@{ub} is locked in a 1:2 orbital resonance with @{b}Dione@{ub}.
    @{b}Mimas@{ub}     is locked in a 1:2 orbital resonance with @{b}Tethys@{ub}@{ui}.

