    Iapetus                    3561300 7.570 0.0283 79.33018 10.2-11.9 1436 ± 8    1.253±.168 0.2 / 0.6  1671 Giovanni Cassini    1880     0.586       S
   @{b} Irregular Satellites@{ub}
    Kiviuq                    11365000 46.16 0.334  449.2    22.0R     16          2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Ijiraq                    11440000 46.74 0.322  451.5    22.6R     12          2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Phoebe                    12952000 174.8 0.1633 -550.48  16.4      230×220×210 1.3±0.7    0.081±.002 1898 William Pickering      4.00  0.0697     0.4
    Paaliaq                   15199000 45.13 0.364  686.9    21.3R     22          2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Skadi                     15647000 152.7 0.270  -728.9   23.6R     8           2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Albiorix                  16404000 33.98 0.478  783.5    20.5R     32          2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Erriapo                   17616000 34.45 0.474  871.9    23.0R     10          2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Siarnaq                   18160000 45.56 0.295  893.1    20.1R     40          2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Tarvos                    18247000 33.51 0.536  925.6    22.1R     15          2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Mundilfari                18709000 167.5 0.208  -951.4   23.8R     7           2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    S/2003 S1                 18719000 134.6 0.352  -956.2   24.0      7           2.3        0.04       2003
    Suttung                   19463000 175.8 0.114  -1016.   23.9R     7           2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Thrym                     20382000 175.8 0.470  -1086.   23.9R     7           2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman
    Ymir                      23096000 173.1 0.333  -1312.   21.7R     18          2.3        0.06       2000 B. Gladman

  @{b}Pan@{ub} is the innermost satellite of Saturn.An iceberg actually, 20 km in
    diameter.@{i}It is a shepperding satellite which keeps the Encke gap open@{ui}.
  @{b}Atlas@{ub} is a small moonlet, few times larger than Pan.@{i}It is a shepperding
    satellite for Saturn's A-ring@{ui}.

  @{b}Prometheus@{ub} [pra-MEE-thee-us] is a small moon that @{i}acts as a shepperding
    satellite for the inner edge of Saturn's F-ring@{ui}.The moon is too small
    to be round, and thus it has a very extended, irregular shape.Several
    craters about 20 km in size are visible.It has a number of ridges and
    valleys on it's northern side.The density of Prometheus is estimated
    to be quite low, indicating that it is a porous, icy body.The value
    is quite uncertain, though.
  @{b}Pandora@{ub} [pan-DOR-uh] is a small moon,similar to Prometheus, that @{i}acts
    as a shepperding satellite for the outer edge of Saturn's F-ring@{ui}.It
    is very heavily cratered, with two largest craters having sizes of
    38 km in diameter.There are no linear valleys and ridges, but the
    available data is very limited.Pandora is estimated to have quite
    low density level like the Prometheus, but this is quite uncertain.

  @{b}Epimetheus@{ub} [ep-eh-MEE-thee-us] is an irregularly shaped small moon,
    traversed by several large and small grooves, valleys and ridges.
    There are several craters larger than 30 km in diameter, which is
    an indication of an old surface.It @{i}is a shepparding satellite@{ui}.
    @{i}Mythologically@{ui}, Epimetheus was the son of Iapetus and brother to
    Prometheus and Atlas.In greek, it's name means '@{i}hindsight@{ui}'.
      @{b}Epimetheus shares the same orbit with @{i}Janus@{ui}, a somewhat larger
    Saturn's moon.They are not Trojans, but instead when they approach
    each other they exchange a little angular momentum and trade their
    orbits.The outer satellite becomes the inner one and vice versa.
    This exchange happens about once every four years, and this feature
    is unique one in the solar system, at least with the known large
    objects, like moons.A distance between their orbits is only 50 km@{ub}.
      Epimetheus and Janus may have formed from a disruption of a single
    body to form co-orbital satellites.If this is the case, it must have
    happened early in the history of the satellite system, since both
    bodies are heavily cratered, and the cratering must have occured
    after the disruption.The craters would have been erased otherwise.
  @{b}Janus@{ub} [JAY-nus] is an irregularly shaped small monn, somewhat larger
    than Epimetheus, it's co-orbiting companion.Just like Epimetheus,
    it is a heavily cratered moon, with several craters larger than
    30 km in diameter.It has few linear features.@{i}Mythologically@{ui}, @{b}Janus
    was the god of @{i}gates@{ui} and @{i}doorways@{ui}, depicted with @{i}two faces looking
    in the opposite directions@{ui}@{ub}.The name suits the satellite very well.
    (@{i}Please read the last 2 paragraphs about the Epimetheus as well@{ui}.)

  @{b}Mimas@{ub} [MY-mass] is @{i}one of the ring shepparding satellites@{ui} of Saturn,
    barely large enough to be round (diameter 397 km).It's low density
    indicates that it is @{b}composed mostly of water ice@{ub}.Mean surface
    temperature is 73 K.@{i}At that temperature, the water ice is strong
    as steel@{ui}, which means that the terrain is deformation resistant.
      Mimas is a @{i}heavily cratered@{ui} moon, which mean that it's surface
    is quite old.Most of the surface is covered with craters larger
    than 40 km in diameter except for the south pole region, which
    lacks craters larger than 20 km in diameter.This indicates that
    some process has erased the larger old craters from that area.
      One of the craters, named @{i}Herschel@{ui}, is exceptionally large in
    comparison with the size of the moon.It's diameter is 130 km,
    which is one third of the diameter of Mimas.Herschel is 10 km
    deep, with a central peek rising 6 km above the crater's floor.
    This impact almost disintegrated the moon, and the traces of it
    can be seen on the opposite side of Mimas.To corelate with the
    story, @{i}mythologically, Mimas was a Titan slained by Hercules@{ui}.

  @{b}Enceladus@{ub} [en-SELL-ah-dus] is a small moon, not much bigger than Mimas,
    but a very bright one.It's smooth icy surface @{b}reflects almost 100% of
    the light that strikes it, just like if it is a mirror@{ub}.@{i}@{b}This is perhaps
    the most reflective body in the solar system@{ub}@{ui}, and certainly a moon
    with the highest albedo.Because of high reflection, temperature on
    the surface is only 72 K.
      Enceladus displays at least 5 different types of terrain.It has no
    craters larger than 35 km in diameter, and there are regions with no
    craters at all.There are @{i}fissures, plains, corrugated terrain@{ui} and
    other @{i}crustal deformations@{ui}.All of these indicate a very young surface,
    with @{i}@{b}the interior of the moon perhaps still liquid today, although it
    should have been frozen long time ago@{ub}@{ui}.The cause of this state may be
    @{i}tidal heating@{ui}, generated by perturbations by Saturn, Tethys and Dione.
      Enceladus is @{i}one of the shepperding satellites@{ui} of the rings.It's
    presence in the middle of the rings makes it exposed to @{i}@{b}micrometeoric
    bombardment by ring particles, which are mainly water ice@{ub}@{ui}.These @{i}@{b}tend
    to erode the old terrain and make it smooth, since the ice melts on
    impact and then quickly freezes again, making the surface smoother@{ub}@{ui}.
    High albedo is thus a characteristic of all moons within the rings.
    Enceladus just happens to be located in the very center of the rings,
    and is thus the most exposed one to their @{i}ice-polishing@{ui} influence.

  @{b}Tethys@{ub} [TEE-this] is an icy body similar to Dione and Rhea.Density of
    Tethys is 0.99, indicating that it is @{b}composed mostly of water ice@{ub}.
    It's surface is @{i}heavily cratered@{ui}, and contains many cracks in the
    ice.There is also a lightly cratered dark belt across the satellite.
    Light cratering indicates some internal activity in the past that
    has erased the old craters.The origin of a dark belt is unknown.
    One possible explanation is that the moon consists of hazy polar
    caps of unresolved bright ice patches with a darker zone between.

      Tethys has an enormous trench named @{i}Ithaca Chasma@{ui}, 65 km wide
    and several km deep, which @{i}covers 75% of Tethys's circumference@{ui}.
    It indicates that @{b}the moon was once liquid.A crust has hardened
    first, and when the interior started to freeze, it expanded and
    broke the overlaying envelope@{ub}.This indicates that a core mainly
    consists of water ice, which expands on lowering temperatures.
      One more prominent feature is the giant crater named @{i}Odysseus@{ui},
    400 km in diameter.It spans two thirds of a satellite.
      Mean surface temperature on Tethys is 86 K.

  @{b}Telesto@{ub} is a @{i}leading Trojan satellite of Tethys@{ui}, and
  @{b}Calypso@{ub} is a @{i}trailing one@{ui}.They both are a very small moonlets.

  @{b}Dione@{ub} [dy-OH-nee] is an icy monn, similar to Tethys and Rhea.It is the
    second densest among the Saturn's moons (density 1.43 g/cm^3), after
    Titan.It probably has a rocky core containing about one third of it's
    mass, and the rest being the water ice.There is a smaller percentage
    of ice on Dione, than on other moons of Saturn.Thus, it has a higher
    density.The surface gravity on Dione is 0.223 m/s^2 (Earth has 9.81).
      The trailing hemisphere contains most of the heavily cratered areas,
    with many craters larger than 100 km in diameter, while the leading
    hemisphere consists mainly of moderately cratered plains, with craters
    of less than 30 km in diameter.This is opposite from what is expected.
    It suggests that during the period of heavy bombardment, Dione was
    tidally locked in the opposite orientation.However, any impact that
    has created a crater larger than 35 km could have spun the satellite,
    giving it's relatively small size.Given the number of large craters
    present on it's surface, Dione has probably been repeatedly spun.
      The average albedo on the leading hemisphere is higher than that
    on the trailing side.This suggest a prolonged exposure to micrometeor
    dusting of the leading hemisphere, which means that Dione has been in
    it's current orientation for quite a while, possibly for a few Gyr.
      There are also traces of bright wispy material on the surface with
    obscure origin.This material has a high albedo, but is thin enough
    not to obscure the surface features lying below.It might have formed
    from eruptions along cracks in Dione's surface that fell back to the
    surface as snow or ash.Mean surface temperature on Dione is 87 K.

  @{b}Helene@{ub}, the other Saturn's moon (only 32 km in diameter), is a @{i}leading
    Trojan satellite of Dione@{ui}.It means that it orbits the Saturn on the
    same distance and with the same orbital period as Dione does, but 60°
    in front of Dione.

  @{b}Rhea@{ub} [REE-a] is the second largest Saturn's satellite, similar to Dione
    and Tethys.It @{b}consists mainly of water ice@{ub}, with a small rocky core in
    the middle.The core takes up less than a third of the moon's mass.
    On the sunlit side, the mean temperature is 99 K, while on a dark side
    it fells to about 53 K.This is similar situation as on Dione and Tethys.
    Albedo and terrain features also resemble that of Dione and Tethys.
      Rhea is a @{i}heavily cratered@{ui} moon, with bright wispy markings like
    on Dione, probably with same origin.Rhea's surface can be divided
    into two geologically different areas based on craters density.The
    first area contains craters which are larger than 40 km in diameter.
    The second area has craters under 40 km in diameter.This suggests
    that some event has erased the larger and older craters from the
    second area (parts of polar and equatorial regions).

  @{b}Titan@{ub} is the largest of Saturn's satellites, and the second largest moon
    in the solar system (the largest is one @{i}Ganymede@{ui}, a moon of Jupiter).
    It @{i}@{b}is bigger than Mercury, and it is the only moon that has a thick
    atmosphere@{ub}@{ui}.It has no magnetic field of it's own, and thus it has no
    convection in the core.No wander, since it has synchronised it's
    orbital and rotational periods long ago.

      The atmosphere on Titan is going to be intensively researched by
    the @{i}@{b}Cassini@{ub}@{ui} spacecraft, starting from the 1st Jul 2004.It is important
    because the composition and chemistry of Titan's atmosphere may be
    similar to conditions that occured in primeval Earth's atmosphere.

      @{b}The atmosphere is thick and opaque@{ub}.A dense photochemical haze blocks
    the view.@{i}@{b}It's main layer lies 300 km above surface, but there are also
    several distinct, detached haze layers above the opaque one@{ub}@{ui}.They all
    merge near the north pole of Titan, forming a dark ring around it, that
    looks like a dark hood.It was early autumn on the south hemisphere when
    the Voyagers arrived, hence it was slightly warmer than the north one.
    @{i}The atmosphere is mostly nitrogen molecules@{ui}, just as it is on Earth.

      Atmospheric pressure on the surface is about 1.6 bar, 60% more than
    on Earth, and @{b}the temperature is about 95 K, which is only 4 K above
    the triple-point temperature of methane (CH4)@{ub}.However, CH4 appears to
    be below it's saturation pressure near the surface, so the rivers and
    lakes of CH4 probably do not exist.On the other hand, @{i}@{b}scientists think
    that lakes of ethane (C2H5) exist, and that CH4 is probably dissolved
    in ethane@{ub}@{ui}.

      Photochemistry in the atmosphere converts CH4 into @{i}ethane@{ui}, @{i}acetylene@{ui},
    @{i}ethylene@{ui} and @{i}hydrogen cyanide@{ui}.The last one mentioned is an especially
    important molecule, since it is a building block of amino acids, which
    are used to make proteins, a main constituent of life.Low temperature
    on Titan probably prevents more complex organic chemistry.

      @{i}Titan's atmosphere interacts with Saturn's magnetosphere to create a
    magnetic wake behind Titan@{ui}.It also serves as a source of hydrogen for
    the magnetosphere.

  @{b}Hyperion@{ub} [hi-PEER-ee-en] is @{b}the largest irregularly shaped satellite
    known@{ub}, although it is actually a rather small moon.It may have
    suffered a collision which blew away one part of the moon.It is
    also @{b}the only known object in the solar system that has a chaotic
    rotation@{ub}.Combined gravitational pulls of Saturn and it's moons
    (mainly of Titan) on the extended parts of Hyperion are able to set
    it's rotation into chaos.This means that @{i}the rotational period
    varies constantly and unpredictably@{ui} from one orbit to another.
    @{i}@{b}Hyperion's color is redder than Phoebe's and it closely matches
    the one found on a dark side of Iapetus@{ub}@{ui}.Perhaps they are related ?
      The largets crater on Hyperion has a diameter of approximately
    120 km.Compare that to the smal size of the moon, which is only
    370×280×226 km.@{b}Hyperion appears to have the oldest surface in the
    Saturnian system@{ub}.

  @{b}Iapetus@{ub} [eye-AP-i-tus] is a rather strange looking moon.@{i}@{b}It's leading
    side is dark and slighty reddish, while it's trailing side is bright@{ub}@{ui}.
    The real reason for this is unknown.
      Density of Iapetus is similar to that of Rhea, indicating that it
    has a small quantity of rocky material.Dark material might be a thin
    layer of organic substances, that may have been swept from space,
    or oozed up from the moon's interior.If it is thin, than it must
    be constantly replenishing.A meteor impact would be able to punch
    through the thin layer to reveal brighter material below, but
    there are no bright rimmed craters present on the dark hemisphere.
      Dark material may have originated from @{i}Phoebe@{ui}, which has a very
    low albedo (0.08).However, Phoebe has a slightly different color.
    On the other hand, dark material seems to be concentrated in crater
    floors, which would indicate an internal origin.Dark material may
    be an erupted methane from the interior.This theory is supported
    by the existance of a dark ring of material about 100 km in diameter
    that straddles the border between the leading and trailing hemispheres
    of Iapetus.Such rings form when volcanic material flow into impact
    crater and fills the landscape around the central peak.

  @{b}Phoebe@{ub} [FEE-bee] is a captured asteroid, one that orbits the Saturn
    in @{i}retrograde@{ui} direction on a plane much closer to the ecliptic,
    than to Saturn's equatorial plane.It has a roughly circular shape
    and a very low albedo (0.08).It @{b}is also quite red@{ub}.
      Unlike other monns of Saturn, @{i}it hasn't yet synchronised it's
    rotational and orbital periods@{ui}, which confirms it's status as a
    captured asteroid.It's rotational period is about 9h.
      Phoebe resembles the common class of @{i}carbonaceous asteroids@{ui}.
    These asteroids are chemically very primitive and contain the
    original solids of the solar nebula in unmodified form, since
    they have never been heated enough to alter their composition
    because of their small size.
      @{i}@{b}Phoebe is suspected to be the source of a dark material found
    on the leading side of Iapetus@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}@{u}Properties of Saturn@{uu}@{ub}:
              mass: 5.688e26 kg (95.181 Earth's)
     equ. diameter: 120.536 Mm (9.4494 Earth's)
    polar diameter: 108.728 Mm
   sidereal period: 29.458 yr (10759.5 d)
   tropical period: 29.424 yr (10747.94 d)
         semi-axis: 9.5388 AU
       inclination: 2.488°
      eccentricity: 0.0560
     mean velocity: 9.67 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.47 (0 = black, 1 = white)
       rot. period: 10h47m 6s ± 40 s (Cassini, May-2006)
              tilt: 25.33°
       nr of rings: 7 rings, 4 divisions, 1 gap
       nr of moons: 31 (1 big, 5 large, 3 medium, 22 small ones)
           density: 0.69 g/cm^3
                 T: 148 K
           gravity: 9.05 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 35.49 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: 0.67 V
  atm. composition: 93% H, 7% He (by nr of atoms)

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically: Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: Time, border, end, stone, soil, past, old, close,
    wisdom, knowledge, hardship, contract, chain, duty, common, agriculture,
    gray, support, grass, mineral, mountain, ridge, complex, problem, desert,
    slow, ash, crocodile, sorrow, matter, gravity, persistance, form, clay.
    Saturn has rulership over the (northern) winter sign of @{b}Capricorn@{ub}.
    (Note that the name of the sign of zodiac is '@{i}Capricorn@{ui}', while the name
    of the corresponding constellation is '@{i}Capricornus@{ui}'.)

  @{b}@{u}History@{uu}@{ub}: @{i}@{b}Saturnalia@{ub}@{ui} - a festival in ancient Rome lasting from 17th to
    24th Dec, a precursor of new year celebration.There was a custom to
    exchange presents, and slaves were temporarily given a great deal of
    freedom.Limitations of Roman Society were considerably eased during
    that period.It was a very popular holiday.

  @{b}@{u}Mythologically@{uu}@{ub}, Saturn was a Roman god of @{i}agriculture@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Uranus                                              //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-URANUS "ASense - Planets: Uranus"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-SATURN
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-NEPTUNE
@{b}@{u}Uranus@{uu}@{ub}: A tilted gas giant.

    Uranus has been discovered by @{b}William Herschel@{ub} on 13th Mar 1781.It
  was observed many times before, but ignored as just another star.
  @{b}John Flamsteed@{ub} labelled it @{b}34 Tau@{ub} in 1690, for example.

    Herschel called it '@{i}@{b}Georgium Sidus@{ub}@{ui}' (Georgian planet) to honor his
  patron King George III of England.Others simply called it '@{i}@{b}Herschel@{ub}@{ui}'.The
  name '@{i}@{b}Uranus@{ub}@{ui}' was proposed by @{b}Bode@{ub}, to make the planet line up with
  other planets, that already have their names originating in mythology.
  It wasn't until 1850 that this name became commonly used, though.

    Uranus is a gas giant, similar in size and composition to @{"Neptune" link ASENSE-PLANETS-NEPTUNE}.It is
  barely visible on a very clear and dark sky if one knows exactly where to
  look.The planet's main curiosity is that @{i}it is tilted about 97°, so that
  it's axis of rotation is almost parallel to the ecliptic@{ui}.Hence, Uranus's
  poles are subsequently directly exposed to the sunlight for several decades,
  as the planet slowly orbits around the Sun.This phenomenon creates some
  rather interesting seasonal weather changes.Winds at mid-latitudes blow
  in prograde direction, at speeds of 150..600 km/h (Earth has winds of
  ~180 km/h in the upper atmosphere).On the equator, however, the winds
  blow in retrograde direction.Speeds of 360 km/h were detected.

    Surprisingly, almost the entire planet (both lit and dark poles and the
  equatorial regions) show nearly the same temperatures below the tropopause
  (a border between the troposphere and the stratosphere).The exception is
  a somewhat cooler band between 15° and 40° latitude, with 2..3 K lower
  temperatures.Minimal temperature on Uranus is about 52 K and is measured
  near the tropopause.The temperature rises below to thousands of degrees
  in the interior, and above to about 150 K in the upper stratosphere.
    @{i}Average temperature on Uranus is about 60 K@{ui}.

    @{b}Sunlit atmosphere radiates large amounts of UV light@{ub}, a phenomenon that
  is called a '@{i}dayglow@{ui}'.

    The atmosphere is composed of 83% H, 15% He and 2% methane (CH4).Methane
  in the upper stratosphere gives a distinctive blue color to the planet,
  because it absorbs the longer red wavelengths of the sunlight.The blue is
  what remains to be seen.
    @{b}The Uranus receives only 0.25..0.30% of the energy from the Sun that the
  Earth does@{ub}.Unlike other gas giants, the planet radiates @{i}less@{ui} heat than the
  amount that it receives from the Sun.

    @{b}There is a hypothesis that a tilt of the rotational axis is a result of a
  collision with some planet-sized body long ago@{ub}.Composition of the planet is
  similar to those of Jupiter and Saturn, but without liquid metallic hydrogen
  envelope.It seems that the material is more or less uniformly distributed
  within the planet, and that there seems to be no rocky core, or a very small
  one.Perhaps this is also a result of the assumed gigantic collision which
  tilted the planet's axis.

    Uranus has an odd @{i}@{b}off-centered magnetic field@{ub}@{ui}, tilted about 60° from the
  axis of rotation (12° on Earth).The origin of the field is always a motion
  of some liquid electro-conductor in the interior (liquid metallic hydrogen,
  magma, water).What exactly is the source in the case of Uranus is unknown.
    The strength of the field is roughly comparable to Earth's, though it
  varies a lot across the surface, because it originates in shallow depths.
    So far, Uranus has been visited by only one spacecraft: @{b}Voyager 2@{ub} in
  Jan 1986.During a time of it's arrival, Uranus's south pole was aiming
  directly toward the Sun.As a result of that, planet's rotation combined
  with the solar wind have twisted the planet's magnetosphere into a long
  @{i}corkscrew shape@{ui} extending to at least 10 Gm behind the planet.

    Voyager also found @{b}radiation belts@{ub} of similar intensity as those found
  on Saturn, although they differ in composition.@{i}@{b}On Uranus, the belts are
  dominated by hydrogen ions, without any trace of other heavier ions@{ub}@{ui}.
  The radiation is so intense, that it would quickly darken the surfaces
  of all objects orbiting in the vicinity of the planet.In 100,000 years
  or less, the methane trapped in the icy surfaces of inner moons and ring
  particles is being destroyed.Hydrogen escapes, leaving the dark layer of
  soot behind.This phenomenon explains their low albedos.

    @{b}Uranus has 11 known rings and ringlets@{ub}, all but the outermost thinner
  than 100 m and very dark (albedo 0.03).The outermost ring (epsilon) is
  gray in color, less than 150 m thick and composed of small ice boulders,
  measuring from few dm upto 30 meters across.This ring is 20..100 km wide.
    Uranus's other @{i}@{b}rings are very narrow, only few km wide, except for the
  innermost one, which has a span of 3000 km@{ub}@{ui}.Oddly, this one has only been
  discovered in 1986, since it is composed of very fine dust particles.A
  tenuous distribution of fine dust covers the entire ring system.
    The rings are spread in the area that is 38 to 51.14 Mm away from the
  planet's center (the Uranus's radius is 25.56 Mm), and there may be still
  some undetected rings or ring arcs, as narrow as 50 m.
    Small moonlets @{i}Cordelia@{ui} and @{i}Ophelia@{ui} are responsible for shepperding
  the rings, together with about 18 other such small satellites.
    The ring system itself is probably a remnant of a small moon that was
  broken by a collision or torn up by tidal forces.@{i}Smaller particles and
  dust are more frequent in the inner regions of the ring system because
  they are more affected by the atmospheric drag of Uranus's extended
  hydrogen atmosphere, which spirals them down@{ui}.

    @{b}Uranus has 27 so far discovered moons.5 of them are large enough to
  be round@{ub}, smashed into form by their own gravity, while the others are
  of irregular shape.@{b}9 of them are captured asteroids, orbiting at large
  distances in eccentric orbits@{ub}.The largest one in this group is @{i}Sycorax@{ui},
  measuring only 190 km in mean diameter.

    Large Uranian moons are ice-rock conglomerates, composed of about 50%
  of water ice, 30% rocks, and 20% carbon- and nitrogen-based materials.
  Dark gray colored surfaces are usually heavily cratered, but some of
  the moons also show strong evidence of internal tectonic activity.

  @{b}@{u}The moons of Uranus@{uu}@{ub}:

