       rot. period:-17h14m (retrograde rotation due to the tilt)
              tilt: 97.86°
       nr of rings: 9
       nr of moons: 27 (5 large ones)
           density: 1.29 g/cm^3
                 T: 80 K
           gravity: 7.77 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 21.30 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: 5.52 V
  atm. composition: 83% H, 15% He 2% CH4 (by volume)

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically: Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: CHANGE, revolution, alternating power, TV,
    difference, excentrism, sudden, electromagnetism, waves, technology,
    expert, university, altruism, future, outside, field, opportunity,
    new, open, vast, space, eternity, blue, solution.
    Uranus has rulership over the (northern) winter sign of @{b}Aquarius@{ub}.

  @{b}@{u}Mythology@{uu}@{ub}: Uranus was the Greek god of sky.He was the first son of Gaea,
    the Mother Earth, and also became her husband.Their children were the
    @{i}Titans@{ui} (6 sons (Oceanus, Coeus, Crius, Hyperion, Iapetus and Kronos),
    and 6 daughters (Theia, Rhea, Themis, Mnemosyne, Phoebe and Tethys)),
    3 @{i}Cyclopes@{ui} (Brontes, Steropes and Arges), 3 monsters @{i}Hecatonchires@{ui}
    (Briareus, Cottus and Gyes), who each had 100 hands and 50 heads, and
    @{i}Erinyes@{ui} (Furies), the spirits of punishment and goddesses of vengeance.
    Their offspring also includes the @{i}Giants@{ui}, @{i}Aphrodite@{ui} (Venus), @{i}Meliae@{ui}
    (Nymphs of the manna ash trees), and the @{i}island of Corfu@{ui}, the homeland
    of Phaeacians.He was dethroned by his son @{i}Kronos@{ui} (Saturn), who suffered
    the same fate from his son, Uranus's grandson, the @{i}Zeus@{ui} (Jupiter).
@endnode
///
///   Neptune                                             //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-NEPTUNE "ASense - Planets: Neptune"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-URANUS
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-PLUTO
@{b}@{u}Neptune@{uu}@{ub}: The outermost gas giant (the densest and the smallest of them).

    Neptune was discovered on 23rd Sep 1846 by @{b}Johann Gotfried Galle@{ub} of the
  Berlin Observatory and @{b}Louis d'Arrest@{ub}, an astronomy student.These 2 men
  were testing the mathematical predictions made by 2 other theoreticians:
  @{b}John Couch Adams@{ub} (an amateur astronomer) and @{b}Urbain Jean Joseph Le Verrier@{ub}
  (a french mathematician).The Adams predicted it in 1845, but was ignored
  at first.The search began when Le Verrier made his calculations, because
  of his reputation.A debate arose later between the France and England
  about who had to be credited for the Neptune's discovery.Adams and Le
  Verrier eventually met and became good friends, which ended a dispute.
    Orbit that they calculated diverge quickly from a real one, and only
  few years later, a search would have been futile.
    @{b}Galileo@{ub} observed it in 1613 with his telescope, but thought it was
  just another star.Cloudy weather prevented him to conclude otherwise.
  He was observing @{"Jupiter" link ASENSE-PLANETS-JUPITER} when he saw the Neptune for the first time.

    Several weather features, similar to those found on Jupiter, were
  detected.The largest one was a '@{i}@{b}Great Dark Spot@{ub}@{ui}', a hurricane as big as
  the Earth.Later observations have shown that it had vanished, but some
  others have appeared.The weather on Neptune isn't as stable as it is on
  Jupiter.(Jupiter's 'Great Red Spot' goes around for more than 300 yrs.)
  Cloud streaks that range from 50..200 km were observed by Voyager 2.
  They were casting their shadows on other clouds, some 50..100 km below.
    @{i}Neptune radiates twice as much energy as it receives from the Sun@{ui}.The
  heat comes from tidal effects originating from it's moon Triton, from
  decay of radioactive elements (mostly uranium) present in it's core and
  from Kelvin-Helmholtz mechanism of gravity compression.Temperatures in
  stratosphere were measured to be 750 K, while at 100 mbar pressure they
  were only 55 K.

    The movements within the mantle creates an @{i}@{b}off-center magnetic field@{ub}@{ui}.
  It's offset is at least 0.55 radii (about 13.5 Mm).The field is also
  @{b}highly tilted@{ub} (47°).The strength of this magnetic field varies from
  1 Gauss on equator to 0.1 Gauss on poles (Earth has 0.32 Gauss max).
  Because of the tilt, a dramatic changes occur, as Neptune rotates in
  the solar wind.@{i}@{b}Extremely complicated auroras@{ub}@{ui} occur over wide regions.
  Due to the much weaker solar radiation (only 3% of the amount that
  reaches Jupiter), the Neptune's auroras are also @{i}weak@{ui}, estimated to
  be about 50 MW.Compare this to 100 GW power of the Earth's auroras.

    @{i}@{b}Methane@{ub}@{ui} (CH4) gives the Neptune's clouds their blue color.It circles
  in the atmosphere in similar way as water does on Earth.The cycle goes
  like this:
    1. @{b}Solar UV light destroys CH4@{ub} high in atmosphere @{b}and makes@{ub} various
       @{b}carbohydrates@{ub}, such as ethane, acetylene and more complex polymers.
    2. Haze of these @{b}carbohydrate particles sink@{ub} down to cold stratosphere
       where they freeze @{b}to become ice@{ub}.
    3. @{b}Ice fall as snow into warmer troposphere, where it evaporates again@{ub}.
    4. The resulting @{b}carbohydrate gases mix with hydrogen@{ub} (more abundantly
       present in lower layers).Under higher pressure and temperature they
       react @{b}to form CH4 again@{ub}.
    5. Convective @{b}CH4 clouds rise again@{ub} to the top of stratosphere.
       Cycle completes.

    @{i}Neptune has the fastest blowing winds in the solar system@{ui} (2000 km/h).
  Once created, the winds never slow down, because the cold atmosphere on
  Neptune doesn't have enough energy to produce the braking turbulences.
  Curiosity is that they blow @{i}@{b}retrograde@{ub}@{ui} to the rotation of the planet.
  This is due to the tidal interactions with @{b}Triton@{ub}, Neptune's largest
  moon, which rotates in the retrograde direction around the planet.
  Retrograde rotation coupled with high orbital inclination, indicate that
  Triton is a captured body.An icy one, originating from the Kuiper-Belt.
  Consequently, it looses angular momentum and spirals swiftly towards
  the Neptune.As it does so, the tidal forces thrown upon it are getting
  increasingly stronger.The stretching is already large enough to create
  volcanism, melt ice and make an @{i}@{b}atmosphere@{ub}@{ui}, mostly of molecular nitrogen
  (N2) and methane (CH4).@{i}Erruptions of invisible nitrogen gas mixed with
  tiny dust particles were observed by Voyager 2@{ui}. Eventually, @{b}in about
  10..100 Myr, Triton will approach too close to the surface of Neptune,
  and the tides would thorn it apart, creating a MONUMENTAL ring system@{ub}.
    Triton has a density of 2.066 g/cm^3 and similar composition as the
  other Kuiper Belt Objects (KBOs).It closely resembles the Pluto.
    Triton is an ex-Kuiper Belt Object, captured by Neptune's gravity
  long time ago when it accidently ventured into inner solar system.
  Same thing happened to @{i}Centaur@{ui} family of asteroids.They wander around
  until they find their place, get ejected, evaporated like comets, get
  captured by some of the gas giants to become their moons or destroyed.
    Curiosity about Triton is that it is @{b}really large, larger than Pluto@{ub}.
  It's diameter is 2705 km, which makes it a 16th body in solar system
  when ordered by size.@{i}Note that if all material from Saturn's rings
  combine to form a single body, it would have less than 400 km in it's
  diameter.@{b}Triton is more than 300 times larger@{ub}@{ui}.
    Triton also has an @{i}extremely rare atmosphere@{ui} that originates from it's
  cryogenic volcanoes.It's about 800 km thick and composed of N2 and CH4.
  The atmospheric pressure is about 14 µbar, and @{b}the surface temperature
  is only about 38 K, which makes Triton the coldest body among all so far
  visited ones@{ub}.On the upper edge of the atmosphere, the temperature rises
  to about 95 K.Because of the ice cover, Triton's @{i}albedo@{ui} is high, ranging
  from 0.6 upto 0.95 (Earth has 0.30).This means that it is very bright
  object, reflecting 60..95% of light that strikes it.
    Icy terrain of Triton reminds the observer to other icy moons of the
  solar system: @{i}Ariel@{ui} (a satellite of Uranus), @{i}Enceladus@{ui} (a satellite of
  Saturn) and @{i}Europa@{ui} (the moon of Jupiter).
    Triton moves in a @{i}circular@{ui} orbit now.

    @{b}Neptune has 4 rings@{ub}, made from dusty particles.Rings are very faint
  and narrow.They originate from tiny meteorites that smash onto surface
  of Neptune's moons.High force of impact stems from high gravity field
  coupled with high magnetic field.Same phenomenon occurs on all gas
  giants, and they have rings that are constantly being replenished.

    Neptune has been visited by only one spacecraft so far: @{b}Voyager 2@{ub}
  in Aug 1989.

  @{b}@{u}Layers of Neptune@{uu}@{ub}:
    - @{i}rocky core@{ui} (Earth size)
    - @{i}mantle@{ui} (liquid) - rocks, H20, NH3, CH4 (10..15 Earth masses, 2/3 of diam.)
    - @{i}atmosphere@{ui} (gaseous) - 85% H, 13% He, 2% CH4, water         (1/3 of diam.)

  @{b}@{u}The moons of Neptune@{uu}@{ub}:

