    @{b}Naiad@{ub} and @{b}Thalassa@{ub} are irregularly shaped small rocky moons with no signs
      of geological modifications.They are the most inner of neptunian moons.
    @{b}Despina@{ub}, @{b}Galatea@{ub} and @{b}Larissa@{ub} are irregularly shaped rocky moons with no
      signs of geological modifications.

    @{b}Proteus@{ub} @{i}@{b}is as dark as soot@{ub}@{ui}, and reflects only 6% of the light that
    strikes it.Proteus is the second largest Neptune's moon, and it is
    @{i}@{b}just about as massive as a body can be without being pulled into
    spherical shape by it's own gravity force@{ub}@{ui}.

    @{b}Triton@{ub} is the largest moon of Neptune, and has already been discussed above.

    @{b}Nereid@{ub} is so far away, that it requires 360 days to make an orbit,
    almost as much as Earth does.@{i}@{b}It's orbit is the most eccentric in
    the solar system@{ub}@{ui}, ranging from 1,353.6 Mm to 9,623.7 Mm.It is a
    rocky moon, because it's albedo is only 0.14 (similar to Moon).

  @{b}@{u}Properties of Neptune@{uu}@{ub}:
              mass: 1.0247e26 kg (17.135 Earth's)
          diameter: 49.528 Mm (3.88 Earth's) (60 Earth's volumes)
    orbital period: 164.79 yr (60,190 d)
         semi-axis: 30.0611 AU
       inclination: 1.774°
      eccentricity: 0.0097
     mean velocity: 5.45 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.41 (0 = black, 1 = white)
       rot. period: 16h 6.7m
              tilt: 28.31°
       nr of rings: 4
       nr of moons: 13 (1 big, 3 medium, 9 small ones)
           density: 1.64 g/cm^3
                 T: 80..120 K
           gravity: 11.0 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 23.50 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: 7.84 V
  atm. composition: 85% H, 13% He 2% CH4 (by volume)

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically@{uu}@{ub}: Neptune represents (surprise, surprise) all sorts of
    @{i}liquids and volatile substances and processes@{ui}.It rules the sign of
    @{b}Pisces@{ub}.It is also connected with @{i}chemistry, socialism, religions
    and illusions@{ui}.
    @{b}@{u}Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: Water, mist, sea, river, lake, vast, fluid, chemistry, socialism,
      religion, illusion.

  @{b}@{u}Mythology@{uu}@{ub}: Neptune started as Roman god of @{i}rivers@{ui} and @{i}streams@{ui}, but got promoted
    to occupy the place of Poseidon, a Greek's god of @{i}sea@{ui} who was responsible
    for the bronze gates which imprisoned the Titans in their exile in the
    depth of Tartarus.(@{i}@{b}Note that the planet Neptune actually cleared away the
    cometary bodies from the outskirts of the solar system.Few remaining ones
    now reside in the Kuiper Belt.Neptune's moon Triton is the largest one of
    those objects, and the second largest is the Pluto-Charon double planet@{ub}@{ui}.)

@endnode
///
///   Pluto                                               //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-PLUTO "ASense - Planets: Pluto"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-NEPTUNE
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-ERIS
@{b}@{u}Pluto@{uu}@{ub}: The most distant known planet (until recently).

  UPDATE: As of 24-Aug-2006, the Pluto has lost the official @{"planetary" link ASENSE-SELECT-PL-DEF} status,
  and has been demoted to a newly established category of @{b}dwarf planets@{ub}, of
  which it is a prototype. It also received a MPC designation nr of @{b}134340@{ub}.

    Pluto was discovered in 1930 by @{b}Clyde W. Tombaugh@{ub} at Lowell observatory
  in Arizona.Tombaugh was conducting a research for a planet beyond Neptune,
  when he discovered Pluto.It was a fortunate accident, because calculations
  that predicted the existance of such a planet were in error, and the small
  Pluto was just at the right place on the right time.(@{i}If the correct mass
  of Neptune is used, as it was established by Voyager 2, than there are no
  more unknown large planets in our solar system.Neptune is the last one@{ui}.)

    The name @{i}Pluto@{ui} for the planet has been chosen among many suggestions,
  perhaps because @{b}PL@{ub} are the initials of @{b}Percival Lowell@{ub}, the founder of
  the Lowell observatory.Pluto is the Roman god of the @{i}underworld@{ui}, and
  the planet lies at the edge of interstellar darkness of outerspace.
  It circles at the end of our solar system.
    The name was originally suggested by @{b}Venetia Burney@{ub}, an 11-year-old
  schoolgirl from Oxford, England.She thought that a name of a Disney's
  character (A @{i}Mickey Mouse's dog@{ui} if anyone doesn't know) is a god one.

    There was a dispute of whether the Pluto is a planet at all, or just
  the largest one of the Kuiper-Belt Objects (KBOs).The Kuiper-Belt is a
  source of short term comets, so the Pluto may also be classified as a
  comet.A dispute has ended in favour of tradition, so the Pluto is still
  officially recognised as a planet, and it is likely that it will remain
  to be so.(Actually, Neptune's moon @{i}Triton@{ui} is the largest KBO, though a
  former one.)

    @{i}@{b}Pluto has the most eccentric orbit of all planets@{ub}@{ui} (e = 0.248), @{i}@{b}and also
  the most inclined one@{ub}@{ui} (i = 17.1°).It is usually the farthest planet, but
  due to the eccentricity of its orbit sometimes it isn't.@{b}From 21st Jan 1979
  untill 11th Feb 1999 it was closer to the Sun than the Neptune@{ub}.
    Although their orbits cross, Pluto and Neptune do not approach closer
  than 18 AU to each other, and thus they will never collide.Due to its high
  inclination, Pluto is either high above or high below the plane of ecliptic
  whenever it approaches it's perihelion.The planet has also synchronised its
  movement into 3:2 orbital resonance lock with Neptune, which means that its
  orbital period is exactly 1.5 times longer than the Neptune's.If it wasn't
  so, the Pluto would have been perturbed from it's orbit long time ago.
    From Pluto's surface, the Sun appears only as a very bright star.

    Just like Venus and Uranus, @{i}@{b}Pluto rotates in a retrograde direction@{ub}@{ui}.
  Moreover, the planet rotates with its poles almost in its orbital plane,
  similar to Uranus.(Pluto's rotational axis is tilted 122°.)
    When it was first discovered, it's relatively bright south polar region
  was pointing toward Earth.The planet dimmed as our viewpoint gradually
  shifted from nearly pole-on in 1954 to nearly equator-on in 1973.

    Pluto is the smallest one among the planets, but it is almost a @{i}double@{ui}
  planet.It has only one moon, @{b}Charon@{ub}, but it is so large, that it has benn
  able to tidally lock Pluto's rotation.@{b}Pluto is the only planet to travel
  in a synchronous orbit with it's moon@{ub}.Their mutual rotation period is
  6.387 days.It is thought that Charon has been created in a similar way
  like our Moon: as a residue of a gigantic collision.Pluto's rotational
  axis and Charon's orbit are highly inclined, as it can be expected from
  such a collision.A couple has the highest angular momentum in the solar
  system.Both Pluto and Charon are close to their stability thresholds.

    During the 1985-1990 period, Earth was aligned with the orbit of Charon.
  An eclipse could have been observed every Plutonian day.This provided an
  excellent opportunity for data collection, which has led to creation of
  albedo maps of the surfacess of both bodies and to accurate determinations
  of their sizes.The fact that this has happened during their perihelion
  approach to the Sun allowed more detailed observations due to (relative)
  proximity of the objects.
    First eclipses began by blocking the northern polar region, the later
  ones blocked the equator, and final ones blocked the view onto southern
  polar region of Pluto.Careful measurements of brightness over time led
  to determination of surface features.
    It was found that Pluto has a highly reflective south polar cap, a dimmer
  north one, and both bright and dark features in the equatorial region.The
  planet has an albedo ranging from 0.49 to 0.66, which is much brighter than
  Charon's (0.36 to 0.39).@{i}Pluto is the second most contrasting body in the
  solar system@{ui} (after Iapetus), which is a result of frosts migration due to
  orbital movement and seasonal changes, as well as to terrain configuration.
    A duration of an average eclipse was about four hours.Careful timing of
  their beginnings and endings yielded measurements of the diameters of both
  bodies.Recent direct observations by HST have reduced the errors of these
  measures to less than 1%.@{i}Pluto has a diameter of 2,274±16 km, and Charon's
  diameter is about 1,172 km, just over half the size of Pluto.Their average
  separation is 19,640 km, which is roughly 8 Pluto's diameters@{ui}.This is much
  closer than the Earth-Moon separation, by absolute and by relative figures.
    Average separation and orbital period are then used to calculate the
  masses of Pluto and Charon.It was found that the Pluto has a mass of about
  12.7 Et, which is 6.7 times more than Charon's, but only 0.0021 of Earth's
  mass.Pluto is much smaller than our Moon, and @{b}the entire Plutonian system
  has only fifth of the Monn's mass@{ub}.

    Pluto has an uncertain density of 1.8 to 2.1 g/cm^3, which indicates that
  it consists of 50-75% rocks, mixed with ices.On the other side, Charon has
  a density of only 1.2 to 1.3 g/cm^3, indicating that it contains very small
  quantity of rocks.Difference in density may indicate separate origins, but
  one must bare in mind that the Earth's Moon also has a lower density than
  the Earth.If Charon is a collision remnant, like Moon, than it may have
  been made from the outer portions of Pluto's envelope.This would imply that
  the Pluto's internals have been molten at some point and hot eough to allow
  some layering to take place.Charon's density has been derived from HST data,
  but the numbers are still being chalenged by the ground based observations.
  (@{i}Charon is bluer than the Pluto, indicating different surface composition@{ui}.)

    Icy Plutonian surface is made of 98% nitrogen (N2), some methane (CH4),
  and traces of carbon monoxide (CO).Solid CH4 indicates that Pluto is cooler
  than 70 K.Eccentricity of Pluto's orbit causes great variations of surface
  temperature between its perihelion at 30 AU and aphelion at 50 AU.When the
  system is close to the Sun, it is warm enough for an atmosphere to form from
  gases made of melting ices.@{i}A tenuous atmosphere has been detected during the
  Pluto-Charon eclipses examinations@{ui}.(Light has faded gradually, not sharply.)
  This atmosphere has a pressure of only 1 Pa, which is a 1/100,000th part of
  the Earth's surface atmospheric pressure.
    @{b}Neither Pluto, nor Charon are massive enough to hold the atmosphere into
  place.As soon it forms, it slowly floats away into space, leaving a light
  molecular tail behind the system, a very thin cometary tail@{ub}.Some of the
  moleculs from Charon, may end up on Pluto, because of its higher gravity.
  This might explain somewhat different surface composition.
    As the system goes away from the Sun, the temperature drops again, and
  the remains of flimsy atmosphere freeze and fall down as snow.They would
  remain in the form of ice until another Plutonian summer.(Plutonian year
  is 248.54 years long, but its summer lasts only a few @{i}decades@{ui} because of
  the high eccentricity of Plutonian orbit.)
    It is believed that surface temperatures on Pluto may fall to only 33 K
  during its winter, perhaps even more on its dark side that remains turned
  away from the Sun during Pluto's aphelion passage.At that time, Plutonian
  system is almost 50 AU away from the Sun, deep within the Kuiper-Belt.

    None of the spacecrafts have ever visited Pluto.Even HST has difficulties
  in resolving the surface features.
    @{b}Pluto Express@{ub} mission has been canceled because of NASA's budget cuts.
    @{b}New Horizons@{ub} mission is planned for launch in 2006 if it gets funded.

    Until a spacecraft is send, much of the system's properties would remain
  uncertain.

  @{b}Charon@{ub} [SHAR-on] is the only moon of Pluto, but the largest one in the solar
    system when compared with the size of its primary planet.It was discovered
    on 2nd Jul 1978 by @{b}James W. Christy@{ub}, a U.S. Naval Observatory scientist.
      Charon was named after a ferryman who rowed a boat across the river @{i}Styx@{ui},
    carrying the souls of the dead to @{b}Hades@{ub}, the underworld.Souls had to pay
    a coin for the service.
      Though officially named for the mythological figure, Charon's discoverer
    was also naming it in honour of his wife, @{b}Charlene@{ub}.Thus, those in the know
    pronounce it with first syllable sounding like '@{i}shard@{ui}' [SHAHR en].

      Prior to Charon's discovery it was thought that Pluto was much larger,
    since the images of the Plutonian system were blurred.The discovery came
    as a fortunate breakthrough in Pluto's exploration, because it occured
    just prior to a period of mutual occultations of Pluto and Charon that
    occured during 1985-1990.These occultations, as it was mentioned above,
    revealed a great number of details about the system that would otherwise
    remain unknown.(These eclipses occur only twice during a Plutonian year.)

      Unlike Pluto's, @{b}the Charon's surface seems to be covered with water ice@{ub}.
    Its low density indicates that it may be similar to Saturn's icy moon @{i}Rhea@{ui}.
    This is quite different from Pluto, and may imply their independent origin.
    Unlike Pluto, Charon does not have large albedo differences on its surface.
    It is doubtful that it has a significant atmosphere either.

      @{i}@{b}If Charon has been created by collision, large parts of both bodies have
    been melted during the event.Volatile chemicals like nitrogen and other
    gases were able to easily escape the Charon's loose gravity pull, leaving
    the heavier water behind to form the icy Charon's surface.
      Some of the escaping gases may have been recaptured by Pluto to form the
    upper layer of ice on its surface.Layering of ices on both bodies may thus
    be the result of gradual cooling after their creation@{ub}@{ui}.

    @{FG shine}NEWS@{FG text}: Recent observations by HST seem to indicate that the Pluto maybe
    has 3 moons (larger than 10 miles across).Their provisional names are
    S/2005 P1 and S/2005 P2.Both are some 44 Mm away from Pluto, which is
    more than twice the Charon's distance.They were discovered in Dec 2004.
    It is unlikely that the Pluto has any more moons larger than 10 miles.
    UPDATE: The moons were named Nyx and Hydra.

  @{b}Properties of@{ub}     @{b}@{u}Pluto@{uu}@{ub}:                        @{b}@{u}Charon@{uu}@{ub}:
        discoverer: Clyde W. Tombaugh             James W. Christy
 date of discovery: 18th Feb 1930                 2nd Jul 1978
              mass: 1.27e22 kg (0.002125 Earth's) 1.90e21 kg (0.0003188 Earth's)
     equ. diameter: 2,320±16 Mm (0.1819 Earth's)  1186±26 Mm (0.0919 Earth's)
   tropical period: 247.92 yr (90,550 d)          -6.38725 days
   sidereal period: 248.54 yr (90,777.3 d)
         semi-axis: 39.5294 AU                    19,410 km
       inclination: 17.148°                       99.089°
      eccentricity: 0.2482                        0.0002
     mean velocity: 4.74 km/s (orbital)           0.23 km/s (orbital)
            albedo: 0.55 (0 = black, 1 = white)   0.372±.012
       rot. period: -6.38725 days                 -6.38725 days
              tilt: 122.52°
       nr of rings: 0                             0
       nr of moons: 3 (1 large, 2 small)          0
           density: 2.06 g/cm^3                   1.853±.158 g/cm^3
                 T: 33 K
           gravity: 0.4 m/s^2 (equatorial)
   escape velocity: 1.22 km/s (equatorial)        0.610 km/s (equatorial)
         magnitude: 13.6 V                        17.26±.01 V
  atm. composition: N2, CH4, CO

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically: Keywords@{uu}@{ub}: Elementary, raw, pure, regeneration, recycling,
    mass production, many, unknown, energy, force, primitive, psychology,
    root, analysis, basement, physics, atom, core, nucleus, essence.
    Pluto has been assigned the rulership over the zodiacal sign of @{b}Scorpio@{ub}.
    (Note that the name of the sign of zodiac is '@{i}Scorpio@{ui}', while the name of
    the corresponding constellation is '@{i}Scorpius@{ui}'.)

  @{b}@{u}Mythologically@{uu}@{ub}: @{b}Pluto@{ub} is the Roman god of the @{i}underworld@{ui} (Greek's @{b}Hades@{ub}),
    or the underworld by itself.He was the son of @{i}Cronos@{ui} (Saturn) and @{i}Rhea@{ui}.
      @{b}Charon@{ub} is the ferryman who rows a boat across the river Styx, carrying
    souls to the Hades, a Pluto's (Hades's) realm of the underworld.Souls
    have to pay a coin for the service.
@endnode
///
///   Eris                                                //f
@node ASENSE-PLANETS-ERIS "ASense - Planets: Eris"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-PLUTO
@NEXT ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-CHIRON
@{b}@{u}Eris@{uu}@{ub} - The most inclined, recently discovered dwarf planet.

    @{b}Eris@{ub} is the second @{i}dwarf@{ui} planet in a sub category of objects of which
  @{"Pluto" link ASENSE-PLANETS-PLUTO} is the prototype. It has a comparatively large satellite, @{b}Dysnomia@{ub}.

  Note: These objects were provisionally named @{i}Xena@{ui} and @{i}Gabrielle@{ui} by their
  discoverers.These names are no longer valid. Please use the proper ones.
    @{i}Xena@{ui} is a warrior princess from a trivial TV serie, and @{i}Gabrielle@{ui} is
  Xena's fictional sidekick. (@{b}Astrological note@{ub}: @{i}the main actress playing
  Xena has the Sun in her natal chart conjuncting Eris@{ui}.)

    Provisionally designated 2003 UB313, this newly discovered dwarf planet
  received its official designation @{b}(136199) Eris@{ub} from the IAU on 13-Sep-2006.
    The name was proposed by @{i}@{b}Mike Brown@{ub}@{ui}, a member of the team that made
  its discovery, and accepted almost unanimously by the @{i}Working Group for
  Planetary System Nomenclature@{ui} (WGPSN) and the @{i}Committee for Small Body
  Nomenclature@{ui} (CSBN).
    Eris is pronounced ee -ris.
    Eris' moon, formerly known as S/2005 (2003 UB 313) 1, and now known
  technically as @{b}(136199) Eris I@{ub}, has been named @{b}Dysnomia@{ub}.

    First 3 images of Eris were taken on 21-Oct-2003 at the Palomar Obs.,
  in an ongoing survey by astronomers @{i}@{b}Mike Brown@{ub}@{ui} (Caltech), @{i}@{b}Chad Trujillo@{ub}@{ui}
  (Gemini Observatory), and @{i}@{b}David Rabinowitz@{ub}@{ui} (Yale University).However, due
  to the slow motion of Eris, the software that automatically analyzed the
  images failed to discover the planet.A special reanalysis for very distant
  objects was performed a year later, and that reanalysis found recognized
  Eris on @{b}11:20 AM PST, 5-Jan-2005@{ub}, (@{b}Palomar Observatory, San Diego, CA@{ub}).
  @{i}Discovery was hastily announced on @{b}29-Jul-2005 (Friday) at 4:00 PM@{ub}@{ui} (single
  best time to announce news that you want no one to hear about), because of
  the leak of their research data to the internet, 3 days earlier.@{i}Together
  with Eris, aanouncements of discoveries of two more large KBO were made@{ui}.
  (These were @{b}2003 EL61@{ub} and @{b}2005 FY9@{ub}, both about 3/4 of the Pluto's size.)
    The @{i}Dysnomia@{ui} was discovered on @{b}10-Sep-2005@{ub}.

    Preliminary observations indicate that @{b}Eris is as large as Triton@{ub}, the
  moon of Neptune, which is about 20% larger than Pluto.The HST will reveal
  more details after the observations scheduled for Nov-Dec 2005.The actual
  size depends on the reflectivity, which depends on the composition of the
  surface.The ice/rock combination is expected, but percentages may vary,
  as well as the types of ices involved (methane, ethane, nitrogen, water).
    The prelimianry diameter of Eris is estimated to be @{b}about 2400 km@{ub}, just
  like Triton's, @{b}while the Dysnomia, its moon, has a diameter of 250 km@{ub}.

    @{i}@{b}The color of the surface is gray@{ub}@{ui}, which is puzzling, since the other
  KBOs are mostly red in color (the Pluto is moderately red, Quaoar a bit
  more, while Sedna, the most distant of the known objects, is deeply red.)

    The orbit is very @{i}eccentric@{ui} (38..97 AU), with a 560 years period. @{b}The
  inclination is the largest known, 44°@{ub}.Currently, the object is in @{i}Cetus@{ui}.
  The details of the orbit are preliminary, and may change in the future.
    Currently, Eris is even further away from the Sun than Sedna, recently
  discovered planetoid from the inner Oort Cloud.This is because Sedna is
  now approaching it's perihel, while the Eris is almost at it's aphel.

    @{i}Dysnomia@{ui} is 100 times fainter than Eris (about 5 magnitudes), and has
  only one tenth of Eris's size.The orbital period is only few weeks long.

  @{b}Properties of@{ub}     @{b}@{u}Eris@{uu}@{ub}:                         @{b}@{u}Dysnomia@{uu}@{ub}:
       discoverers: Brown, Trujillo, Rabinovitz
 date of discovery: 5th Jan 2005, 11:20 AM PST    10th Sep 2005
                    Palomar Obs., San Diego, CA
              mass:
     equ. diameter: 2,400±?? Mm                   250±?? Mm
   tropical period: 560 yr
   sidereal period:
         semi-axis: 67.5 AU
       inclination: 44°
      eccentricity: 0.43
     mean velocity:
            albedo: 4th brightest KBO
       rot. period:
              tilt:
       nr of rings: 0                             0
       nr of moons: 1 (1 large)                   0
           density:
                 T:
           gravity:
   escape velocity:
         magnitude:
  atm. composition:

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically@{uu}@{ub}: Unknown, unstudied, recently discovered.
    Please read the following essay to learn more about Eris and other KBOs:
    - @{"Delineation" link ASENSE-PLANETS-DELINEATION} of the newly discovered planets and planetoids (essay).

  @{b}@{u}Mythologically@{uu}@{ub}: In Greek lore, @{b}Eris@{ub} is the goddess of @{i}@{b}discord@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}strife@{ub}@{ui}.
    She stirs up jealousy and envy to cause fighting and anger among men. At
    the wedding of @{i}Peleus@{ui} and @{i}Thetis@{ui}, the parents of the Greek hero @{i}Achilles@{ui},
    all the gods with the exception of Eris were invited, and, enraged at her
    exclusion, she spitefully caused a quarrel among the goddesses that led
    to the Trojan war. (Note that the discovery of Eris caused a quarrel among
    the astronomers about how to define the term 'planet'. At the end of this
    debate, on 24-Aug-2006, the Pluto lost his planetary status.)
      @{b}Dysnomia@{ub} is the @{i}@{b}Daimon spirit of lawlessness@{ub}@{ui}. She is the @{i}daughter@{ui} of Eris,
    goddess of @{i}@{b}chaos@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}strife@{ub}@{ui}, and the @{i}counterpart to @{b}Eunomia@{ub}@{ui} who puts an end
    to the anger of grievous strife.
@endnode
///
///   Chiron                                              //f
@node ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-CHIRON "ASense - Asteroids: Chiron"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@PREV ASENSE-PLANETS-ERIS
@NEXT ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS
@{b}@{u}Chiron@{uu}@{ub} - the first of the Centaurs and the largest of comets.

    Chiron is the first found @{i}Centaur@{ui}, discovered on 1 Nov 1977 on a photographic
  plate that was taken on 18 Oct 1977 by @{b}Charles Kowal@{ub}.The next one, @{i}Pholus@{ui},
  was found 15 years later, in 1992.
    Moreover, @{b}Chiron has a gas and dust coma with a diameter which sometimes
  reaches 2 Gm@{ub}.Both the size and the brightness of coma vary with time.@{i}@{b}The
  brightness can fluctuate by a factor of 4 over a period of only few hours@{ub}@{ui}.
  A gravitationally bound '@{i}dust atmosphere@{ui}' appears to exist in the inner
  1,200 km of coma, with an evidence of structure within the dust, which
  indicates a possibility of particle plumes emanating from the nucleus.
    Chiron was bright even when it was at it's aphelion distance, in 1970.
  Coma was detected in 1988, and its existance points that Chiron's surface
  contains @{b}super-volatile@{ub} substances, like methane (CH4), carbon-monoxide
  (CO), molecular nitrogen (N2) and other gas ices that are able to sublime
  at very low temperatures in order to produce a coma.@{i}@{b}At Chiron's current
  orbit these substances would completely vaporize in a few million years@{ub}@{ui}.
  The fact that the Chiron's surface is still active, coupled with the
  instability of its orbit indicated that it has moved relatively recently
  to it's current orbit from further away.@{i}Kuiper Belt@{ui} contains many objects
  of similar size and composition and @{i}is the most probable place of origin@{ui}.
    There are only several Centaurs that venture within the orbit of Saturn,
  and Chiron is the second largest among them.It is officially reclassified
  as a comet '@{b}95/P Chiron@{ub}' in 1995, because a @{i}faint coma@{ui} surrounding it and
  a @{i}short tail@{ui} have been detected.If Chiron ever gets perturbed to an orbit
  closer to the Sun, it would become a @{i}truly@{ui} magnificient comet, because @{b}it
  has 50,000 times more mass than the average comet@{ub}.(Note that @{i}Comet Halley
  has only about 1/10th of Chiron's diameter@{ui}.)
    @{i}@{b}The orbit of Chiron is unstable@{ub}@{ui}, which is also true for the orbits of
  other Centaurs and asteroids.@{i}@{b}Because of the close encounters with Saturn,
  the orbit of Chiron gets unpredictably perturbed in the years 650 and 4650.
  Thereafter, it cannot be computed outside of the 650 - 4650 time range@{ub}@{ui}.
  Last perihelion approach was on 14 Feb 1996, 18:06 UT, at 8.4639422 AU.

  @{b}Chiron astrologically@{ub}: Chiron is not a large body, but is considered to be
    a very important one from the astrological point of view.This is because
    it @{i}@{b}crosses the orbits of Saturn and Uranus, thus connecting them.If Saturn
    is the wall (astrologically), and the Uranus is the outer space (the sky)
    then Chiron is a window (or a door) between them, allowing an easy pass@{ub}@{ui}.
    @{b}ASense notes@{ub}: The other Centaurs do similar things, but Chiron is the only
    one among them, which is @{b}still an active comet@{ub} (and has an @{i}atmosphere@{ui}).
      Active comets have by far more prominence than their dead counterparts,
    the rocky (and icy) asteroids.And as a comet, Chiron is quite huge.These
    facts piled together are suggesting a @{b}greater importance and influence of
    this body in particular, than it can be attributed to the other members
    of asteroidal population@{ub}.
      Future observations, however, may show up that the Chiron is not the only
    one of its class, but it will certainly remain as the largest and therefore
    the most prominent one.

  @{b}Mythologically@{ub}: Chiron was the only one immortal among the Centaurs, the one
    that was dying from a wound, but couldn't die for a long time.The analogy
    is clear, and the name was well chosen.(@{i}Note that the choosing of a name
    was done prior to discovery of the Chiron's cometary nature@{ui}.)
      Chiron was named after a very special @{i}Centaur@{ui}, the only one that has
    been @{i}immortal@{ui} and civilized to a greater extent, the @{i}wisest@{ui} one.
@endnode
///

/// Minor planets                                         //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS "ASense - Asteroids"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-PLANETS
@NEXT ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-HISTORY
@{b}@{u}Asteroids and Comets@{uu}@{ub}: The @{i}minor@{ui} and (some) @{i}dwarf@{ui} planets.

    Currently, tens of thousands of asteroids are known.A thorough search of
  the sky, being done by NASA, has the aim to map all of the objects larger
  than 1 km until 2007.It is estimated that there can be more than a million
  of them.Most of the asteroids have a rotational period of about 5 to 20 h.
  Some even have their own satellites or are binaries.These systems are the
  impact remnants, not the captured bodies.The gravity of an asteroid is too
  small to allow that possibility to happen frequently.

    @{i}Total mass of all known asteroids is smaller than the mass of the Moon.
  Ceres alone has 25% of the mass of all currently known Main Belt asteroids.
  There are only 26 Main Belt asteroids with a diameter larger than 200 km@{ui}.

  @{"Historical review" link ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-HISTORY} - discoveries and naming of minor planets.
  @{"Groups of minor planets" link ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-GROUPS} - all avialable forms, including dust.
  @{"Types of asteroids" link ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-TYPES} - division by composition.
  @{"Surfaces of minor planets" link ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-SURFACES} - dynamics based on coloring.

  @{b}@{u}Astrologically@{uu}@{ub}: The influence is dubious.They are not yet included in the
    Asense package.Even the largest of these bodies are very small.Caution
    is advised.@{i}@{b}Only the comets are known to be undoubtedtly influential@{ub}@{ui}.
    Perhaps because of the enormous size of their coma.Centaurs are second
    on the list of potentially useful bodies, followed by the largest of KBOs.

