 136199 Eris     icy   67.5    44    0.43     560      2400         0.99       2005 Mike Brown              SKBO

  @{b}Ceres@{ub} is by far @{b}the largest of the main belt asteroids@{ub}.It contains about @{i}@{b}25%
    of the combined mass of all other main belt asteroids@{ub}@{ui}.Ceres is a @{i}C type
    asteroid@{ui} (mostly made of carbon-containing dust) and it has never melted.
    Ceres was named after a Sicilian goddess of grain.

  @{b}Vesta is the only asteroid known that has been differentiated into layers
    by igneous processes.It has a huge crater upon it, large enough to expose
    the underlying mantle@{ub}.Many small asteroids originate from Vesta.They are
    the rarest achondrite (melted) type. (Debris from Vesta that entered the
    Kirkwood Gap were perturbed by the gravity of Jupiter and thrown into a
    new orbit that crosses the path of Earth.) These asteroids contain some
    isotopes of Oxygen that are not present in the rocks on Earth and Moon.
      @{i}@{b}Vesta is the most reflective of the main belt asteroids@{ub}@{ui} (i.e. it has
    the highest albedo).

  @{b}Halley@{ub} is a @{i}short term comet@{ui}, small in size, but great in appearance.@{i}@{b}It's
    dust tail can stretch 6° across the sky@{ub}@{ui}, because it comes very close to
    the Sun.The comet has been known since 240 BC, possibly since 1059 BC,
    but it was @{b}Halley@{ub} who has discovered its orbital parameters and predicted
    its next return, so it was named after him.(Comets are named after their
    discoverers.)
      The comet has its perihelion at 0.587 AU and aphelion at ~35 AU, thus it
    has a highly eccentric orbit and it also moves in a @{i}retrograde@{ui} direction.
    Halley's last perihelion approach was on 9th Feb 1986, and the next one
    will be in 2061.Orbits of active comets are highly unstable, because these
    bodies melt and slowly crumble apart as they approach the Sun, spurting
    jets of material from their surfaces.Jets are able to change the comet's
    orbit in an unpredictable manner.
      Several spaceships have visited Halley.They determined that @{i}@{b}only 10% of
    the surface is still active@{ub}@{ui}.

  @{b}Pholus@{ub} connects the orbits of @{i}Saturn@{ui} and @{i}Neptune@{ui}.It is slightly smaller
    than Chiron.It's orbit is unpredictable for the years before 3850 BC.
    This was the second discovered Centaur, found in 1992, 15 years after
    the discovery of Chiron, the first found Centaur.
      @{b}The surface of Pholus is very red@{ub} in color, indicating an old age.
    It is quite different from the neutral colors present on comet Chiron,
    (which indicate a young, active surface, as can be expected on a comet).

  @{b}Asbolus@{ub} has a bright impact crater, about 10 Myr old.It is the residue of
    the impact that has sent it closer to the Sun.Formerly KBO, now a @{i}Centaur@{ui}.

  @{b}Quaoar@{ub} is a large KBO.It @{b}has@{ub} a number 50000, and @{b}about the same volume
    as other 50000 numbered asteroids put together@{ub}.It is roughly the size of
    Pluto's moon @{i}Charon@{ui}.Quaoar has a @{i}nearly circular orbit@{ui}, slightly inclined,
    lying at 43.4 AU away from the Sun.This is very different from Pluto.
      Quaoar was named after the @{i}great force of creation of Tongva people@{ui}.
      First image was taken at 4th Jun 2002 5:41:40 UT at Palomar Observatory.
    The object was identified on the image at 5th Jun 2002 10:48:08 Pacific
    Daylight Time.
    UPDATE: The diameter of Quaoar is estimated to be about @{b}1000@{ub} km.
      The prefered form of ice on @{b}50@{ub} K, which is the surface temperature on
    Quaoar, is @{i}amorphous@{ui} (structureless, jumbled pattern). But, the surface
    ices are detected to be in @{b}crystalline@{ub} form, which requires temperatures
    above @{i}@{b}110@{ub}@{ui} K to form. Moreover, this type of ice is @{i}unstable@{ui} on the long
    run, and breaks by solar wind and cosmic rays into amorphous ice within
    10 Myr period (which is practically yesterday in cosmic terms). As the
    crystalline ice is still present, there must be some active replenishing
    process in existance. @{i}Cryovolcanic outgassing@{ui} (as in comets) or @{i}impact
    gardening@{ui} (heating of surface by micrometeorite impacts) are the possible
    candidates.

  @{b}Orcus@{ub} - PKBO of 1200 km in diameter (estimate). Discovered on 17-Feb-2004.

    @{FG shine}NEWS@{FG text}: On 29th Jul 2005 4:00 PM PST at Palomar Obs., San Diego, CA, the
    discovery of @{"Eris" link ASENSE-PLANETS-ERIS} was announced, which is a KBO as big as Triton.
    This means that @{b}Eris is larger than Pluto@{ub}.
      On the same time 2 other large objects were announced, @{b}2003 EL61@{ub} aqd
    @{b}2005 FY9@{ub}, @{i}@{b}both@{ub}@{ui} about 3/4 of the Pluto size, (@{i}@{b}a bit larger than Quaoar@{ub}@{ui}).
      The former, nicknamed '@{b}Santa@{ub}', has a moon and @{b}is the fastest rotating
    KBO, with a period of only 4 hours@{ub}.@{i}@{b}This forces it to be shaped like a
    cigar@{ub}@{ui}.The surface of Santa is composed of water ice, and it has only 30%
    of Pluto's mass.Orbital period is 285 years, with moderate eccentricity
    that takes Santa from 35 to 52 AU away from the Sun.Inclination is 28°.
      The later, nicknamed '@{b}Easterbunny@{ub}@{b}@{ub}', has no satellites and the surface
    composition similar to Pluto's.Orbital period is 307 years, inclination
    29°, and moderate eccentricity that takes the planetoid from 39 to 52 AU.
    Easterbunny is the second brightest KBO (after Pluto), while the Santa
    is a third one in line.Eris comes forth, only because of its distance.
    @{b}All three newly discovered bodies are now approaching their @{i}aphels@{ui}@{ub}.
    UPDATE: Observations by Hubble telescope revealed that Eris is in fact
    much smaller than estimated, just about 70 km larger than Pluto. This
    makes it very bright, the 2nd brightest object in solar system, after
    Enceladus, one of the moons of Saturn. The planet probably have had an
    atmosphere of methane near perihel, that has frozen and covered the
    surface with fresh snow layer.(27-Apr-2006).

  @{b}Sedna@{ub} is @{b}the only known member of the Inner Oort Cloud@{ub}.@{i}Sedna@{ui} (a proposed,
    but not yet officially adopted name) will be named after an @{i}Innuit goddes,
    the one that rules the arctic sea and has created all of the arctic sea
    creatures@{ui}.
      Sedna (a.k.a. @{b}2003 VB 12@{ub}) has an @{i}@{b}extremely elliptic orbit@{ub}@{ui} which flings it
    990 AU away and back to 76.1 AU.Currently it is approaching its perihelion,
    which it will reach in about 72 years.The orbit is not yet well determined.
    Period is estimated to be about 12,260 years,which means that it is coming
    back for the first time after the Ice age.When it returns again, the Earth
    would undoubtedly be entirely different place again.
      Note that although it currently approaches its perihel, the temperatures
    on Sedna are about -240°C.
      KBOs are typically @{i}reddish@{ui} in color.Sedna is not a KBO, but a member of
    the @{i}@{b}Inner Oort Cloud@{ub}@{ui} (currently the only one known), and it has a @{b}deeply
    red color@{ub}.It is @{b}almost as red as Mars@{ub}.This is an indication of an ancient,
    inactive crust on surface, carbonized and irradiated by cosmic rays.
      Sedna has a slow rot. period (~40 days), maybe because it has a @{i}moon@{ui}.
    It has a diameter of 1250-1800 km.@{i}@{b}It is also the most distant known object
    of the solar system, 3 times further away than Pluto@{ub}@{ui} (currently).
      Sedna is far beyond the scattering influence of Neptune, but is close
    enough to be imune to external forces (passing stars and Galactic tides).
    It is puzzling how this object had had it's perihel lifted out of the
    planetary region. (The fact that Sedna has a low inclination indicates
    that it knows where the plane of the solar system is, which means that
    it has inner origin.)
      Sedna was discovered on 14th Nov 2003 at the Palomar Observatory of San
    Diego, California.The discovery was officially announced on 15th Mar 2004.
@endnode
///
///   Historical review                                   //f
@node ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-HISTORY "ASense - Asteroids: Historical review"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS
@NEXT ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-GROUPS

    In 1766, 15 years before the discovery of Uranus, @{b}Johan Titius@{ub} mentioned
  a pattern in the arrangements of the orbits of known planets.In 1778, just
  3 years before the discovery of Uranus, @{b}J.E.Bode@{ub} has formulated an @{u}empiric@{uu}
  @{u}rule to help remember the distances of planets from the Sun@{uu}:
  1. @{i}Take the array@{ui} 0, 3, 6, 12, 24, 48, 96, 192, 384, 768,...
  2. @{i}Add 4 to each member@{ui}: 4, 7, 10, 16, 28, 52, 100, 196, 388, 772,...
  3. @{i}Divide the result by 10 to obtain the mean distances of planets from
  the Sun, expressed in AU@{ui}: 0.4, 0.7, 1.0, 1.6, 2.8, 5.2, 10.0, 19.6,...
  This rule is now known as @{i}@{b}Titius-Bode Law@{ub}@{ui}, or just @{i}@{b}Bode's Law@{ub}@{ui}.The rule
  has showed that there is a gap between Mars and Jupiter.The existance of
  a gap has been considered as an evidence @{i}against@{ui} the rule.(Remember that
  ancient astronomers have thought that @{b}7@{ub} is a perfect number, hence there
  should be no more planets other than the seven already known (@{i}Sun, Moon,
  Mercury, Venus, Mars, Jupiter and Saturn@{ui}).)
    Anyway, only 3 years later, in 1781, @{b}William Herschel@{ub} discovered the
  @{i}Uranus@{ui}, and its orbit fit Bode's Law.This fact made the lure of the gap
  between Mars and Jupiter irresistible.The objects that was predicted to
  exist in the gap, at 2.8 AU away from the Sun, needed to be a small one.
  Otherwise, it would have been visible and known since prehistoric times.

    An organization was set up in Gemany by @{b}Franz Xaver von Zach@{ub}, director
  of the observatory in Gotha in order to search for the unknown planetoid.
  Zodiac has been divided into sections (24 of them), and each member of
  the society got one to observe.

    First and largest of the asteroids, @{b}Ceres@{ub} (933 km in diameter), has
  been discovered on 1st Jan 1801 (the first day of the XIX century) by
  @{b}Giuseppe Piazzi@{ub} (1746 - 1826), director of astronomy observatory in
  Palermo.Although Piazzi was a member of the above mentioned society,
  at that time he was engaged in forming an extensive catalogue of stars.
    At first he thought that he has found a new comet.It wasn't fuzzy, so
  he called it a star-like comet.Piazzi followed the object for 6 weeks,
  until 11th Feb, then got sick.He mailed his observations to others, but
  the mail was delayed because of an ongoing war in Italy.
    Eventually, the news of a discovery came to @{b}Bode@{ub}, who was at that time
  a director of astronomy observatory in Berlin.He immediately concluded that
  it is not a comet, but more like a small planet, one that his empiric rule
  predicted long time ago, but he himself was unable to find.Unfortunately,
  too much time has passed since the discovery and the object was lost in the
  twilight.Available methods of orbital calculations were unable to yield an
  accurate orbit from such a short span of observations and nothing was found
  at the computed position.
    Later that year, @{b}Johan Friederich Carl Gauss@{ub} (30 Apr 1777 - 23 Feb 1855),
  a great mathematician and physicist, has invented a new method of orbital
  determination from just 3 known positions.His technique was applied to the
  lost object and the predicted position was right on.The object was recovered
  on 31st Dec 1801 by @{b}Franz von Zach@{ub}, the founder of the group.

    Piazzi gave the name @{i}Ceres@{ui} to the newly found object, after a Sicilian
  @{i}goddess of grain@{ui}.Its mean distance from the Sun is 2.77 AU, close to the
  predicted value of 2.8 AU.Everything seemed to be fine for a while.

    However, 3 months later, on 28th Mar 1802, @{b}Wilhelm Olbers@{ub} (1758 - 1840),
  a reputable amateur astronomer from Bremen, discovered @{b}Pallas@{ub} (522 km) while
  searching for Ceres.The orbit of Pallas has nearly the same size as Ceres's,
  but is strongly inclined to the ecliptic.The simple picture was shattered.
    To clear the confusion, Olbers suggested the idea that these small bodies
  were merely a fragments of a larger planet that has crumbled into pieces.He
  thought that more small bodies were to be found, and that they all must pass
  through two opposite points on the sky where the orbits of Ceres and Pallas
  intersect.One of them should be the point of ancient planet's destruction.To
  prove his assumption, he checked the areas 3 times each year.Note that this
  theory is not correct.Pieces of a crumbled body would be involved in further
  mutual collision and their ever smaller chunks would scatter around in every
  posssible direction, rendering the initial place of impact undetectable.
  Perturbations by gravity (mainly from Jupiter) would play their part too.

    In 1803, 2 chemical elements were discovered and named after the 2 known
  asteroids: @{i}@{b}Cerium@{ub}@{ui}, a rare-earth metal; and @{i}@{b}Palladium@{ub}@{ui}, a precious metal from
  the Platinum group of metals.

    On 2nd Sep 1804 @{b}Carl Ludwig Harding@{ub} from Bremen has discovered @{b}Juno@{ub} (246 km)
  near one of the points suggested by Olbers.Finally, on 29th Mar 1807 @{b}Olbers@{ub}
  has managed to find @{b}Vesta@{ub} (530 km) on the opposite point.No more bodies were
  found until 1845.Searches were made, but didn't go faint enough.

    The fifth asteroid, @{b}Astraea@{ub} was finally found on 8th Dec 1845 by @{b}Hencke@{ub},
  an amateur astronomer from Dresden, after 15 years of searching.Hencke has
  also found @{b}6 Hebe@{ub} on 1st Jul 1847.

    In 1846, the @{i}Neptune@{ui} was discovered, which has led to a large increase
  in the interest for the astronomy observations.Crush of the revolution in
  1848/49 in Europe has also influenced the minds to turn up to the sky.New
  star charts were made by Berlin Academy, going as faint as 9th magnitude.
  Quantity coupled with quality and improved equipment have quickly produced
  impressive results: every year more and more objects have been discovered.
    Soon, it became obvious that all of the newly found objects have their
  orbits confined in a belt between Mars and Jupiter.This belt became known
  as the @{i}@{b}asteroidal belt@{ub}@{ui}.Subsequent examinations of the area have revealed
  a great number of rocky objects, the @{i}@{b}asteroids@{ub}@{ui}.
    The term '@{i}asteroid@{ui}' was given by @{b}William Herschel@{ub} in the early part of
  XIX century to indicate that the newly found objects are faint like stars.
  Other names for asteroids are @{i}@{b}minor planets, planetoids, telescopic objects
  and star-form planets@{ub}@{ui}.

    The upkeep of orbital data of hundreds of small lumps of rocks, easily
  perturbed from their paths has soon became a severe drag for astronomers.
  Without computers to solve the equations, they have had to manually solve
  systems with more than 400 equations.Since the orbital elements were very
  imperfectly determined, frequent, almost continual observations were still
  needed in order to keep the track of all objects.It was a never-ending and
  exhausting work, but there was no other way.The offices had to cope with it.

    On 13th Aug 1898 @{b}Gustav Witt@{ub}, director of Urania Observatory in Berlin,
  has discovered @{b}Eros@{ub}, the first @{b}NEO@{ub} (@{i}Near Earth Object@{ui}).Eros is a small
  asteroid with a highly eccentric orbit.It's mean distance from the Sun
  of 1.458 AU is within the Martian orbit (1.524 AU), and it's perihelion
  is only 1.133 AU.Moreover, @{i}when Eros is close to its perihelion, the
  Earth is also not far away.It can get as close as 0.15 AU@{ui}.
    @{b}The presence of such a small object near the Earth have enabled the
  scientists to finally manage to measure the solar parallax, i.e. to
  determine the actual distance to the Sun in km@{ub}.Since Copernicus, all
  astronomical measurements were expressed in astronomical units (AU),
  which is the mean distance of Earth from the Sun, but the value of AU
  has only benn known approximately.Eros has enabled the scientists to
  refine their figures by several different methods.
    @{i}Dynamical method@{ui} (perturbations of Eros by Earth-Monn system) yielded
  a value of @{i}8.799''@{ui} of arc, as determined by @{b}Noteboom@{ub} in 1921.
    @{i}1930-31 opposition@{ui} (another method) triggered a great campaign of
  observations world-wide.Best equipment was used, with nearly fourty
  laboratories participating on all sides of the globe.More than 10
  years was needed for the analysis of obtained data.Finally, in 1942,
  @{b}Spencer Jones@{ub} of Greenwich Observatory published the results.The value
  for parallax was @{i}8.790±.001''@{ui}.The size of Eros started to be a limiting
  factor for measurements.
    In 1958 @{i}radar observations@{ui} have started.
    @{b}Jan H. Lieske@{ub} of Yale University Observatory has again reviewed the
  so far obtained data (8,639 observations in 1893 - 1966 period) using
  a @{i}dynamical method@{ui}, and further refined the solar parallax value to be
  @{i}8.79402±.00012''@{ui}.The error corresponded to ~800 km in Sun's distance,
  or 87 m in the size of Earth's diameter.
    @{b}Current value of the solar parallax is 8.79414±.00004''@{ub}.

    Eros has been visited by the @{b}NEAR@{ub} spacecraft.On 14th Feb 2000 NEAR
  has entered into the orbit around Eros, becoming @{b}the first artificial
  satellite of an asteroid@{ub}.Due to a computer glitch, this encounter has
  been delayed for 15 months.(On 23rd Dec 1998 NEAR flied past Eros.)
  NEAR was launched on 17th Feb 1996 as the first of NASA's @{i}Discovery
  missions@{ui}.She has sent pictures of a heavily cratered surface of Eros.

    The discovery of @{"Eris" link ASENSE-PLANETS-ERIS} in 2003 has led to redefinition of the term @{"planet" link ASENSE-SELECT-PL-DEF}
  and consequently to demotion of @{"Pluto" link ASENSE-PLANETS-PLUTO} from an official planetary status.
@endnode
///
///   Groups of Asteroids                                 //f
@node ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-GROUPS "ASense - Asteroids: Groups"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS
@PREV ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-HISTORY
@NEXT ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-TYPES
@{b}@{u}Groups of asteroids@{uu}@{ub}:

  1. @{b}Main Belt@{ub} (2 - 4 AU) - region of rocky bodies between Mars and Jupiter.
     @{u}Subgroups (named after a main asteroid within the group)@{uu}:
     - @{i}@{b}Hungarias, Floras, Phocaea, Koronis, Eos, Themis, Cybeles, Hildas@{ub}@{ui}.
     Each of the subgroups is made of several bodies, orbiting in more or less
     similar paths.Once upon a time they were elements of several single bodies
     that have since been shattered into pieces by mighty collisions.The largest
     (and main) member of each subgroup is just the largest remnant.Subsequent
     collisions between the pieces and perturbations by other bodies and planets
     (chiefly by Jupiter) tend to disperse the chunks relatively quickly.
     @{i}@{b}Kirkwood Gaps@{ub}@{ui} - areas within the Main Belt devoid of asteroids.@{i}Any object
     orbiting within these gaps@{ui} would have an orbital period that is a simple
     fraction of Jupiter's.This means that it @{i}would get perturbed very quickly@{ui}.

  2. @{b}Kuiper Belt@{ub} (30 - 55 AU) - icy bodies beyond the orbit of Neptune (Pluto
     included).They are the @{i}source of short term comets@{ui}.Several large bodies
     were recently discovered within the Belt, including Quaoar, 1250 km in
     diameter.The Belt is quite unexplored, and @{b}is estimated to contain about
     100 times more mass than the Main Belt@{ub}.KBOs are typically @{i}reddish@{ui}.Those
     members of the Kuiper Belt which are locked in an orbital resonance with
     Neptune like Pluto (3:2 or 4:3) are called '@{i}@{b}plutinos@{ub}@{ui}', the little Plutos.
     The Belt abruptly ends at 55 AU, as if something has cleared the space
     beyond (a good indication of a planet of a Mars size or bigger).
       There might be an outer belt of icy objects, but only after 100 AU.
       The estimates are that the belt contains at least 70,000 KBOs > 100 km
     in diameter within 30..50 AU distance interval.
     @{u}Subgroups of KBOs@{uu}:
     a. @{b}Plutinos@{ub} (resonant KBOs) - These objects are in a 3:2 motion resonance
        with Neptune. @{"Pluto" link ASENSE-PLANETS-PLUTO} is the prototype of these objects (hence the name).
        They group at 39 AU, thus there is an observational bias toward finding
        them. PKBOs make 25% of all known KBOs.
          The estimate is that there are about 1400 PKBOs > 100 km in diameter.
          Although most of them are locked in 3:2, there are also few that are
        in 4:3 and other mean motion resonances.
     b. @{b}Classic KBOs@{ub} - These objects have their semimajor axis at 42..48 AU.
        They have small eccentricities, but inclinations range is high, some
        have i > 30°. This indicates excitation by something (by passing star
        or by a large scattered planetesimal). The archetyp is @{b}1992 QB1@{ub}, the
        first found KBO after Pluto.
     c. @{b}Scattered KBOs@{ub} - These objects have their perihel near 35 AU, large
        eccentricities and inclined orbits, and are only under weak dynamical
        control by Neptune. Prototype of these objects is @{b}1996 TL66@{ub} (275 km).
        Scattered KBOs form a doughnut around the classical and resonant KBOs.
          As they have heavily eccentric orbits they are most of the time too
        far away to be found by ground based surveys. According to the laws of
        Kepler, the body moves faster on its orbit when it is closer to the
        focus of orbit (i.e. to the Sun), hence the SKBOs  remain undetectable
        for about 90% of their orbiting time.
          Due to heavy observational bias against finding the KBOs at large
        distances, the SKBOs make only 3..4% of all known KBOs.
     @{b}Binary KBOs@{ub} - about 1.5% of known KBOs are known to be binaries, but the
       exact figure is probably much higher due to observational bias. They are
       assumed to be the @{i}@{b}product of low velocity collisions@{ub}@{ui} (< 100 m/s) within
       the Kuiper Belt. @{i}If 2 bodies of unequal size making a binary low collide
       with a third one to form a triple system, eventually the smallest of the
       bodies will either get ejected@{ui} from the system or merge with the others.
       As a result, most of the existing binaries will have comparable sizes,
         Although @{b}most of the observed binaries@{ub} do indeed @{b}have comparable sizes@{ub},
       this may simply be the product of an observational bias toward finding
       the largest of objects first.
         The other proposed method of formation of binaries is @{i}@{b}dynamic friction@{ub}@{ui},
       where many coorbiting bodies slowly tug on each other and spiral together.
         Stability of binaries is @{i}marginal@{ui} on a large timescales.
       @{u}KBOs known to be binaries@{uu}: 1998 WW31, 2000 CF105, 2001 QC298, 2001 QW322,
         15883, 26308, 47171, 88611, 136108 (2003 EL61).

  3. @{b}Centaurs@{ub} - former KBOs which have strayed into inner solar system.They
     have unstable, @{i}temporary orbits@{ui} and are @{i}lurking in the area between the
     gas giants@{ui}.If they get perturbed enough to stray closer, they become
     comets (like Halley), and eventually evaporate.Very few pieces remain.
     Examples are @{i}2060 Chiron@{ui} (orbit between Saturn and Uranus), @{i}5145 Pholus@{ui}
     (Saturn - Neptune), @{i}5335 Damocles@{ui} (Mars - Uranus).These objects are
     named @{i}Centaurs@{ui} after the race of @{b}half-man/half-horse@{ub} beings fron Greek
     mythology to acknowledge their dual @{b}half-comet/half-asteroid@{ub} appearance.
     @{u}Subgroup@{uu}:
     a. @{b}Damocloids@{ub}, named after @{i}@{b}5335 Damocles@{ub}@{ui} - 8 km in average, these objects
       are the @{b}leftovers of no longer active Halley family comets@{ub}. Only 25% of
       them is moving in retrograde direction and 70% have inclinations < 90°,
       which correlates with the properties of short period comets. Some of
       them are still able to develop a small coma when they approach the Sun,
       proving their cometary origin. (Note that the surface of Halley comet
       is only 10% active, the rest is rubble mantle, the coverage created by
       the dust that falls back from suborbits (ejected by the gas drag).)
         The Damocloid family of Centaurs has extremely dark albedo, indicating
       that their surfaces are irradiated and carbonized, no longer active. On
       the other side, they lack the ultrared material upon them, present only
       on extremely ancient surfaces of very distant objects, like Sedna.
         On Oct 2004, there were 21 known Damocloids.

  4. @{b}NEO@{ub} (@{i}Near Earth Objects@{ui}) - dead comets and strayed chunks from the Main
     Belt, mostly very small objects, rarely exceeding several km in diameter.
     @{b}Atens@{ub} -   a < 1.0 AU; perihel > 0.983 AU
       Example: @{i}Eros@{ui} (36×12 km), used for determination of Sun's distance.
     @{b}Apollos@{ub} - a > 1.0 AU; perihel < 1.017 AU
       Example: @{i}Phaeton@{ui}, approaches the Sun down to 20.9 Gm.
     @{b}Amors@{ub} -               perihel 1.017..1.3 AU

  5. @{b}Trojans@{ub} - objects orbiting @{b}60° in front or behind any planet@{ub} (but mainly
     Jupiter) in so called '@{i}@{b}Lagrangian points@{ub}@{ui}', which allow an orbit to be
     stable.(In case of Jupiter one side is named after @{i}Greek@{ui}, and the other
     after @{i}Trojan@{ui} heroes from the Trojan War.) There are @{i}many more chunks in
     the leading Lagrangian point of Jupiter@{ui} (L4) @{i}than on the trailing one@{ui} (L5),
     for unknown reason.For example @{i}5261 Eureka@{ui} is a Martian Trojan.There may
     be some smaller chunks in the Earth's and Venusian Lagrangian points too.

  6. @{b}Planetary companions@{ub} - objects orbiting together with the planets, in
     close orbits.Occasionally they exchange angular momentum and trade orbits.
     @{i}3753 Cruithne@{ui} is a companion of Earth.It is a very small chunk of rock.

  7. @{b}Zodiacal Cloud@{ub} - concentrations of dust due to the mean motion resonances
     with gas giants, which start from the orbit of Saturn.@{i}The Cloud is being
     maintained by a slow crumbling of Main Belt asteroids into dust@{ui} by mutual
     collisions and micrometeoric impacts @{i}at a rate of about 55 t/s@{ui}.The dust
     is then blown away from the solar system by the solar wind.The Cloud is
     very tenuous and its @{i}density is only about 1 dust particle / 50 km^3@{ui}.

  8. @{b}Oort Cloud@{ub} - trillions of @{i}proto-comets@{ui} at the outer scopes of the solar
     system.The Oort Cloud is a @{i}source of long term comets@{ui}.Outer edge of the
     Cloud extends upto 3 light years away from the Sun.That is the true border
     of any kind of Sun's influence.Although numerous by number, the @{b}total mass
     of the Oort Cloud is estimated to be just about 40 Earth masses@{ub}.It is
     believed that the Cloud has an @{i}ellipsoidal shape@{ui} with a relatively dense
     core near the ecliptic plane and a more scarcely populated outer regions.
     The inner edge of the Cloud lies at about 50,000 AU (very rough estimate).
     Temperatures in the Cloud are only @{b}4@{ub} K.The Cloud was named after @{b}Ian Oort@{ub}.
       Proto-comets beyond 200 kAU (~ 1 ly) are easily perturbed by Galactic
     tides and by nearby stars.They can be lost into interstellar space or be
     thrown into inner solar system.If they do the latter, they become the
     @{i}long-term@{ui} comets.@{i}The average distance from which they arrive is 44 kAU@{ui},
     and they can come at any time from any direction, unpredictably.Once they
     leave, they may never come again, or take any value between 200 yr and
     few Myr for their return.

  9. @{b}Comets@{ub} are icy bodies that have been perturbed by some force to an orbit
     that takes them close to the Sun.The Sun's heat then melts the volatiles
     on their surfaces.Since comets are very small bodies, dust and gases which
     result from the melting of dirty ice easily escape into space.Two tails
     are forming in the process: a @{i}@{b}curved dust tai@{ub}l@{ui} that follows the orbit of
     a comet, and a @{i}@{b}straight ion tail@{ub}@{ui}, made of @{i}charged@{ui} particles, that follows
     the solar wind and the surrounding magnetic field lines (usually of Sun's
     magnetic field, but sometimes of Jupiter's).
       Comets are sometimes called '@{b}dirty snowballs@{ub}' or '@{b}icy mudballs@{ub}', since
     they consist of a mixture of ices (water and frozen gases) and small dust
     particles, with perhaps some rocks.They are the @{i}pristine remnants of the
     original solar nebula@{ui}, which makes them very interesting as samples from
     the early history of the solar system.
       @{i}Since the comets are brightest when they are close to the Sun, they are
     usually visible only at sunrise or sunset@{ui}.
     @{u}Parts of a comet@{uu}:
     - @{b}nucleus@{ub} - relatively solid core of a comet, mostly made of dirty ice;
     - @{b}coma@{ub} - dense cloud of water, CO2, and other neutral gases that have
       sublimed off from the nucleus;
     - @{b}hydrogen cloud@{ub} - huge, but very sparse, envelope of neutral hydrogen,
       several Gm in diameter;
     - @{b}curved @{i}dust@{ui} tail@{ub} - @{i}trail@{ui} of smoke-sized dust particles, a dirt from
       the molten ice that follows the path of the comet, stretching upto 10 Gm
       away from the nucleus.It is the most prominent part of the comet;
     - @{b}straight @{i}ion@{ui} tail@{ub} - up to 100 Gm long laced @{i}rays@{ui} of plasma, created by
       the interactions of gases in the comet's envelope with the solar wind.
       The rays are pointing @{i}away@{ui} from the Sun.
       After several hundred near-Sun passes, most of the ice from the comet's
     surface evaporates, leaving a rocky object behind akin to an asteroid.If
     the orbit of the comet is not too close to the Sun, and the rocky remnant
     is fairly large, the surface may still contain some water ice, and there
     may be even some frozen gases trapped deeply below the rocky surface.The
     moons of Mars, @{i}Phobos@{ui} and @{i}Deimos@{ui}, might be the example of this category
     of 'dead' cometary remnants which still contain some frozen volatiles.
       It is estimated that @{i}perhaps half of the NEOs are 'dead' comets@{ui}.
       When the Earth passes through the tail of a comet, a @{i}meteor shower@{ui}
     occurs.@{i}@{b}Perseid meteor shower@{ub}@{ui} occurs every year between 9th and 13th Aug
     when the Earth passes through the orbit of a @{i}Comet Swift-Tuttle@{ui}.@{i}@{b}Orionid
     shower@{ub}@{ui} in october originates from the @{i}Comet Halley@{ui}.
     @{u}Comet types@{uu}:
     - @{b}Long period comets@{ub} (LPCs) - have @{b}periods > 200 yrs@{ub},
       The LPCs @{i}@{b}come from the Oort Cloud@{ub}@{ui}, most of them for the very first time.
       Isotropic in appearance, with a truly random distribution (no preferred
       direction of entering and 50% of them are retrograde). Their composition
       is thought to be nearly primordial.
     - @{b}Short period comets@{ub} (SPCs) - have @{b}periods > 200 yrs@{ub}.
       The SPCs @{i}@{b}come from the Kuiper Belt@{ub}@{ui}. Most of them are collision fragments.
@endnode
///
///   Types (C S M D)                                     //f
@node ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-TYPES "ASense - Asteroids: Types"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS
@PREV ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-GROUPS
@NEXT ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-SURFACES

  @{b}@{u}Types of the asteroids@{uu}@{ub}:
  - @{b}C@{ub} type (@{b}carbonaceous@{ub}) - 75% of known asteroids; very dark (albedo 0.03-0.09)
      Composition is similar to Sun, but depleted of volatiles (H, He,...).
      These asteroids inhabit main belt's outer regions.
  - @{b}S@{ub} type (@{b}silicaceous@{ub}) -  17% of known asteroids; brighter (albedo 0.10-0.22)
      Composition metallic Fe, mixed with Fe and Mg silicates.
      These asteroids inhabit main belt's inner regions.
  - @{b}M@{ub} type (@{b}metallic@{ub}) - brighter (albedo 0.10-0.18)
      Composition dominated by metallic Fe.They are made of the Fe/Ni alloy,
      typically present in the cores of melted planetary bodies.
      These asteroids inhabit main belt's middle regions.
  - @{b}D@{ub} type - low albedo, reddish, @{b}possibly dead comets@{ub} (KBOs are typically red)
@endnode
///
///   Surfaces                                            //f
@node ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-SURFACES "ASense - Asteroids: Surfaces"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS
@PREV ASENSE-ASTEROIDS-TYPES
@NEXT ASENSE-PLANETS-DELINEATION
@{b}@{u}Surfaces of asteroids and comets@{uu}@{ub} - Neutral and alive, or red and inactive.

    The KBOs and comets have many volatile substances on their surfaces in
  form of @{i}ice@{ui}. Fresh ice is white in color and highly @{i}reflective@{ui}, i.e. it
  has high albedo of almost 100%. However, the KBOs have no atmosphere due
  to their low mass and low temperatures, thus their surfaces are constantly
  exposed to highly energetic @{i}@{b}cosmic rays@{ub}@{ui} (which are the remnants of distant
  supernovas, coming from every direction all the time).
    @{b}The ubiqituous bombardment of surface materials by cosmic rays causes a
  loss of hydrogen and promotes formation of chemically complex polymers@{ub}.
  Many of these polymers are @{b}dark and red due to high carbon abundances@{ub}@{b}@{ub}.
  This carbonized, irradiated material is though to make blackened, very low
  albedo crust, only few meters thick, on the nuclei of inactive comets.

    On the other side, the fresh ice from below may be excavated by micro-
  meteroite impacts (@{i}@{b}impact gardening@{ub}@{ui}), which replenish the ice deposits
  on surface and lighten it's color. It can also be partially renewed by
  @{i}@{b}cryovolcanic outgasing@{ub}@{ui}, typically present on @{i}comets@{ui}.

    If an icy object approaches the Sun close enough for the temperature
  to rise beyond the melting point, the object may develop an @{b}atmosphere
  of gases@{ub} and (if it isn't massive enough to be able to hold it), @{i}@{b}a coma
  and a tail of a comet@{ub}@{ui}. @{b}Once it returns back to outer edges of the solar
  system, the temperatures will again, the remains of the atmosphere will
  freeze again and drop down to create a fresh snow layer with a very high
  albedo@{ub}. This is what has happened to Eris recently, as it has as albedo
  of 99%. @{b}Only very large KBOs are able to retain material of high albedo
  (i.e. to hold atmospheres dense enough to form a layer of ice and frost)@{ub}.
  Smaller objects @{i}loose@{ui} most of their evaporated volatiles back to space.
    @{b}The active comets acquire a brighter rubble mantle, the coverage of dust
  that falls from a suborbit@{ub}, ejected by the gas drag. @{b}Eventually this rubble
  mantle gives an asteroid-like appearance to a comet@{ub}. (The surface of comet
  Halley is only 10% active for example.)

    The asteroids in the Main Belt have @{b}rocky@{ub} surfaces, like the Moon does.
  Irradiation doesn't affect the rocks, only the volatile ices.
@endnode
///
@remark (delineation)

/// Stars                                                 //f
@node ASENSE-SELECT-STARS "ASense - Select: Stars"
@TOC MAIN
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-ASTEROIDS
@NEXT ASENSE-STARS-INTRO
@{b}@{u}Stars@{uu}@{ub}: Shiny dots across the night sky, the skeleton of heavens.

    These pages describe the stars from @{b}astronomical@{ub} point of view.Their
  evolutionary path, mechanism of their work.Fine details about individual
  stars are intended to be written in a @{"separate guide" link "ASense-star-data.guide/MAIN"}, devoted to them.

  1, @{"Intro" link ASENSE-STARS-INTRO} - Which stars are included and why.
  2. @{"Creation" link ASENSE-STARS-CREATION} - The beginning of stars.
  3. @{"Division by mass" link ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_MASS} - from dust specks to black holes.
  4. @{"Division by luminosity" link ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_LUM} - from dwarfs to hypergiants.
  5. @{"Variability types" link ASENSE-STARS-VARS} - classification (table).
  6. @{"Spectral types" link ASENSE-STARS-SPECTRA} - classification (description).

  @{u}Appendix@{uu}@{u}@{uu}:
  a. @{"Elementary particles" link ASENSE-STARS-PARTICLES} - basic quantum physics.
  b. @{"Constellations" link ASENSE-STARS-CONSTELLATIONS} - abbrev., full names, translations.
  c. @{"Greek alphabet" link ASENSE-STARS-GREEK-ALPHABET}

    @{i}Chapters marked with asterisk ('*') contain some previously unknown
  things.They are introduced here for the very first time@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Intro                                               //f
@node ASENSE-STARS-INTRO "ASense - Stars: Intro"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@PREV ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@NEXT ASENSE-STARS-CREATION
@{b}@{u}Stars - Intro@{uu}@{ub}: Which stars are included and why.

    Stars are the skeleton of the heavens.They are the background of the
  chart.Unfortunately, they are rarely computed and grossly misunderstood.
  The ASense attempts to rectify this situation by including a detailed
  fact sheet about the various star systems in order to help delineation.
  Some interpretation rules are also given as a guidance, but beware, this
  is mostly an uncharted territory.Exploration is advised.

    Due to the greatness of their number, when compared with the limited
  number of astronomers researching them, most of the stars are poorly
  studied and not well understood.This rule applies even to some very
  bright stars.Thereby, @{b}this version of ASense contains only stars that
  are known to have proper names@{ub}.Since they are known for longer time,
  the data about them (from both astronomical and astrological sources)
  tends to be nore readily available.
    There are 393 properly named stars on the sky, but to make the number
  even (exactly 400), @{b}the closest stars (upto 15 ly distant) were also
  included.There are 15 such stars@{ub}.8 of them are too faint to be visible.
  Seven of them do not have proper names, but their catalog names, however,
  are probably very well known to all who have played some space related
  video games or read some science fiction.
    @{u}Included close stars without proper names@{uu}: @{b}Epsilon Eridani, Epsilon Indi,
  Tau Ceti, Luyten 726-8 (UV Ceti), Lalande 21185, Ross 154, Wolf 359@{ub}.

    More stars will be added in the future versions of ASense.
@endnode
///
///   Creation                                            //f
@node ASENSE-STARS-CREATION "ASense - Stars: Creation"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@PREV ASENSE-STARS-INTRO
@NEXT ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_MASS
@{b}@{u}Creation@{uu}@{ub}: The beginning of stars.

    Dense clouds of interstellar gas occupy the space.The gas is mostly
  hydrogen with some helium and traces of every other element in a form
  of dust.At some point, a cloud is disturbed by a gravity wave.Density
  in some parts of a cloud become too high, and the cloud collapses into
  itself, driven by the force of gravity.The matter aggregates into knots
  and knobs, which start to rotate faster and faster,since the angular
  momentum must be preserved.The energy must be preserved as well, and
  the potential energy of the gravitational field is turned into heat.
  The temperature and pressure of the accumulating gas raise.Eventually,
  they become so large, that they ignite the fusion of hydrogen gas into
  helium.The resulting output of energy balances the force of gravity,
  and the collapse of matter stops.The resulting radiative pressure of
  a newly borned star pushes away the surrounding interstellar matter,
  creating a protective bubble around the star and stopping the infall.
  The star eventually stabilizes and becomes a zero-age main-sequence
  dwarf (ZAMS).
    (During the accretion process, it is called a @{i}proto-star@{ui}.)

    The twirling knots in the above mentioned interstellar cloud are
  not all of the same dimensions.Those in center will accumulate more
  matter than those on the outskirts of the cloud and will become
  massive stars.The energy output of very massive stars is extremely
  large, because they have to counter-balance the larger gravity force.
  It quickly pushes away the clouds for light-years around, affecting
  the process of formation of it's neighbours. Some of them hence may
  never accumulate enough matter to become stars and will remain as
  @{i}@{b}brown dwarfs@{ub}@{ui} (failed stars, with masses less than 75 Jupiter's),
  which @{i}@{b}can only fuse deuterium@{ub}@{ui} (a heavier isotope of H) into He.
  Or, as very small, low-mass red dwarfs (which are the most abundant
  type of stars). Moreover, the most massive stars die quickly, and
  explode as supernovae, creating a myriad of chemical elements in
  the process and spreading them around, elements which are the key
  ingredient in formation of planets (more about it later).

    Since the angular momentum most be preserved (the law of physics),
  the accumulating gas rotates faster and faster.At some point, some
  of the matter is ejected.This may be enough to trigger the formation
  of another star.The process may repeat.@{b}Double (and multiple) stellar
  systems are in fact the most abundant ones@{ub}.Our solar system is the
  exception, but not so rare one, in this matter.
    Again, some ejected chunks may not be massive enough to become new
  stars, but will become brown dwarfs or large gas giants.(@{i}To be able
  to fuse deuterium into helium, and hence be labelled as '@{b}brown dwarf@{ub}',
  an object must be at least 13 times more massive than Jupiter@{ui}.)
    Knots in the accreting gas may also independently become planets.
  Rocky ones in the inner parts of the system, where there is less gas
  available and the radiative pressure is higher, gaseous ones in the
  middle, and scattered icy remains on the outer parts of the system.
    As it was previously mentioned, this process can be, and usually is,
  heavily affected by the proximity of other newly forming star systems
  in the neighbourhood. Perhaps this was the reason, why there isn't a
  definitive answer on how exactly the Uranus and the Neptune have formed.
  Something was affecting this process from the outside in the case of
  our own system, and we still do not know what and how.It has left it's
  signature in a form of abrupt ending of a Kuiper Belt (at 55 AU away
  from the Sun) and as inexplicable presence of Uranus and Neptune (not
  to mention the 98° tilt of Uranus). These two gas giants contain less
  hydrogen and helium than they should, as if there was something outside,
  which has stripped away the outer portion of the solar nebula (a cloud
  which accreted to form the solar system). It's less massive gaseous
  parts, that is.The remaining ices (water, methane, nitrogen, ammonia),
  formed the small gas giants. Excess material remained as scattered
  assortment of small icy chunks of the Kuiper Belt, with Pluto-Charon
  system being just the largest pair of bodies among them.

    This initial phase of the stellar evolution is very brief, and the
  planets haven't got much time to form.Perhaps only a 100,000 years.
  This may look long, but is a very short period in cosmic proportions.

    What follows next, depends on a mass of a newly formed star, but it
  is generally the longest phase in a life of a star. The fusion of the
  hydrogen into helium within the core of the star.This period is called
  the @{i}@{b}main-sequence@{ub}@{ui} (of the @{i}Hertzshprung-Russel diagram@{ui} of the stellar
  evolution).A star that inhabits this portion of a diagram is called a
  '@{i}@{b}dwarf@{ub}@{ui}' and is labelled as '@{b}V@{ub}' in the luminosity classification.

  @{i}Note@{ui}: If a star contains less elements other than H and He (lesser
  metallicity), it is thereupon a more transparent one, and hence more
  bluer than expected by its luminosity (or less luminous than expected
  by its color). These stars are called @{i}@{b}subdwarfs@{ub}@{ui} and are labelled as
  '@{b}VI@{ub}' in luminosity classification.(@{b}Sun has a metallicity of 1.9% by
  mass, which is about twice as much than the surrounding stars have@{ub}.)
    Stars with smaller metallicity level are less likely to have rocky
  planets orbiting around them, because there is less building material
  for such objects within their systems.They may have gas giants, though.
@endnode
///
///   Division by mass                                    //f
@node ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_MASS "ASense - Stars: Division by mass"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-STARS                                  
@PREV ASENSE-STARS-CREATION                               
@NEXT ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_LUM                             
@{b}@{u}Division of objects by mass@{uu}@{ub} - from dust to black holes.

  1. @{b}Gas giants, planets, minor planets@{ub} (< 13 Jupiters) - no fusion.

  2. @{b}Brown dwarfs@{ub} (13 - 80 Jupiters) - fusing deuterium into helium.

  3. @{b}Normal stars@{ub} (>80 Jupiters..200 solar masses) - creating light.
    3a @{i}@{b}Red dwarfs@{ub}@{ui} (> 80 Jupiters..~0.55 solar masses) - can't fuse He.
    3b @{i}@{b}Medium stars@{ub}@{ui} (~0.55..3 solar masses) - can't fuse C.
    3c @{i}@{b}High mass stars@{ub}@{ui} (3..9 solar masses) - fuse C (C flash may blow
         the star away like a supernova, but some may survive).
    3d @{i}@{b}Very high mass stars@{ub}@{ui} (> 9 solar masses) - fuse C gradually without
         degeneration. @{i}They all explode at the end@{ui}.

  4. @{b}White dwarfs@{ub} (0.6..1.4 solar mass) - stellar remnants, no fusion.
     Remains of stars were compressed into planetary sized objects.
     The electromagnetic force between mutually repelling electrons
     counter-balances the gravity.

  5. @{b}Neutron stars@{ub} (1.4..3.2 solar mass) - stellar remnants, no fusion.
       (1.4 and 3.2 solar masses are called '@{i}Chadrasekhar's limits@{ui}'.)
     Remains of stars were compressed into city sized objects (~15 km).
     The electromagnetic force wasn't strong enough to hold the gravity,
     so the electrons have merged with protons to create neutrons.These
     objects are consisting of neutrons only, with only a thin layer of
     regular degenerated mater on the surface perhaps (mostly iron).
     They may even have a half centimeter thick layer of Fe atmosphere.
     The gravity is counter-balanced by the strong nuclear force, since
     these objects are in fact giant atomic nuclei, and have a density
     of an atomic nucleus.
       These objects are also called 'pulsars', since they rotate very
     fast and emit energy through their poles as beams of radiation.
     Fresh pulsars have periods of rotation of only few milisecs, but
     they lose momentum fast by radiation, and slow down gradually.
     After a few Myr, when their periods exceed 4 s, they can no longer
     be detected.Young pulsars emit gamma and X-rays, the old ones only
     radio waves... The beams are very narrow, and can be detected only
     when they sweep over Earth (about 1% of all pulsar are estimated to
     do that).Pulse durations are about 5% of a period of pulsation.
       There is only ~600 known pulsars.The others have faded away into
     invisibility by radiation braking.

  6. @{b}Quark stars@{ub} (~3.2..? solar masses) - stellar remnants, no fusion.
       These objects are neutron stars in the mantle, and quark stars
     in the core (i.e. they seem to be too small to be neutron stars).
     The gravity in the core is so strong that the strong nuclear force
     is unable to withstand it. The neutrons have collapsed, and the
     pressure is counter-balanced by the @{"quarks" link ASENSE-STARS-PARTICLES} themselves.The core
     acts as a single @{"hadron" link ASENSE-STARS-PARTICLES}...

  7. @{b}Small size black holes@{ub} (>3.2 solar masses) - stellar remnants,
     unknown internals, produced after the explosion of a hypergiant.
       Nothing that we know is able to counter-balance the gravity.The
     mass collapses into itself, and even the light that passes by is
     not fast enough to escape the resulting field of gravity.What goes
     inside is unknown.However, the @{i}angular momentum@{ui}, the @{i}charge@{ui}, and
     the @{i}mass@{ui} of material incorporated into a black hole are still
     preserved.Thus, indirectly, we may detect their presence.

  8. @{b}Medium size black holes@{ub} (?,000 solar masses) - collapsed cores of
     small star clusters (globular ones). May also be created by mergers
     of many stellar black holes.

  9. @{b}Supermassive black holes@{ub} (?,000,000 solar masses) - cores of galaxies.
     SMBH in the center of Milky Way (a.k.a. @{b}Sgr A*@{ub}), has a mass of 2.6±2
     millions of solar masses.Yet, it is still only ~1 AU in diameter...
     Black holes of this type lie in the centers of all galaxies. The size
     of a galaxie's bulge is directly proportional to the mass of it's SMBH.
     (@{b}0.2% of the mass of a bulge is in the central SMBH@{ub}.) Galaxies without
     a bulge do not have SMBH in their centers. If a galaxy rotates faster,
     it's SMBH is more massive. Some SMBH have G solar masses inside them.
     Active SMBH, which consume large quantities of gas are called @{i}blasars@{ui}.
       SMBH in the process of creation are called @{i}@{b}quasars@{ub}@{ui}.
@endnode
///
///   Division by luminosity                              //f
@node ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_LUM "ASense - Stars: Division by luminosity"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@PREV ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_MASS
@NEXT ASENSE-STARS-VARS
@{b}@{u}Division of objects by luminosity@{uu}@{ub} - from dwarfs to hypergiants.

  @{b}VII (white dwarfs)@{ub} - planetary sized stellar remnants containing upto
    1.4 solar masses within them.
      These objects are made of degenerate matter which counter-balances
    the force of gravity by the shear power of the electromagnetic field.
    The electrons are packed together in the most compact way (pushed to 
    lowest orbits) and their mutual repelling blocks further contraction.
      White dwarfs are usually very hot (30..50 kK), and are emitting
    white light.However, since their size is very small, their luminosity
    is also small, only several promiles of the solar luminosity.There is
    no fusion going on, and the radiation comes only from gradual cooling.
    Only the oldest among them have cooled enough to appear slightly reddish.
    None of them has yet became a @{i}@{b}black dwarf@{ub}@{ui} (completely cooled off and
    thus invisible stellar remnant).Trillions of years would be needed for
    this to happen.

  @{b}VI (subdwarfs)@{ub} - hydrogen fusing dwarfs with small metallicity level.
      @{b}These objects are too hot for their luminosity (or too dim for their
    temperature), because @{i}lesser metallicity implies greater transparency@{ui}@{ub}.
    Deeper (and hotter) levels of the star are visible to the observer,
    and hence the star appears to be bluer than expected by its luminosity
    class (or less luminous than its color (and temperature) suggests.
      Metalicity level for these stars is 0.01..0.0001 solar metalicities.
    (Sun has 1.9% of metals by mass (elements other than H and He).)

  @{b}V (dwarfs)@{ub} - regular, core hydrogen-into-helium fusing stars.
      THese are regular @{b}main-sequence stars@{ub} which counter-balance the force
    of gravity by the temperature pressure generated by the fusion process.
    @{i}Hydrogen is being fused into helium in their cores@{ui}.
    - @{i}@{b}Stars with mass < 1.1 Sun masses@{ub}@{ui} have a core temperature > 10 MK, and
    @{i}fuse their hydrogen with a p-p chain reaction@{ui} (proton - proton).
    - @{i}@{b}Stars with mass > 1.1 Sun masses@{ub}@{ui} have a core temperature > 16 MK, and
    @{i}fuse their hydrogen with a more efficient CNO chain reaction@{ui} (carbon -
    nitrogen - oxygen as fusion catalysts).
      @{b}More massive stars have to fuse more hydrogen to counter-balance their
    weight, and hence they use more efficient way to fuse the hydrogen and
    also run out of the H fuel faster, despite the larger initial quantity@{ub}.
      The most massive stars finish their dwarfhood in a few Myr, while the
    smallest red dwarfs would last hundreds of billions of years.The @{"Sun" link ASENSE-PLANETS-SUN} is
    going to be a dwarf for another 5.23 Gyr.

  @{b}Va (bright dwarfs)@{ub} - slightly more luminous than dwarfs, these stars are
    @{i}just about to run out of hydrogen@{ui} fuel for fusion in their cores.
      There is no clear boundary between bright dwarfs and subgiants.

  @{b}IV (subgiants)@{ub} - few times more luminous than dwarfs, these stars have
    ceased their core fusion of hydrogen, and are now @{i}fusing the hydrogen
    in the shell@{ui} around the core.The core slowly contracts, raising the
    temperature in the center.More mass is being continually added by the
    shell fusion as well.
      Since the shell is closer to the surface than the core, the total
    luminosity of these stars increases (there is less material standing
    in a way to block the emission).The radiative pressure pushes away
    the outer layers more efficiently, and stars start to swell.
      Gradual swelling rarifies and cools outer layers of gas, and stars
    are becoming darker, more reddish in appearance.Their spectral types
    slowly shift to redhood.
      Outer layers are counter-balancing their weight with the power of
    the hydrogen fusion, but the core slowly contracts, converting the
    gravitational potential energy into heat and pressure.

  @{b}III (giants)@{ub} - few times more luminous than subgiants, these stars
    have begun to quietly fuse helium in their cores.
      A star which has ascended over the HR diagram into red gianthood,
    descends back when it starts to fuse helium.This is because the fusion
    process now occurs deep in the core, and again there are many layers
    of gas between the core and the surface.Some of the hydrogen fusion
    is still undergoing in the shell around the core, though.Nevertheless,
    a star becomes relatively stable again.
    - @{i}@{b}Stars with a core temperature > 150 MK@{ub}@{ui} are able to @{i}@{b}fuse helium@{ub}@{ui} into
    carbon @{i}@{b}using a triple-alpha chain reaction@{ub}@{ui} (3 alpha particles (helium
    nuclei without electrons) are merged together to form carbon).
      All stars in this phase of their evolution look similar, and they
    clump together in a Hertzshprung-Russel diagram.Therefore, they are
    called '@{b}clump giants@{ub}'.Typical clump giant is a KIII with a luminosity
    of about 50 solar.
      However, there are giants, which are not fusing helium yet, but are
    still preparing itself to do so.They are only giants by their luminosity.
    The Sun is going to increase its luminosity output to more than 2300 of
    current solar luminosities and shine as an M3Ib (@{i}lesser red supergiant@{ui}).
    Only then it would descend back to quietly fuse He as a clump giant for
    another 126 Myr.
      @{i}Radii@{ui} of giant stars are also several times larger than they were
    initially.The Sun is going to engulf its inner planets (Mercury, Venus
    and maybe even the Earth itself) during this stage of its evolution.
      @{b}Whilst the hydrogen fusion may have lasted for billions of years,
    the helium fusing phase lasts only upto 126 Myr@{ub}.This is because fusion
    of @{i}helium doesn't produce as much excess energy as the previous phase
    has been doing, significant portion of that energy is emitted in the
    form of @{b}neutrinos@{ub}@{ui} (which escape effortlessly). @{i}There are less helium
    nuclei available, and the radius which is able to fuse helium is much
    smaller due to higher pressure and temperature being required for the
    process to occur and sustain itself@{ui}.

  @{b}II (bright giants)@{ub} - stars with luminosity 100 - 1,000 solar which have
    ceased their core hydrogen fusion.
      A star of this luminosity class may be in an @{i}ascending phase@{ui} to
    become a @{i}red supergiant@{ui} or in a @{i}descending phase@{ui} to become a @{i}clump
    giant@{ui}.It may also be in a '@{b}second ascend phase@{ub}', which happens when
    the core helium available for fusion runs out too, and the fusion
    of helium continues in the shell as well.There are then two fusing
    shells, one of hydrogen, and the other of helium, and a contracting
    core of carbon and oxygen.@{i}@{b}The helium shell fusion is very unstable,
    and frequently runs uncontrollably@{ub}@{ui}, creating instabillities within
    the star, which therefore becomes a variable again.

  @{b}Ib (lesser supergiants)@{ub} - stars with luminosity 1,000 - 10,000 solar.
      The Sun would be in this phase twice, but only very briefly.Just
    before it ignites the helium, and in the '@{b}asymptotic giant branch@{ub}'
    (AGB) phase.
      The AGB phase happens when a star is not massive enough to allow
    fusion of carbon into heavier elements.Fusion of hydrogen continues
    in the shell, as well as the instable shell fusion of helium, until
    instabilities and pulsations (@{"Mira" link ASENSE-STARS-VARS} type of variability) become so
    large that a star tosses away its outer envelope.The remaining C-O
    core shrinks to become a planetary sized white dwarf, illuminating
    the newly created escaping planetary nebula in the process.This phase
    is very brief, and lasts only ~10 kyr.
      @{b}The mass of a tossed envelope depends heavily on the metalicity
    level of a star@{ub}.The more opaque layers (caused by the higher level
    of metals) are easier to toss away, and therefore a star would lose
    a larger percentage of its mass.@{i}A star of 60 solar masses with 20%
    metals may be reduced to only 4 solar masses by this process, while
    a star with 60 solar masses with 0.02% metals initially would lose
    very little of its mass because of great tranparency of its layers@{ui}.

  @{b}I (supergiants)@{ub} - stars with luminosity 10,000 - 100,000 solar.

  @{b}Ia (bright supergiants)@{ub} - stars with luminosity 100,000 - 810,000 solar.

  @{b}0 (hypergiants)@{ub} - stars with luminosity > 810,000 solar.
      These are the most massive of all stars.They are too luminous to be
    called a mere 'supergiants'.@{b}When they explode, a black hole remains as
    a remnant@{ub}.Despite their enormous luminosity, their mass is not so large.
    They have 30..200 solar masses, depending on their metallicity level.
    (Higher metallicity prevents the creation of larger stars, because the
    opaque gas is blown away from the system before it gets a chance to
    incorporates itself into accreting proto-star.)

    - @{b}Stars with mass > 9 Sun masses may reach a core temperature > 620 MK@{ub},
    which is required to ignite the @{b}carbon fusion@{ub}. These stars are capable
    to fuse the carbon in their cores into heavier elements. This phase is
    even shorter and will last only @{b}for 500..1,000 yr@{ub}.
    - @{b}Stars with a core temperature > 1360 MK are capable of fusing oxygen@{ub}
    in their cores into neon and heavier elements.This phase is very brief
    and lasts for only about @{b}0.5..1 yr@{ub}.

                                     . . .

    - @{b}Stars with a core temperature > 1960 MK are capable of fusing silicon@{ub}
    in their cores into iron and heavier elements.@{i}@{b}This reaction produces
    so many neutrinos and is so short, that it lasts only a single day@{ub}@{ui}.
    There are no more energy producing fusion phases available after that.
@endnode
///
///   Variability types                                   //f
