10               @{b}SNIc@{ub}                                              Collapse of a WR star              No Si lines, same as SNIb, but with He lines (still has an envelope of He)
11               @{b}SNII@{ub}            40..100     -0.1/day              Collapse of a star                 H lines apparent in spectra (envelope mainly of H & He); light curves show greater diversity than those of SNI;
                                                                                                      debris appear in knots; shockwave bubble is fragmented; explosion is freequently off-centered and may accelerate the
                                                                                                      star and its close companion(s) away at high speeds; this is a classic SN; fading is at the rate of 0.1 mag/day
12             @{b}UG@{ub}         U Gem 0.05..0.5              VII+K-MIV-V Occasional fusion of infalling H   Dwarf novae; close binaries, a star filling its Roche lube + VII with accretion disk; small rapid light fluctuations
                                                                                                      and sometimes outbursts; frequently sources of X-rays; at min broad H & He emission lines, at max they almost vanish
                                                                                                      or become shallow absorption lines; longer mean cycle period == greater amplitude; mean cycle periods vary greatly;
13               @{b}UGSS@{ub}    SS Cyg   1..2         2..6                                                   Bursts occur on 10...?000 days cycle; duration of a burst (for all UG? types) is ~= orb.per. of a close binary
14               @{b}UGSU@{ub}    SU UMa   5..10 &      4..8 &  MV                                             2 types of outbursts: normal (short & similar to UGSS) and supermaxima (2 mag brighter, 5 times longer, 3 times less
                                  <0.1       0.2..0.6                                                 frequent); during supermaxima light curves show superposed periodic oscillations (superhumps) (below), per.~=orb.per.
15               @{b}UGZ@{ub}      Z Cam  10..40        2..5                                                   Cyclic outbursts, but, unlike UGSS, sometimes they don't return to original brightness, but retain higher mag.
                                                                                                      (between max & min) during several cycles 
16             @{b}ZAND@{ub}     Zet And                  4     hot+late                                       Irregular; close binaries, hot+late with extended envelope excited by hot star's radiation; inhomogeneous group

 1 @{i}@{b}X-Ray@{ub}@{ui}       @{b}X@{ub}                                       ? + compact Infall of matter                   Close binaries, varying X-ray srcs, not caused by any other var. type; X-ray radiation is reflected from a
                                                                                                      surface of cooler companion, making an area of surface an earlier spectral type (peculiar optical variables)
                                                                                                      compact component is VII, a neutron star or a black hole; matter falls on it directly or from an accretion disk
 2               @{b}XB@{ub}             ?..600sec      0.1                 Bursters                           X-ray & optical bursts
 3               @{b}XF@{ub}              0.0? sec                          Fluctuations                       Fluctuating X-ray & optical (rapidly)
 4               @{b}XI@{ub}             ?min..? h       1      A-M V+comp. Accretion disk                     X-ray irregulars; hot compact object + accretion disk; possible superposition with a per.var. due to orb.motion
 5               @{b}XJ@{ub}    V1343Aql                                    Jets                               Binaries with relativistic jets at X-ray, optical & radio wavelengths;
                                                                                                      emission components showing periodic displacements with relativistic velocities
 6               @{b}XND@{ub}    V616Mon ? months       4..9    VII+G-MIV-V Thermonuclear bursts               Nova-like systems; occasional rapid increase of brightness in V & X-ray range, no envelope ejected
 7               @{b}XNG@{ub}    V725Tau                1..2    VII + I-III Infalls of ejecta (delayed)        Nova-like systems; main component outbursts & ejecta falls on compact with significant delay, causing X-rays
 8               @{b}XP@{ub}             1s-100min       0.?    pulsar+O-AI Reflection + rot. of ellipsoidal I X-rays from pulsar are reflected from surface of I (small effect), superposing on variations caused by the rot.
                                                                                                      of elliptically shaped I; if X-ray beam from pulsar doesn't pass through observer's position, there is no 'P'
                                                                                                      the var. type symbol; if also eclipsing or ellipsoidal var., an 'E' or 'ELL' is added to symbol (E+X, ELL+X)
 9               @{b}XPR@{ub}     HZ Her                2..3    pulsar+B-FV Reflection                         Mean light of system brightest when primary is irradiated by X-rays, faintest during low state of X-ray source
10               @{b}XPRM@{ub}                          4..5    pulsar+K-MV Reflection + accretion on pulsar   ~3 mag from reflection, ~1 mag from accretion; strong magnet. field on pulsar, var.linear and circular polariz.
11             @{b}AM@{ub}        AM Her                4..5    compac+K-MV Reflection + accretion on compact  Strong magnet. field, varying linear and circular polarization (== XPRM, but no pulsar detected)

 1 @{i}@{b}Other@{ub}@{ui}       @{b}BLLAC@{ub}     BL Lac                        blasars     Pole of gal.nuclei pointing to us  Irregular quasistellar object, almost continuous spectra, wk emission & absorption lines, X-rays & radio waves;
                                                                                                      strong varying linear polarization in visible & infrared
 2             @{b}CST@{ub}                                                 Constant                           Non-variable, hastily designated
 3             @{b}GAL@{ub}                                     galaxies                                       Quasistellar objects
 4             @{b}LI@{ub}                                                                                     Slow light changes (unstudied)
 5             @{b}QSO@{ub}                                     quasars     Supermassive black holes formation Quasistellar objects
 6             @{b}S@{ub}:                                                                                     Rapid light changes (unstudied)
 7             @{b}@{ub}*                                                   (unclassified)                     Either short stages of transition from one variability type to another, or earliest/latest evolutionary stages
                                                                                                      of these types, or insufficiently studied members of future new var. types (outside above classification range)

  Note: ZAMS == @{i}zero age main sequence@{ui} (star).

  NOTE: @{i}This table is not a definitive one, and is open to extension or even
  redefinition of some subtypes if new observations shed some more light on
  the subject@{ui}.Only the very obscure subtypes are likely to change, though.

  @{u}Examples for not yet included (and should be there) classses@{uu}:
  - @{b}Normal G stars producing superflares@{ub} (indicating presence of extremely
    close large companion (brown or red dwarf) in a @{i}very@{ui} elliptic orbit).
      At some point the magnetic lines can take no more twisting and they
    unwind, releasing the energy stored within. For a few hours the star
    becomes upto 100,000 times brighter (12.5 mag).These events occur rarely,
    about once per century or less.Such stars and events are also called
    '@{i}@{b}planet sterilizers@{ub}@{ui}'.

  - @{b}Collapse of a neutron star into a black hole@{ub}.
      This event release as much energy as a supernova, but it does that in
    a single beam of gamma rays (@{i}@{b}gamma rays burst@{ub}@{ui}, GRB).Events of this type
    are frequently being detected in other galaxies.
@endnode
///
///   Spectral types                                      //f
@node ASENSE-STARS-SPECTRA "ASense - Stars: Spectral types"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@PREV ASENSE-STARS-VARS
@NEXT ASENSE-STARS-PARTICLES
@{b}@{u}Spectral types@{uu}@{ub}: Description of the stellar spectral types.

    Most of the things that we know about the stars has been acquired by
  studying the spectra of their light.The stars themselves are classified
  upon the features present in their light. Hence, it is very important
  for a user to be familiar with the spectral types of the stars to be
  able to fully understand them.

    Initial, @{b}OBAFGKM@{ub} classification, was invented by @{b}E.C.Pickering@{ub} and
  his assistants in 1890. Every class was additionally divided into 10
  subclasses (M0..M9, K0..K9,...).
    @{"Luminosity classification" link ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_LUM} was added by @{b}W.W.Morgan@{ub}, @{b}P.C.Keenan@{ub} and
  @{b}E.Kellman@{ub} during 1940s, and is now known as @{b}MKK spectra - luminosity
  classification@{ub}.

  @{b}Class  Temp. [kK] Color        Properties@{ub}
    @{b}O@{ub}    31.0..     @{i}bluish@{ui}       Ionized and neutral He, weakened H.
    @{b}B@{ub}    9.75..31.0 @{i}blue-white@{ui}   Stronger H, neutral He.
    @{b}A@{ub}    7.1..9.75  @{i}white@{ui}        Strong H, ionized metals.
    @{b}F@{ub}    5.95..7.1  @{i}yellow-white@{ui} Weaker H, ionized metals.
    @{b}G@{ub}    5.25..5.95 @{i}yellowish@{ui}    Weaker H, neutral metals, strong Ca.
    @{b}K@{ub}    3.8..5.25  @{i}orange@{ui}       Weak H, max CaII, neutral metals.
    @{b}M@{ub}    1.8..3.8   @{i}reddish@{ui}      Little H, neutral metals, moleculs (CO, TiO2).

    @{b}L@{ub}    1.5..1.8   @{i}red-infrared@{ui} No H, metallic hydrides, alkali metals.
    @{b}T@{ub}    1.0..1.5   @{i}infrared@{ui}     Methane (CH4).

    In order to account for very faint objects (brown dwarfs), classes
  L and T were added later. 2/3 of L stars are red dwarfs, while the rest
  are brown dwarfs. There are no red dwarfs between T stars.

  @{u}Special classes (by chemical composition)@{uu}:
    @{b}R@{ub}      ----     @{i}dark red@{ui}     @{b}Carbon@{ub} enhanced, analogous to @{b}G@{ub} and @{b}K@{ub} classes.
    @{b}N@{ub}      ----     @{i}dark red@{ui}     @{b}Carbon@{ub} enhanced, analogous to @{b}M@{ub} class.
    @{b}S@{ub}      ----       ----       '@{i}@{b}Slow process@{ub}@{ui}' elements enhanced (Ba, Zr, Y).

    @{b}Classes R and N were later merged into one, C class@{ub} (carbon stars).These
  stars are usually giants, but may also be dwarfs contamined by companions.
  These stars show enrichments by heavier elements.Carbon stars have entered
  the @{i}asymptotic giant branch@{ui} of stellar evolution (one of the last stages).
  They ceased He fusion in the core, and are now fusing H and He in the shells
  around a dead C-O core. @{b}Carbon compounds absorb blue portion of spectrum,
  which gives these stars a distinctive red color@{ub}.@{i}@{b}Technetium@{ub}@{ui} (Tc) (element
  nr 43, but heavily radioactive, nonexistant on Earth) can be detected in
  the spectra of these stars.This indicates that products of fusion are able
  to reach the surface, driven by convective currents and by instabilities
  in a He fusing shell coupled by its relative proximity to the surface which
  erruptively stir the gases.Carbon and oxygen have to be at least 4..5 times
  enhanced for a star to be a member of this class.
    @{b}C6,3@{ub} (or C6 3) means '@{i}a star of C6 spectral type, with abundance of C of
  about 1,000 solar abundances@{ui}' (log10(1,000) == 3).

    @{b}Slow process@{ub} is fusion by capturing of free neutrons (creation of heavier
  elements).@{b}Rapid process@{ub} occurs in supernovae explosions, where exists the
  abundance of free neutrons.

  @{u}Other special classes@{uu}:
    @{b}W@{ub}    25.0..50.0  @{i}bluish@{ui}      @{i}@{b}Wolf-Rayet@{ub}@{ui} stars, cores of massive stars.
    @{b}D@{ub}    30.0..50.0  @{i}white@{ui}       @{i}@{b}White dwarfs@{ub}@{ui}, planetary sized stellar remnants.

    @{b}W (@{i}Wolf-Rayet@{ui} stars)@{ub} - last evolutionary stages of massive O stars before
      they explode as @{"supernovae" link ASENSE-STARS-VARS 128}.Fierce winds from these stars have blown away
      outer envelopes, exposing the inner layers of the star.@{i}@{b}Depending on star's
      metalicity level, mass of the remaining core varies greatly, from only
      few solar masses@{ub}@{ui} (high metalicity) @{i}@{b}to dozens of them@{ub}@{ui} (low metalicity).
        On average, these stars have about 20 solar masses.

      @{u}Wolf-Rayet stars are further divided into@{uu}:
        @{b}WHe@{ub} - @{i}He rich@{ui} Wolf-Rayet stars.
        @{b}WN@{ub}  - @{i}N dominates@{ui}, some C, some H.
        @{b}WC@{ub}  - C and O dominate, no N, no H, @{i}C/O > 1@{ui}.
        @{b}WO@{ub}  - Ne and O dominate, @{i}C/O < 1@{ui} (rare type),
          @{i}last stage before supernova@{ui}.

    @{b}D (White dwarfs)@{ub} - upto 1.4 solar masses, planetary sized stellar remnants.
      @{i}This spectral type is synonym for @{"VII" link ASENSE-STARS-DIV_BY_LUM} luminosity class@{ui}.

      @{u}White dwarfs are further divided into@{uu}:
        @{b}DA@{ub} - @{i}hydrogen rich@{ui} white dwarfs.
        @{b}DB@{ub} - @{i}helium rich@{ui} white dwarfs.
        @{b}DC@{ub} - @{i}carbon rich@{ui} white dwarfs.
        @{b}DO@{ub} - @{i}oxygen rich@{ui} white dwarfs.
        @{b}DF@{ub} - @{i}calcium rich@{ui} white dwarfs.
        @{b}DZ@{ub} - @{i}metal rich@{ui} white dwarfs.
        @{b}Dp@{ub} - @{i}peculiar, magnetic@{ui} white dwarfs.

  NOTE: @{b}Luminosity classes of stars can be determined from their spectra or
  from U-B and B-V magnitude differences of their light@{ub}.

    Letter '@{b}a@{ub}' sometimes indicates a @{i}@{b}slightly brighter@{ub}@{ui} star than expected for
  its MKK spectral type (M5IIIa).
    Letter '@{b}b@{ub}' sometimes indicates a @{i}@{b}slightly less luminous@{ub}@{ui} star than it can
  be expected for its MKK spectral type (M3Ib).

    @{b}MKK sectral types can be deduced either from the spectra directly, or
  from the U-B and B-V magnitude differences@{ub}, preferably by both methods.

  @{u}Additional spectral features@{uu}:
  @{b}f@{ub} - @{i}@{b}fierce stars@{ub}@{ui}, usually of O spectral type, so hot and luminous that they
      are able to @{i}ionize the surrounding nebula for several light years around@{ui}.
  @{b}n@{ub} - @{i}@{b}nebulous lines@{ub}@{ui}, indicating @{i}rapid rotation@{ui}.
 @{b}nn@{ub} - @{i}@{b}very nebulous lines@{ub}@{ui}, indicating @{i}very rapid rotation@{ui}.
  @{b}e@{ub} - spectra show @{i}@{b}emission lines@{ub}@{ui} (usually of H), indicating that a @{i}star is
      surrounded by a @{b}ring@{ub} of hot gas@{ui}.This is typical for B stars, which eject
      material sometimes due to rapid rotational speed and high luminosity.
 @{b}e(a)@{ub} - @{i}@{b}hydrogen alpha emission@{ub}@{ui} (UV strong), indicating @{i}@{b}ring@{ub}@{ui} of @{i}very hot gas@{ui}.
 @{b}e(av)@{ub} - @{i}variable@{ui} hydrogen alpha emission, indicating @{i}inhomogenities@{ui}.
 @{b}e(b)@{ub} - @{i}@{b}hydrogen beta emission@{ub}@{ui}, indicating @{i}@{b}ring@{ub}@{ui} of @{i}hot gas@{ui}.
 @{b}e(bv)@{ub} - @{i}variable@{ui} hydrogen beta emission, indicating @{i}inhomogenities@{ui}.
 @{b}e(H)@{ub} - @{i}@{b}radio star@{ub}@{ui}, emission from a @{i}cold@{ui} hydrogen envelope, indicating @{i}expanding
      shell of gas@{ui}.
  @{b}q@{ub} - @{i}@{b}quick emission@{ub}@{ui}, star is surrounded by a @{i}@{b}shell@{ub}@{ui} of ejected material.
      Ejection were caused by rapid rotation combined with sudden erruptions.
  @{b}q(v)@{ub} - @{i}variable@{ui} quick emission from a shell, indicating @{i}inhomogenities@{ui}.
 @{b}sh@{ub} - @{i}@{b}shell stars@{ub}@{ui} (B..F V), same as '@{b}q@{ub}' (quick emission) stars.
  @{b}v@{ub} - @{i}variable@{ui} lines, indicating the existance of @{i}unresolved companion@{ui}.
 @{b}wl@{ub} - @{i}@{b}weak lines@{ub}@{ui}, indicating a @{i}metal poor star@{ui} (typical for @{i}subdwarfs@{ui}).
 @{b}wk@{ub} - @{i}@{b}weak lines of a particular element@{ub}@{ui} (CH wk).
  @{b}m@{ub} - @{i}@{b}metallic lines@{ub}@{ui}, indicating that a star has been @{i}polluted by ejected
      envelopes of a dead companion@{ui} (Sirius), @{i}or@{ui} that it has an @{i}unresolved
      companion of low luminosity@{ui} (red dwarf) @{i}in a close orbit@{ui} (Castor).
  @{b}s@{ub} - @{i}@{b}sharp lines@{ub}@{ui}, indicating @{i}slow rotation@{ui}.
  @{b}p@{ub} - star is @{i}@{b}chemically peculiar@{ub}@{ui}, some elements show unusal abundances.
    - @{b}Increase of Mg, Si, Sr, Cr, Eu@{ub} indicates @{i}high magnetism@{ui}.
      (Mg typically enhanced on B8..B9 stars;
       Si typically enhanced on B9..A0 stars, above dwarfhood;
       Eu, Sr, Cr typically enhanced on A0..F0 stars.)
    - @{b}Increase of Hg, Mn@{ub} indicates @{i}slow rotation@{ui}.
    - @{b}He weak@{ub} indicates slow rotation of a hot B star.
    - @{b}Increase of Ba, Zr, Y@{ub} indicates @{i}pollution by a dead companion@{ui}.
    - @{b}Increase of Ba, Zr, Y, Va, La, Ti in a giant star@{ub} indicates @{i}advanced stage
      of stellar evolution@{ui} (enhancement by a @{i}slow process@{ui} of fusion).
    - @{b}Mg weak@{ub} indicates @{i}poor metalicity@{ui} (subdwarf), @{i}or a lam Boo star@{ui}.
    - @{b}Increase of Li@{ub} indicates @{i}presence of a @{b}warm@{ub} brown dwarf@{ui} (1/3 of L stars).
    - @{b}No Li@{ub} indicates a @{i}cannibal star@{ui}, which has eaten another one.Li has been
      destroyed in the process. Such star have a large spin, acquired from the
      eaten one, from which very little remains (red or a brown dwarf perhaps).
    - @{b}CH (G band)@{ub} is typical for @{b}G5..K5 stars@{ub}.@{i}Weak G-band indicates lack of C@{ui}.
    - @{b}C2 (swan band)@{ub} is typical for @{b}G stars@{ub}.@{i}Weak swan bands indicates lack of C@{ui}.
    - @{b}lack of C2, CH, CN, with a lot of O and CO@{ub} indicates that @{i}O is abundant@{ui}
      (all of C has oxidized into CO).
    - @{b}stronger CN@{ub} indicates higher luminosity class.
    - @{b}Presence of Tc@{ub} (radioactive element which doesn't exist on Earth)
      indicates @{i}an advanced stage in stellar evolution@{ui}, usually @{i}a carbon star@{ui}.
      @{i}Peculiarites are logarithmic values@{ui} (of comparisons to solar abundance).
    - @{b}CI means @{i}neutral@{ui} carbon, CII- @{i}single@{ui} ionized, CIV - @{i}triple@{ui} ionized one@{ub}.
  @{b}X(sft)@{ub} - star is a source of @{i}@{b}X-rays@{ub}@{ui}.
  @{b}X(hrd)@{ub} - star is a source of @{i}@{b}gamma@{ub}@{ui} rays.
  @{b}comp@{ub} - @{i}@{b}composite spectra@{ub}@{ui}, indicating @{i}unresolved binary@{ui}.
   @{b}neb@{ub} - @{i}@{b}nebula spectrum mixed with stellar@{ub}@{ui}.
  @{b}single line spectra that oscillates@{ub} - presence of large unresolved planet(s).
      (Jupiter tugs the Sun back and forth with 3 m/s speed).
  @{b}fast spin@{ub} - @{i}@{b}no planets around@{ub}@{ui}, moment of inertia not transferred to them.
      Typical for hot stars (O, B, A types).
  @{b}lam Boo@{ub} - @{i}young star with poor metalicity@{ui} (Mg wk), @{i}but with solar abundances
      of C, N, O, S@{ui}.
  @{b}Herbig Ae/Be@{ub} - @{i}pre-dwarf stars with 2..10 solar masses@{ui}.
  @{b}k@{ub} - @{i}@{b}interstellar lines@{ub}@{ui}, indicating @{i}chemicals in interstellar dust@{ui}.
  @{b}T@{ub} - @{i}@{b}forbidden lines@{ub}@{ui} (CH4), indicating @{i}extremely low densities@{ui}, either @{i}a
      brown dwarf or a T Tau star@{ui} (matter streaming into a new born star).
  @{b}I@{ub} - @{i}@{b}infrared emission@{ub}@{ui}, indication of a @{i}cold dust ring@{ui} (protoplanetary disk).
@endnode
///

///   Elementary particles                                //f
@node ASENSE-STARS-PARTICLES "ASense - Stars: Elementary particles"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@PREV ASENSE-STARS-SPECTRA
@NEXT ASENSE-STARS-CONSTELLATIONS
@{b}@{u}Quarks@{uu}@{ub}: Elementary particles that everything is made of.

    There are 6 types of quarks: '@{b}up@{ub}', '@{b}down@{ub}', '@{b}charm@{ub}', '@{b}strange@{ub}', '@{b}top@{ub}',
  '@{b}bottom@{ub}', and their @{i}anti-quarks@{ui}. The quarks do not exist as separate
  entities, but only go in triplets of 3 '@{i}colors@{ui}' ('@{i}@{b}red@{ub}@{ui}', '@{i}@{b}green@{ub}@{ui}', '@{i}@{b}blue@{ub}@{ui}').
  (These are not @{i}real@{ui} colors, but only fancy names.)
    A triplet must have 1 quark of every color (which merge as '@{i}white@{ui}').

    Under normal conditions, only 'up' and 'down' quarks are stable.The
  other, heavier '@{i}@{b}flavours@{ub}@{ui}' quickly break down into myriads of particles.

    @{b}Baryons@{ub} (@{i}protons@{ui}, @{i}neutrons and other) are made of @{b}quarks@{ub}, which are
  glued together by the @{b}strong nuclear force@{ub} (transmitted by '@{b}gluons@{ub}').
  Baryons have a spin of ±1/2@{ui}.

  @{u}For example@{uu},
  - @{b}proton@{ub} is an @{i}@{b}up-up-down@{ub}@{ui} triplet, and
  - @{b}neutron@{ub} is an @{i}@{b}up-down-down@{ub}@{ui} triplet.
  (From here one may conclude that 'up' quark has a charge of 2/3, and
   that 'down' quark has a charge of -1/3.)

    @{b}Mesons@{ub} @{i}are exotic particles with spins of 0 or ±1 which consist of a
  quark and it's anti-quark@{ui}@{i}@{ui} (which is a colorless combination).They tend
  to annihilate each other very quickly, creating a shower of particles.

    @{b}Hadrons@{ub} @{i}are particles which react on strong nuclear force, either
  baryons, or mesons@{ui}.

@{b}@{u}Leptons@{uu}@{ub}: Small elementary particles that ignore the strong nuclear force,
  and have a spin of ±1/2.

  There are 6 known leptons (and their anti-mater counterparts), each one
  corresponding to one of the quarks. @{i}Anti-electron@{ui} for example is called
  '@{i}positron@{ui}' and has a charge of +1. Leptons @{i}do@{ui} exist as single entities.

     @{u}Lepton@{uu}:               Matching quark:  React on these forces:
  1. @{b}Electron@{ub}            - 'down'           wk nuclear, EM, gravity
  2. @{b}Electron's neutrino@{ub} - 'up'             wk nuclear, gravity (no charge)

  3. @{b}Muon@{ub}                - 'charm'          wk nuclear, EM, gravity
  4. @{b}Muon's neutrino@{ub}     - 'strange'        wk nuclear, gravity (no charge)

  5. @{b}Tau@{ub}                 - 'bottom'         wk nuclear, EM, gravity
  6. @{b}Tau's neutrino@{ub}      - 'top'            wk nuclear, gravity (no charge)

    Pairs 3..6 are unstable, high energy particles.@{i}Masses of @{b}neutrinos@{ub}@{ui}
  are extremely small, but still @{b}30% of the universe is made of them@{ub}.
  They create a ghostly world of their own, and can traverse through
  stars and planets without effort, since they do not react on strong
  nuclear and electromagnetic forces. They are created in large numbers
  during fusion of heavier elements (other than H).

    @{b}Only 5% of everything is normal mater@{ub} (protons, electrons, neutrons).

@{b}@{u}Fermions@{uu}@{ub}: @{i}Particles with spin of half@{ui} (±1/2), @{i}@{b}leptons@{ub}@{ui}, @{i}@{b}quarks@{ub}@{ui} and @{i}@{b}baryons@{ub}@{ui}.
  Pauli exclusion principle @{i}applies@{ui} to them.

@{b}@{u}Spin@{uu}@{ub}:
  - @{b}Normal particles@{ub} (quarks, leptons) @{i}have a spin of ±1/2, which means
    that they would look the same if they are turned *@{b}TWO@{ub}* full circles@{ui}.
      Pauli exclusion principle applies to them.

  - @{b}Force carrying particles@{ub} (photons, bosons, gluons, gravitons) @{i}have
    spins that are whole numbers@{ui} (0,±1,±2).Spin of 0 means that particle
    looks identical from any direction (like a ball). Spin of ±1 means
    that a particle must be turned full circle to appear identical (like
    an arrow). Spin of ±2 means that a particle has to be turned only
    half a circle to appear identical (like a simple line).
      Pauli exclusion principle @{i}@{b}doesn't@{ub}@{ui} apply to them.

@{b}@{u}Particles responsible for exchange of forces between quarks and leptons@{uu}@{ub}:
  1. @{b}Gluons@{ub} (@{i}strong nuclear force carriers@{ui}) - heavy mass, range upto fm
     (femto meter == 10^-15 m).@{b}These keep together the nuclei of atoms@{ub}.
  2. @{b}Photons@{ub} (@{i}EM force carriers@{ui}) - massless, range unlimited.
     @{b}These keep the atoms and moleculs together and transmit the energy
     over great distances@{ub}.
  3. @{b}Bosons@{ub} (@{i}weak nuclear force carriers@{ui}) - heavy mass, small range.
     @{b}These are responsible for ß-decay radioactivity, and also for the
     existance of mater in general, since they prefer it over anti-mater@{ub}.
     @{u}There are 3 types of bosons@{uu}: @{b}W+@{ub}, @{b}W-@{ub}@{b}@{ub} and @{b}Z0@{ub}.
       First 2 are charged (±1), and change @{i}flavour@{ui} of quarks, while the
     third one only changes their @{i}color@{ui}. ('Up' quark may receive a boson
     and become a 'down' quark (most probably), or perhaps a 'charm' or
     'bottom' (less likely, since this requires more energy, which isn't
     usually available).The process is reversible.)
       @{i}Electron@{ui} which emits or receives a boson changes @{i}speed@{ui}, @{i}direction@{ui}
     and becomes an @{i}electron's neutrino@{ui}. The process is reversible.
       @{i}It is interesting to note that bosons are about 80,000 times more
     massive than electron (40 times more massive than protns/neutrons).
     Still, these particles are able to emit and receive them@{ui}. (E=m/c˛).
  4. @{b}Gravitons@{ub} (@{i}gravity force carriers@{ui}) - massless, unlimited range.
     These particles have never been detected, but the theories predict
     their existance. @{b}They are supposed to carry the curvature of space
     around. Gravitons are responsible for clumping the mater together
     to form planets, stars, galaxies, clusters of galaxies@{ub},...
@endnode
///
///   Constellations                                      //f
@node ASENSE-STARS-CONSTELLATIONS "ASense - Stars: Constellations"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@PREV ASENSE-STARS-PARTICLES
@NEXT ASENSE-STARS-GREEK-ALPHABET
@{b}@{u}Constellations@{uu}@{ub}: abbrev., full names, translations.

  @{b}And (Andromeda)@{ub} - Princess of Ethiopia, a.k.a. '@{i}@{b}The Chained Lady@{ub}@{ui}'.
  @{b}Ant (Antlia Pneumatica)@{ub} - Air Pump. Named by @{"Lacaille" link ASENSE-STARS-CONSTELLATIONS 200}.
  @{b}Aps (Apus)@{ub} - Bird of Paradise. Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Aql (Aquila)@{ub} - Eagle. Bird that belonged to Zeus. Aquila's most famous task was
       to carry the mortal Ganymede to the heavens to serve as Zeus' cup bearer.
  @{b}Aqr (Aquarius)@{ub} - Water Bearer. Sun enters Aquarius in early winter when the
       rainy season begins in many parts of the world.
  @{b}Ara (Ara)@{ub} - Altar. Named after the altar of the famous Centaurus, named Chiron.
       Chiron, half horse, half man was thought to be the wisest creature on Earth.
       Ara was also known as the altar that Noah built after the great flood.
  @{b}Ari (Aries)@{ub} - Ram.
  @{b}Aur (Auriga)@{ub} - Charioteer.
  @{b}Boo (Bootes)@{ub} - Bear Driver, Hunter (or Herdsman) that keeps bears together by
       encircling them with his hunting hounds (The Canes Venatici).
  @{b}Cae (Caelum)@{ub} - Sculptor's Chisel. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Cam (Camelopardalis)@{ub} - Giraffe.
  @{b}Cap (Capricornus)@{ub} - Sea Goat. Depicted as a goat with a fish tail, which might
       relate to a story about the god Pan. Pan, fleeing a monster called Typhon,
       jumped into the river Nile. The part of him that was below water turned
       into a fish, while the rest of him which was above water, remained a goat.
  @{b}Car (Carina)@{ub} - The Keel.
  @{b}Cas (Cassiopeia)@{ub} - Queen of Ethiopia and Andromeda's Mother.
  @{b}Cen (Centaurus)@{ub} - Centaur. Represents Chiron.
  @{b}Cep (Cepheus)@{ub} - King of Ethiopia and Andromeda's Father.
  @{b}Cet (Cetus)@{ub} - Sea Monster (a whale).
  @{b}Cha (Chameleon)@{ub} - Chameleon. Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Cir (Circinus)@{ub} - Compass. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}CMa (Canis Major)@{ub} - Greater Dog.
  @{b}CMi (Canis Minor) @{ub}- Lesser Dog.
  @{b}Cnc (Cancer)@{ub} - Crab.
       While fighting Hydra, Hercules also killed the little crab, Cancer.
  @{b}Col (Columba)@{ub} - Dove.
  @{b}Com (Coma Berenices)@{ub} - Berenice's Hair.
  @{b}CrA (Corona Australis)@{ub} - Southern Crown.
  @{b}CrB (Corona Borealis)@{ub} - Northern Crown.
  @{b}Crt (Crater)@{ub} - Cup.
  @{b}Cru (Crux)@{ub} - Southern Cross.
  @{b}Crv (Corvus)@{ub} - Crow.
  @{b}CVn (Canis Venatici)@{ub} - Hunting Dogs. Invented by @{b}Johannes Hevelius@{ub} in 1687.
  @{b}Cyg (Cygnus)@{ub} - Swan or the Northern Cross.
  @{b}Del (Delphinus)@{ub} - Dolphin.
  @{b}Dor (Dorado)@{ub} - Swordfish. Goldfish, more correctly.
       Not named after the pet goldfish, but after @{i}mahi-mahi@{ui}, a Hawaian fish.
       Some old star atlases call this constellation '@{i}@{b}Xiphias@{ub}@{ui}', the Swordfish.
       @{i}Contains part of the Large Magellanic Cloud@{ui}. Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Dra (Draco)@{ub} - Dragon.
  @{b}Equ (Equuleus)@{ub} - Foal.
  @{b}Eri (Eridanus)@{ub} - River.
  @{b}For (Fornax)@{ub} - Laboratory Furnace. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Gem (Geminy)@{ub} - Twins. Greek heroes.
       They were among the men Jason led on his voyages on the Argo.
  @{b}Gru (Grus)@{ub} - Crane. Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Her (Hercules)@{ub} - Hercules.
  @{b}Hor (Horologium Oscillitorium)@{ub} - Clock with a pendulum. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Hya (Hydra)@{ub} - Water Serpent, female.
  @{b}Hyi (Hydrus)@{ub} - Water Serpent, male. Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Ind (Indus)@{ub} - American Indian. Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Lac (Lacerta)@{ub} - Lizard.
  @{b}Leo (Leo)@{ub} - Lion.
  @{b}Lep (Lepus)@{ub} - Hare.
  @{b}Lib (Libra)@{ub} - Beam Balance.
  @{b}LMi (Leo Minor)@{ub} - Lion's Cub.
  @{b}Lup (Lupus)@{ub} - Wolf.
  @{b}Lyn (Lynx)@{ub} - Lynx.
  @{b}Lyr (Lyra)@{ub} - Lyre.
  @{b}Men (Mensa)@{ub} - Table Mountain. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Mic (Microscopium)@{ub} - Microscope. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Mon (Monoceros)@{ub} - Unicorn.
  @{b}Mus (Musca)@{ub} - Fly. Named '@{i}@{b}Apis@{ub}@{ui}' (Bee) by Bayer. Renamed to '@{i}@{b}Musca Apis@{ub}@{ui}'
       (Fly Bee), then to '@{i}@{b}Musca Australis@{ub}@{ui}' (southern fly). Renamed by Lacaille.
  @{b}Nor (Norma)@{ub} - Carpenter's Square. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Oct (Octans)@{ub} - Octant (predecessor to sextant). Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Oph (Ophiuchus)@{ub} - Serpent Holder.
  @{b}Ori (Orion)@{ub} - The Great Hunter.
  @{b}Pav (Pavo)@{ub} - Peacock. Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Phe (Phoenix)@{ub} Phoenix. Named by Bayer. Also called '@{i}@{b}The Griffin@{ub}@{ui}', '@{i}@{b}The Eagle@{ub}@{ui}',
       '@{i}@{b}The Young Ostriches@{ub}@{ui}' (Arabic), and '@{i}@{b}The Fire Bird@{ub}@{ui}' (Chinese).
       Greek word for dark red or purple. The region amd culture of Phoenicia
       were given that name because of their famous Tyrian purple dye made out
       of rotted molluscs, although the Phoenicians were the direct descendents
       of the Canaanites and "kenani" means dark red in Canaanite and may have
       referred to sunburned complexions.
  @{b}Peg (Pegasus)@{ub} - The Winged Horse.
  @{b}Per (Perseus)@{ub} - The Hero.
  @{b}Pic (Pictor)@{ub} - Painter's Easel. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}PsA (Piscis Austrinus)@{ub} - The Southern Fishes.
  @{b}Psc (Pisces)@{ub} - The Fishes.
  @{b}Pup (Puppis)@{ub} - The Stern.
  @{b}Pyx (Pyxis)@{ub} - Compass Box. Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Ret (Reticulum)@{ub} - Crosshairs in a telescope's eyepiece, also referred as '@{i}@{b}Net@{ub}@{ui}'.
       Originally named '@{i}@{b}Rhombus@{ub}@{ui}' by Isaak Habrecht of Strasbourg.
       Renamed by Lacaille.
  @{b}Scl (Sculptor)@{ub} - Sculptor's Workshop.
       Originally called "@{i}@{b}L'Atelier du Sculpteur@{ub}@{ui}". Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}Sco (Scorpius)@{ub} - Scorpion.
       Scorpius is the beast which finally killed the Great Hunter, Orion.
  @{b}Sct (Scutum)@{ub} - Shield.
  @{b}Ser (Serpens)@{ub} - Serpent. Actually split into two distinct, disjoint areas of
       the sky which are divided by the constellation Ophiuchus. They are named
       '@{i}@{b}Serpens Caput@{ub}@{ui}' (head of the serepnt) and '@{i}@{b}Serpens Cauda@{ub}@{ui}' (tail of the
       serpent), or, in jargon terms, @{i}Ser1@{ui} and @{i}Ser2@{ui}.
  @{b}Sex (Sextans)@{ub} - Sextant.
  @{b}Sge (Sagitta)@{ub} - Arrow.
  @{b}Sgr (Sagittarius)@{ub} - Archer. @{i}Contains Galaxy Center@{ui}.
  @{b}Tau (Taurus)@{ub} - Bull.
  @{b}Tel (Telescopium)@{ub} - Telescope. Originally called '@{i}@{b}Tubus Telescopium@{ub}@{ui}' (tube of
       a telescope). Named by Lacaille.
  @{b}TrA (Triangulum Australe)@{ub} - Southern Triangle. It's three brightest stars
       have been called the '@{i}@{b}Three Patriarchs@{ub}@{ui}', Abraham, Isaac and Jacob.
       Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Tri (Triangulum)@{ub} - Triangle.
  @{b}Tuc (Tucana)@{ub} - Toucan. Also called '@{i}@{b}Anser Americanus@{ub}@{ui}' (American Goose.
       @{i}Contains Small Magellanic Cloud@{ui}. Named by Bayer.
  @{b}UMa (Ursa Major@{ub} - Greater Bear. In other cultures it was identified as a
       wagon or cart, a plow, a bull's thigh, and (by Chinese) the government.
  @{b}UMi (Ursa Minor)@{ub} - Lesser Bear. @{i}Contains Little Dipper asterism@{ui}.
  @{b}Vel (Vela)@{ub} - Sail.
  @{b}Vir (Virgo)@{ub} - Maiden.
  @{b}Vol (Volans)@{ub} - Flying Fish, also called '@{i}@{b}Passer@{ub}@{ui}' (Sparrow) by Johannes Kepler.
       Named by Bayer.
  @{b}Vul (Vulpecula)@{ub} - The Fox.

  @{u}Obsolete constellation@{uu}:
  @{b}--- (Argo Navis)@{ub} - Great Ship, sailed by Jason and his Argonauts during the
       search for the Golden Fleece. Now split onto @{i}Puppis@{ui} (Stern), @{i}Vela@{ui} (Sails),
       @{i}Pyxis@{ui} (Compass), @{i}Carina@{ui} (Keel), @{i}Volans@{ui} (Flying Fish) and @{i}Columba@{ui} (Dove).
         Because of the precession, more southern stars were visible to the
       ancient sailors of the Mediterranean than are visible today. Low on their
       horizon, in spring skies, there appeared the apparition of a great ship.
       This ship sailed ever westward skimming along the southern horizon.

  @{b}Abbé Nicolas Louis de Lacaille@{ub} (1713-1762) - an astronomer who had the great
    honor of naming 15 of the 88 constellations in the sky.
      He spent 1750-1754 studying the stars of the southern hemisphere from
    the Cape of Good Hope. In his years there, he was said to have observed
    over 10,000 stars using just his 1/2-inch refractor.
@endnode
///
///   Greek alphabet                                      //f
@node ASENSE-STARS-GREEK-ALPHABET "ASense - Stars: Greek alphabet"
@TOC ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@PREV ASENSE-STARS-CONSTELLATIONS
@NEXT ASENSE-SELECT-STARS
@{b}@{u}Greek Alphabet@{uu}@{ub}:

  alp - alpha    nu  - nu
  bet - beta     xi  - xi
  gam - gamma    omi - omicron
  del - delta    pi  - pi
  eps - epsilon  rho - rho
  zet - zeta     sig - sigma
  eta - eta      tau - tau
  the - theta    ups - upsilon
  iot - iota     phi - phi
  kap - kappa    chi - chi
  lam - lambda   psi - psi
  mu  - mu       ome - omega
@endnode
